[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Introduction"]
[Black "Ruy Lopez Introduction"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ Welcome to this course about the Ruy Lopez!  When I grew up learning chess, a lot of knowledgeable people explained to me that if there is one opening one really ought to know, it would be the Ruy Lopez. Apart from being one of the most commonly played openings, the argument is that it leads to very “classical” play – another word for rich strategic positions with a lot of different ideas and plans for both sides. In short, positions with a lot of “content”, which is such a popular thing nowadays.    Taking on such a historical, rich, and broad subject as the Ruy Lopez, is of course quite a challenge. While this technically speaking isn't a Lifetime Repertoire @@StartBracket@@as it doesn't cover alternatives to 1...e5 and 2...Nc6@@EndBracket@@ it is certainly intended to be something that can be used as a backbone repertoire for a lifetime. Concrete lines and evaluations always change with time, so the only real way of providing something long-lasting is to focus on the general concepts and understanding – those things will rarely change throughout time. In the course, I have tried to focus as much on how to handle the arising middlegame positions as on the specific opening moves. This is an approach I strongly advocate in general, but perhaps even more so in such a strategic opening as the Ruy Lopez.    Having played the Ruy Lopez with both colours most of my life, I believe myself to be well qualified on the subject. I have also been a second of World Champion Magnus Carlsen numerous times. This has helped me greatly understand chess and opening work in general, but also specifically a lot of things in the Ruy Lopez. Opening work has always been one of my main interests, and sharing my knowledge with all of you now is a great pleasure for me.    Repertoire choices   There are basically two groups of systems for Black against the Ruy Lopez: the very solid ones, and the slightly riskier ones. The very solid ones consist mainly of the Berlin and the Marshall. Those are so incredibly solid, that it really doesn't make any sense to try to 'refute' or 'punish' them immediately. Therefore I have adopted systems based on playing d2-d3 rather than pushing the pawn to d4 in one go. This makes for a slightly slower game, where the fight is typically delayed until the middlegame. But don't be fooled into thinking this is a less ambitious approach – in fact, keeping a lot of pieces on the board and the position full of play is arguably more ambitious than trying something concrete where the board might end up emptied quickly. It is an additional benefit that the d3-systems are playable both against the Berlin and against the Marshall, as the knowledge of how to handle the pawn structure can be used for both lines.    Then there are the lines which I consider slightly riskier for Black. Some of them have an excellent reputation, especiallythe Arkhangelsk andthe Open Ruy Lopez, but I do believe the setups I have chosen to recommend are positionally well-founded and will remain mainlines for a very long time. From a theoretical standpoint, it is of course impossible to prove a win @@StartBracket@@or indeed, even an edge@@EndBracket@@ but I believe some of the new ideas will prove quite challenging for Black to handle. In my own practice, I have played the setups for several years already, and been very content with the results.    Finally, there is an alternative repertoire, with playing d2-d3 a move earlier. When playing the Ruy Lopez regularly, and as in my case, having had quite a few games with it, it's always nice to add a little extra flexibility. By being able to play d2-d3 a move earlier, we cut out a huge part of the theory, meaning that it requires a lot less concrete knowledge. The reason we can do this with relative ease is that we are already familiar with the pawn structures arising, as they are largely the same as in our main repertoire. Therefore, despite it being called “alternative” I would recommend viewing it more as an “addition” as it makes a lot of sense to be able to play both!    Other authors   So much material is written and published nowadays that it’s impossible to keep track of everything. I have naturally tried to read and watch as much of the relevant material as possible, and of course have studied the other Chessable repertoires in depth. That there are clashes in opinion is natural, and it is certainly much easier to build upon other people's work. Still, I have tried my best to make use of this unfair advantage, and I am sure future authors will do the same with my work!  Nils Grandelius, June 21st 2021 }
*

