[Black "Arkhangelsk #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5
{ Going for the Arkhangelsk. One of the sharpest and most dynamic ways for Black to meet the Ruy Lopez. }
6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move is the start of the Arkhangelsk variation in the Ruy Lopez. Black's idea is pretty straightforward: all pieces should be developed to the most active positions, and once White occupies the centre Black is ready to attack it with all pieces. The main downsides are that Black will have to lose time by moving the bishop again  (after White pushes c3 and d4)  and, more importantly, that with the bishop stuck on the queenside the Black king will miss an important defender. Therefore our idea here as White is often connected to attacking the Black king. }
7. c3 { Occupying the centre makes a lot of sense against the bishop on c5. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ My preferred move order, as it keeps the option of putting the d-pawn on d3 in case of ...Bg4. }
8... Bb7
{ A topical move, popularized by Vishy Anand and recently employed frequently by Levon Aronian. In comparison to ...Rb8 it develops a piece, but the bishop is often more useful on the c8-h3 diagonal. }
9. d4 Bb6 10. Be3
{ Very rare. In practical play White has most often placed the bishop on g5, but I believe we can play in similar fashion to the other Arkhangelsk lines. }
10... exd4
{ The critical move.   10...O-O  11.Nbd2  is very similar to the ...Rb8-lines. }
11. cxd4 Na5 { Attacking both b3 and e4, forcing us to give up our bishop. }
12. Nbd2 Nxb3
{ Otherwise, we are in time for Bc2, defending e4 and saving the bishop. } 13.
Qxb3 O-O 14. a5
{ Similar to the ...Rb8-lines. We are blocking the queenside in order to start the activity on the kingside. }
14... Ba7 15. Bg5
{ As usual the pin is very annoying for Black. Next up we try to transfer as many pieces as possible to the kingside. Whenever Black plays ...c5, we block with d5. Black does have some potential for counterplay with the bishop pair, but our centre is stable and our long-term attack pretty dangerous. }
