1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5
{ Going for the Arkhangelsk. One of the sharpest and most dynamic ways for Black to meet the Ruy Lopez. }
6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move is the start of the Arkhangelsk variation in the Ruy Lopez. Black's idea is pretty straightforward: all pieces should be developed to the most active positions, and once White occupies the centre Black is ready to attack it with all pieces. The main downsides are that Black will have to lose time by moving the bishop again  (after White pushes c3 and d4)  and, more importantly, that with the bishop stuck on the queenside the Black king will miss an important defender. Therefore our idea here as White is often connected to attacking the Black king. }
7. c3 { Occupying the centre makes a lot of sense against the bishop on c5. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ My preferred move order, as it keeps the option of putting the d-pawn on d3 in case of ...Bg4. }
8... Rb8
{ The traditional mainline. Black keeps the c8-bishop flexible. By stepping away from the a8-square the rook is no longer hanging, meaning that Black after axb5 can safely recapture with the pawn. The downside is that the move Rb8 in itself does not really contribute to the development as much as Bb7 or Bg4 would have done. }
9. d4 Bb6 { 9...Ba7??  10.axb5  axb5  11.d5!  drops a piece. } 10. a5
{ This move has completely taken over as the mainline in the last couple of years. The logic is that with the bishop stuck on b6/a7 Black will lack defenders on the kingside, therefore White is closing the queenside to get free hands to focus on the kingside and centre. }
10... Ba7
{ Note that  10...Nxa5  does not really work. After  11.Rxa5!  Bxa5  12.dxe5  White's attack is simply too strong. }
11. h3
{ Important! Lately, there has been a slight change in favour of the immediate  11.Be3  , but I prefer to cut out any ...Bg4 options whatsoever. }
11... O-O 12. Be3
{ If we are in time to solidify our centre we have a pleasant edge, so it's up to Black to create quick counterplay.   Note that  12...Bb7  loses a piece to  13.d5! }
12... Ra8
{ The Old Main Line, which has gone slightly out of fashion for Black. } 13.
Nbd2 h6 14. Re1
{ Overprotecting e4, which will come under fire by ...Bb7 and ...Re8 later on. }
14... Re8 15. Bc2
{ This is a very rare move. The idea is simply to overprotect the e4-pawn. }
15... Bb7 16. Bb1
{ Very typical for this line. It looks strange, but we are thinking prophylactically against Black's idea of ...exd4 followed by ...Nb4. }
16... exd4 17. cxd4 Nb4 18. Qb3 { Forces Black to push ...c5. } 18... c5 19. d5
{ Closing the centre when Black can no longer break with ...c6. The pawn structure is rather complex, but we do have great potential on the kingside. Either pushing g4-g5, or Nh2-g4 in combination with Qd1-f3 is promising. Additionally, the rook can be brought to the kingside via a3. }
