1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5
{ The so-called Neo-Møller. This line is very similar to the Arkhangelsk, and much of the same reasoning applies. The bishop is more actively placed on c5 and will exercise pressure against our centre, but it will also be missed on the kingside, and black will have to lose some time moving it again once d4 comes. This specific line has been employed numerous times by Magnus Carlsen and deserves to be treated with a lot of respect. }
6. c3 O-O 7. d4 Ba7
{ A provocative way of playing - Black is trying to trick us into being too aggressive. }
8. Re1 { I like this simple stabilizing move. } 8... d6 9. h3
{ Always useful to stop ...Bg4. } 9... Re8 { The trickiest option. } 10. Be3
{ A strong and very thematic pawn sacrifice. } 10... exd4 11. Nxd4 Bxd4 12.
cxd4 Rxe4
{ The only critical move, as otherwise, Black is just significantly worse strategically.   12...Nxe4?!  13.d5  b5  14.Bc2  Na5  15.Bd4± }
13. Nc3 Re7 14. d5
{ Gives excellent compensation for the pawn. Our bishop pair is strong and Black is struggling to bring the queenside into play. }
