[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Open Spanish #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ This move signals the start of the Open Spanish. Black immediately captures a central pawn, and the game takes on a more forcing character. By nature, the Open Spanish is a rather forcing opening, in which Black is immediately trying to fight for the initiative. However, Black's activity also has downsides - pushing a lot of pawns creates weaknesses, and if we manage to push Black back, then we can often end up with a big positional edge. A lot of contemporary and historical top players have used the Open Spanish as Black and it is a very well-respected opening overall. }
6. d4 Be7
{ A rare but rather tricky line. The point is to play ...b5 on the next move, tricking White into a suboptimal version of the Open Spanish. For a long time it was considered highly dubious, but after Mamedyarov used it to beat Aronian in an important game in the 2018 Olympiad it has gotten a lot more popular, even being played by Magnus Carlsen more than once. It is highly provocative, but not bad at all and leads to some very unusual positions.   6...exd4  is too dangerous, as it opens up the e-file prematurely.  7.Re1  d5  8.c4!  already creates very, very difficult problems for Black to solve. }
7. Re1 b5 8. Rxe4 { Very important. If  8.Bb3  d5  we would be tricked. } 8...
d5 { 8...bxa4  9.d5  and Black would get rolled over quickly. } 9. Nxe5
{ This all looks quite messy, but in fact, we are just trading off sets of pieces. }
9... Nxe5 10. Rxe5 bxa4
{ A rather weird position. Black has a horrible pawn structure, but the bishop pair could become strong, meaning we should still be careful here. }
11. Qe2 { Preventing ...O-O. } 11... f6
{ This is the recommendation of Yuriy Krykun in his Chessable course.   11...c6  is another option analyzed in the course. After  12.Nc3  we will pick up the a-pawn. Black gets some compensation, but White is definitely pressing. }
12. Re3 c5 13. dxc5 Kf7 14. Nc3
{ Just developing instead of caring too much about material. } 14... Bxc5 15.
Rd3 { Black is suffering from all the pawn weaknesses. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Open Spanish #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ This move signals the start of the Open Spanish. Black immediately captures a central pawn, and the game takes on a more forcing character. By nature, the Open Spanish is a rather forcing opening, in which Black is immediately trying to fight for the initiative. However, Black's activity also has downsides - pushing a lot of pawns creates weaknesses, and if we manage to push Black back, then we can often end up with a big positional edge. A lot of contemporary and historical top players have used the Open Spanish as Black and it is a very well-respected opening overall. }
6. d4 b5
{ 6...exd4  is too dangerous, as it opens up the e-file prematurely.  7.Re1  d5  8.c4!  Already creates very, very difficult problems for Black to solve. }
7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6
{ Black has a strong knight on e4 and in general an active position. However, if we manage to kick back or trade the e4-knight we are left with a nice spacial advantage due to the advanced e5-pawn. }
9. c3
{ Move orders are very important here! We start with 9.c3 in order to have the c2-square available in case Black goes ...Nc5. }
9... Nc5 10. Bc2 { The point of starting with 9.c3! } 10... Bg4 11. Re1
{ This is a very decent version for White. Next, we can follow up with b4 followed by a4, putting very serious pressure on the b5-pawn while our own e5-pawn is safely protected. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Open Spanish #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ This move signals the start of the Open Spanish. Black immediately captures a central pawn, and the game takes on a more forcing character. By nature, the Open Spanish is a rather forcing opening, in which Black is immediately trying to fight for the initiative. However, Black's activity also has downsides - pushing a lot of pawns creates weaknesses, and if we manage to push Black back, then we can often end up with a big positional edge. A lot of contemporary and historical top players have used the Open Spanish as Black and it is a very well-respected opening overall. }
6. d4 b5
{ 6...exd4  is too dangerous, as it opens up the e-file prematurely.  7.Re1  d5  8.c4!  Already creates very, very difficult problems for Black to solve. }
7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6
{ Black has a strong knight on e4 and in general an active position. However, if we manage to kick back or trade the e4-knight we are left with a nice spacial advantage due to the advanced e5-pawn. }
9. c3
{ Move orders are very important here! We start with 9.c3 in order to have the c2-square available in case Black goes ...Nc5. }
9... Be7 10. Bc2 { Again not allowing Nbd2 ...Nc5. } 10... O-O 11. Nbd2 f5
{ Is the other way for Black to play, safeguarding the e4-knight. The problem for Black is that we will eventually be able to play f3, kicking the knight away. }
12. Nb3 { Is the key reply. The knight goes to d4. } 12... Qd7 13. Nfd4
{ This knight, so that f3 can come later to kick out the e4-knight. } 13...
Nxd4 14. Nxd4 { Intending to snatch the bishop pair on e6. } 14... c5 15. Nxe6
Qxe6 16. f3 { Finally kicking the knight out! } 16... Ng5 17. Bf4
{ A rare move. We are not yet committing our pawn to f4 and keep the option of trading on g5 later on. Next, we intend to play Qe2 or Qd2 followed by centralizing the rooks. Later on, we are likely to take on g5 anyway under better circumstances. Our light-squared bishop will always be slightly better than Black's, and the d5-pawn more vulnerable than the one on e5. }
17... Qc6 18. Bxg5
{ Is actually quite good, as the queen is better on e6 than c6 here. } 18...
Bxg5 19. f4
{ Later on, pushing g4 to open up for the c2-bishop and initiating a kingside attack is one of the key ideas. }
