[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Dilworth Open Spanish"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ This move signals the start of the Open Spanish. Black immediately captures a central pawn, and the game takes on a more forcing character. By nature, the Open Spanish is a rather forcing opening, in which Black is immediately trying to fight for the initiative. However, Black's activity also has downsides - pushing a lot of pawns creates weaknesses, and if we manage to push Black back, then we can often end up with a big positional edge. A lot of contemporary and historical top players have used the Open Spanish as Black and it is a very well-respected opening overall. }
6. d4 b5
{ 6...exd4  is too dangerous, as it opens up the e-file prematurely.  7.Re1  d5  8.c4!  Already creates very, very difficult problems for Black to solve. }
7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5 Be6
{ Black has a strong knight on e4 and in general an active position. However, if we manage to kick back or trade the e4-knight we are left with a nice spacial advantage due to the advanced e5-pawn. }
9. c3
{ Move orders are very important here! We start with 9.c3 in order to have the c2-square available in case Black goes ...Nc5. }
9... Bc5 { The most active move, and traditionally the mainline. } 10. Nbd2
{ Now that ...Nc5 is not possible White can play Nbd2 before Bc2. } 10... O-O
11. Bc2 { As mentioned, a lot revolves around the e4-knight. } 11... Nxf2
{ The best move and the start of the Dilworth Variation of the Open Spanish. Black sacrifices two pieces for a rook and a pawn, but our king is a bit vulnerable and we are behind in development.   11...Nxd2  12.Qxd2  is just great - we have kingside potential and the d5-pawn is weak. }
12. Rxf2 f6
{ The most common move. Black is opening up the f-file to get counterplay as quickly as possible before we have time to get our king back to safety and develop our queenside.  12...Bxf2+  13.Kxf2  f6  14.Nf1  transposes to the mainline. }
13. Nf1
{ A key move. We should not capture on f6, as it would speed up Black's counterplay. Instead, we are give up a second pawn in order to develop comfortably. Next, we threaten to break the pin with Be3 so Black has to take our rook immediately. }
13... Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 fxe5 15. Kg1
{ Stepping out of the pin. The position is strategically very interesting. Black has a rook and two pawns for the two pieces, but if we manage to block the pawns well the pieces will be clearly superior. Next, we are trying to develop with Be3, followed by for instance Qe2/e1 and Rd1/e1. The onus is on Black to create something fast, but to me, it looks much easier to play for White. We go deeper in thecorresponding chapter. }
*

