[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Martinez Variation 6.d3 b5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ The mainline.   Black can also delay ...Be7 in favor of  5...b5  6.Bb3  d6  attempting to move order us into  7.d3  , when Black can hunt down our bishop with ...Na5.  But we play  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.c3  instead, and after  7...Be7  we can transpose back into out repertoire with  8.d3  . }
6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 O-O
{ We always need to be careful when Black delays ...d6, as the d-pawn might go to d5 in one move! Usually, it means that we should delay c3, to keep the option of Nc3 instead. }
8. a4
{ Highlighting the drawback of delaying ...d6 - Black does not have ...Bd7 as a possible reply here.  8.c3  d5!  would be fine for Black. }
8... b4 9. a5 Bc5
{ This is an interesting idea with Nbd2 played instead of a5 for White. Black loses a tempo but puts the bishop much more actively outside the pawn chain before playing ...d6. However, not having played Nbd2 gives us extra options. }
10. Be3
{ An excellent response and normally not possible due to the knight being on d2 already. }
10... Bxe3 11. fxe3
{ This structure is very nice for us. The b3-bishop is strong and the open f-file very useful. We will get an easy-flowing initiative. }
