1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ The mainline.   Black can also delay ...Be7 in favor of  5...b5  6.Bb3  d6  attempting to move order us into  7.d3  , when Black can hunt down our bishop with ...Na5.  But we play  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.c3  instead, and after  7...Be7  we can transpose back into out repertoire with  8.d3  . }
6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
{ A tricky move order that has gained in popularity recently. We keep the option of playing either with or without a4, depending on Black's next move. }
8... Na5 { After this, we switch to central play with d4 instead of a4. } 9.
Bc2 c5 10. d4
{ This looks a bit strange, as we have lost a tempo by going d3 before d4. However, Black has already committed to the setup with ...Na5 and ...c5, which has gone out of fashion completely. In the closed structures that often arise, the tempi are not so relevant and we should still be enjoying a nice edge. }
10... Qc7 11. d5
{ Leads to a real Chigorin. We have a slight space advantage and will try to create threats on the kingside in the long run. }
11... O-O 12. b3
{ An important move, getting ready to always meet ...c4 with b4!. } 12... Bd7
13. h3
{ Necessary, in order to play Be3 without ...Ng4. Additionally, h3 is part of our long-term plan, both by preparing g4 but also Nh2 with the idea of f4. }
13... g6 14. Be3
{ We want to develop with Nbd2, Re1 and then choose which side to play on. As soon as the knight leaves a5 we play a4 to put pressure on b5, and if the knight stays on a5 for a long time, then we start kingside play, either by pushing g4 or the slower Re1, Nbd2-f1-g3 followed by eventually maneuvering Nh2-g4. }
