6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
{ A tricky move order that has gained in popularity recently. We keep the option of playing either with or without a4, depending on Black's next move. }
8... O-O 9. a4
{ Forcing Black's bishop to choose side, and giving our own bishop a square on a2 in case Black plays ...Na5.  The move ...b5 has also created a hook for us to try to attack, and we are well placed to fight for the light squares on the queenside. }
9... Bd7 10. Bc2
{ This looks strange and requires an explanation. Black's main problem in these positions is the misplaced knight on c6. With the pawn already on c5, Black would be absolutely fine. Therefore the most common plan for Black is to play ...Na5, hitting the b3-bishop, and follow up with ...c5 once it retreats. Therefore we prophylactically retreat it already now, to be able to meet  10...Na5  with  11.b4! }
10... Re8 11. Re1
{ Our plan is to push d4 at an appropriate moment, but first we need to develop all our pieces. }
11... h6 { Black prepares ...Bf8 by preventing Bg5 first. } 12. Nbd2 Bf8 13. h3
{ Keeping the knight on d2 for a while longer is especially useful in case Black tries to break in the centre with ...d5. }
13... d5
{ We respond to  13...b4  with  14.Nc4  .  ...b4 can be played almost at any moment, but it does give up the c4-square and leaves us with a very pleasant position. We are still long-term intending to push d4, but we have a lot of small improving moves available to start with. Bd2, a5, Ba4, and so on will increase the pressure bit by bit. }
14. d4 { Is very promising for White. } 14... exd4 15. e5 dxc3 16. bxc3
{ We have excellent compensation for the pawn, as the f6-knight will have to move to a really clumsy square. }
