[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Martinez Variation 6.d3 d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ The mainline.   Black can also delay ...Be7 in favor of  5...b5  6.Bb3  d6  attempting to move order us into  7.d3  , when Black can hunt down our bishop with ...Na5.  But we play  @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/2p2ppp/p1np1n2/1p2p3/4P3/1B3N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.c3  instead, and after  7...Be7  we can transpose back into out repertoire with  8.d3  . }
6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... d6
{ The big alternative to  6...b5  . The advantage of delaying ...b5 is that we can't attack the b5-pawn, and the disadvantage is that after a later ...b5 we are able to retreat our bishop to c2 in one go. Generally speaking, 6...d6 is considered slightly less solid than 6...b5 for Black, but on the other hand also gives slightly more winning chances. The play often becomes quite similar to the Breyer or the Zaitsev variations of the normal Ruy Lopez. While 6...b5 is relatively straightforward with move orders and ideas, the lines after 6...d6 are a bit messier and we have to be quite observant not to get tricked. }
7. c3
{ Now we are able to retreat the bishop to c2 in one move in case Black ever plays ...b5. }
7... O-O 8. Re1
{ A flexible move order, keeping the option of Be3 before Nbd2. } 8... b5 9.
Bc2 d5
{ When the 6.d3 line started to appear on top level some years back, this was one of the most popular responses. Black immediately challenges the centre. However, practice has shown that this far from solves all the problems. }
10. Nbd2 dxe4
{ The solid option. Black aims for a symmetrical structure.   10...d4  is a very aggressive move, favoured by Levon Aronian. We respond  11.h3!  stopping ...Bg4, preparing to take on d4 at the appropriate moment.  11...Nd7  is how everybody reacts. But the knight is needed on the queenside.  12.a4!  initiating some play on the queenside. Black will either have to give up the a-file, or advance the pawn to b4 thereby giving us the c4-square. }
11. dxe4
{ This might look harmless, but in fact we are pleasantly better. The b5-pawn is a weakness, and we have an easier time bringing our pieces over to the kingside. The knight maneuver to f5 is particularly unpleasant for Black to face. }
11... Be6 12. h3 h6 13. Qe2
{ This is a typical move. We intend a4, to pressurize the b5-pawn, but also preparing Nf1-g3 without having to trade queens. }
