1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ 3...a6  4.Ba4  g6  5.c3  Nge7  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  5.c3  g6  , are alternative move orders simply transposing into the same line. }
4. c3 a6 5. Ba4 Nge7
{ This delays ...Bg7 for a while, creating slightly different positions. } 6.
d4 exd4 7. cxd4 b5 8. Bc2
{ We always retreat the bishop in one go to c2 once given the chance. } 8... d5
9. e5
{ Is the key move here. Our e5-pawn is strong rather than weak, and helps to highlight the weak dark squares in blacks position. }
