1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ 3...a6  4.Ba4  g6  5.c3  Nge7  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  5.c3  g6  , are alternative move orders simply transposing into the same line. }
4. c3 Bg7 { The most popluar move order. } 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 a6
{ Necessary for Black to play sooner or later. Of course it could also have been played on move 3 or 4 to reach the same position. }
7. Ba4 b5 8. Bc2 { As usual the bishop goes immediately to c2. } 8... d5
{ This is another critical position one does well to remember. } 9. Bg5
{ Very important.  9.e5  would not be so strong before Nge7, as Black can play  9...f6!  and recapture on f6 with the knight. }
9... Nge7 10. Nc3 h6 { The only reasonable way of saving the d5-pawn. } 11.
Bxe7 Nxe7 12. e5
{ We have given up the bishop pair, but won a bit of time and our centre is very secure, giving us a pleasant position. }
*

