[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6
{ 3...a6  4.Ba4  g6  5.c3  Nge7  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  5.c3  g6  , are alternative move orders simply transposing into the same line. }
4. c3 Bg7 { The most popluar move order. } 5. d4 exd4 6. cxd4 a6
{ Necessary for Black to play sooner or later. Of course it could also have been played on move 3 or 4 to reach the same position. }
7. Ba4 b5 8. Bc2 { As usual the bishop goes immediately to c2. } 8... d6 9. d5
{ Immediately asking the knight where it is headed. } 9... Na5
{ The best square for the knight, as it keeps the g7-a1 diagonal open. } 10.
O-O Ne7 11. Nc3 { Simply developing. } 11... O-O 12. Re1
{ A typical position for the g6-setups. Black does have a strong bishop on g7, but we have a space advantage and potential for a kingside attack. Most likely Black will play ...c6 some time in the future, which we will take and then try to play against the d6-pawn. }
