[Black "Berlin Sidelines #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 d6
{ A solid line that has gone out of fashion. We should be happy to see it, as the best Black can hope for is generally to transpose to the 6.d3 Ruy Lopez. }
5. O-O a6
{ The independent try, immediately catching our bishop.   If  5...Be7  6.c3  O-O  7.Re1  Black's best move is  7...a6  , transposing to the 6.d3 d6 chapter.   5...Bd7  6.Re1  g6  is another line that used to be popular some ~15 years ago, but we can simply continue with our usual moves and achieve a nice edge:  7.c3  Bg7  8.h3  O-O  9.a4!?  is an interesting way to handle the situation - we grab space on the queenside and keep our pawn on d3 for a long while. }
6. Bxc6+
{ Unfortunately necessary, as  6.Ba4  b5  7.Bb3  Na5  would give up the bishop pair. }
6... bxc6 7. Re1
{ Intending to push in the centre, making use of our lead in development. }
7... Be7
{ In case of  7...Bg4  ,  8.Nbd2  is the typical way against an early ...Bg4. We intend h3 Bh5 and then Nf1-g3, after which Black will have to give up the bishop. }
8. d4 Nd7
{ Trying to keep the stronghold on e5.   8...exd4  9.Nxd4  Bd7  10.c4!  leads to an interesting strategic position. Black has a solid compact position with the bishop pair, but we have a space advantage and very free piece play. Next, we develop with Nc3, h3, Bf4 and centralize all our heavy pieces. }
9. Na3 { An excellent route for the knight. } 9... O-O 10. Nc4
{ No matter how Black reacts, a serious concession will soon have to be made after we play Na5. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Berlin Sidelines #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O Re8
{ An interesting move. Black is keeping the d-pawn on d7, hinting at the possibility of going ...d5 later on. }
7. Bg5
{ Intended to stop ...d5. Usually, we are a bit hesitant to place our bishop on g5 this early, but it makes some additional sense after ...Re8.   If Black pushes  7...h6  8.Bh4  g5  ,  then the rook would be better placed on f8 to support a later ...f5-break. Thinking even further ahead, if after  9.Bg3  Black  goes Nh5-Nxg3 hunting down our bishop, then after fxg3, the f7-pawn is weaker! This sounds a bit far-fetched, but it is surprisingly relevant for the evaluation of the move ...Re8.   7.Re1  would not be as good here, due to  7...a6  8.Ba4  d5!  gaining counterplay in the centre. }
7... a6 8. Ba4 Be7 { Is always a solid option against Bg5. } 9. Nbd2 d6 10. h3
h6 11. Bh4 Nh5 12. Bg3
{ This is the idea. When Black takes on g3, we open up the f-file and get pressure along the f-file. All our other pieces are working well, whereas Black looks a bit passive overall. }
*

