[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3
{ In recent top level practice this has gone a bit out of fashion, but in relation to the the rest of our repertoire it makes a lot of sense. The idea is similar to many of our other lines - we intend to push d4 at an appropriate moment. Black has a very important choice to make now: either develop calmly with O-O, d6 and so on, or go for the immediate ...d5-push. Whereas the slower play leads to positions with a lot of fight for both colours, the d5-lines are generally more forcing in nature and Black is really trying to equalize by very concrete means. 5.c3 is necessary immediately, as if we start with  5.O-O  Black has the very annoying  5...Nd4  which trades off the bad c6-knight and equalizes comfortably. }
5... O-O 6. O-O d5
{ Another move order for this, which plays out slightly differently. } 7. exd5
Qxd5 8. Bc4 Qd8
{ 8...Qd6?!  This is worse here, as Black does not want to have castled so early.  9.b4  Bb6  10.Ba3!  is the punishment. After a later b5, both Qd6 and the rook on f8 will be hanging. }
9. Nbd2
{ Settling for normal development. Now we intend to grab space on the queenside and put pressure along the e-file. Later on, Qe2 and Ne4 could be played to increase pressure. In the long-term, a potential idea could be to push h3 and g4, creating tension against Black's king.  9.Bg5  e4!  10.Bxf6  Qxf6  11.dxe4  Bg4  gives Black excellent counterplay. }
9... a5
{ 9...h6  is popular but a little slow. We just gain some space with  10.b4!   After  9...a6  , intending ...b5 and trying to win the d3-pawn,  10.a4  leads to typical kind of play. }
10. h3 { Taking the g4-square under control. } 10... h6 11. Re1 Qd6 12. Qe2
{ Building slowly. We are not so much threatening to take on e5 as just activating our position overall. }
12... Bf5 13. Nf1
{ is a typical maneuver, intending Ng3, perhaps followed by Nh4-f5. Black has a healthy position, but the light squares are slightly soft, especially the one on f5. It will take a lot of patience, but our maneuvering is slightly easier than Black's. }
