1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6
{ The most common move. Black treats the position similar to an Italian. Now there are a lot of different move orders and possible plans for both sides. }
7. Re1
{ This is my recommendation. I do not want to waste time on h3 if it isn't necessary, and also not yet commit to Nbd2. }
7... a6
{ A common move against @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  and  7.Nbd2  . }
8. Bxc6 bxc6 9. Bg5
{ This is the idea. Here Re1 is much more useful than h3, as our idea is to push d4 for which the e4-pawn needs to be defended. }
9... h6 10. Bh4 g5 { Necessary sooner or later. } 11. Bg3 Bg4
{ The most natural move. } 12. Nbd2 Bb6 { Typical prophylaxis against d4. } 13.
Nc4
{ Intending to push d4 next, which can't really be stopped in a good way. Black does have the bishop pair, but the kingside is soft and there are also weaknesses on the queenside. I believe the position to be quite unpleasant to play as Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
