[White "Quickstarter Guide"]
[Black "Berlin 6...d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6
{ The most common move. Black treats the position similar to an Italian. Now there are a lot of different move orders and possible plans for both sides. }
7. Re1
{ This is my recommendation. I do not want to waste time on h3 if it isn't necessary, and also not yet commit to Nbd2. }
7... Bb6
{ This is a very cunning try for Black. Normally ...Bb6 unprovoked is not so good due to Nbd2-c4xb6, but here Black still has the option of ...Ng4, meaning things are not as simple for us. }
8. a4 { Threatening to trap the bishop with Bxc6 followed by a5! } 8... a6 9.
Bxc6 bxc6 10. a5 Ba7 11. h3
{ Our idea is that the a7-bishop is out of play, especially if Black follows up with ...c5 later on, which often happens. Next up, we simply develop our pieces calmly with Nbd2-f1-g3 and Be3 or Bd2. It is quite hard for Black to push ...d5 in a good way, and there does not really exist other good plans. If Black isn't careful after Ng3, we might also include the Bg5-pin, which is always a bit unpleasant for Black with the bishop so far away on a7. }
*

