1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6
{ The most common move. Black treats the position similar to an Italian. Now there are a lot of different move orders and possible plans for both sides. }
7. Re1
{ This is my recommendation. I do not want to waste time on h3 if it isn't necessary, and also not yet commit to Nbd2. }
7... Ng4
{ A move we must always consider seriously when playing Re1 without h3. Black puts pressure on the f2-pawn while also making room for an...f5 advance. }
8. Re2 f5
{ This is the idea of playing ...Ng4. It's very double-edged, but we have to be careful here as Black's counterplay can come very quickly. }
9. exf5 Bxf5 10. d4 { A good move, making f2 less vulnerable. } 10... Bb6 11.
Bg5 { Developing with tempo, but also getting another defender to our king. }
11... Qe8 12. h3 Qh5 13. Nbd2
{ Overprotecting f3, thereby threatening to take on g4. Now Black's attack will be pushed back and we will take over the initiative. }
*

