1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6
{ The most common move. Black treats the position similar to an Italian. Now there are a lot of different move orders and possible plans for both sides. }
7. Re1
{ This is my recommendation. I do not want to waste time on h3 if it isn't necessary, and also not yet commit to Nbd2. }
7... h6
{ A slow-looking move, but Black's idea is to play ...a6 without being faced by the Bxc6 followed by Bg5-option. }
8. h3
{ After 7...h6 Black is no longer as fast with the plan of ...Ne7 followed by c6 and d5, therefore we can allow ourselves to play h3. }
8... a6 9. Ba4
{ Now that we don't have Bg5 as a follow-up we don't want to trade on c6. }
9... b5 { The most common move, grabbing some space. } 10. Bc2
{ The position is quite similar to 6.d3 b5 Ruy Lopez. We intend to play a4, putting some pressure on the b5-pawn, hoping it will have to move to b4. }
10... d5
{ Always an important question to ask oneself when retreating with the bishop to c2 rather than b3.   To  10...Re8  we will respond with  11.a4!  , creating some pressure on the queenside. Black will either have to give up the c4-square by playing ...b4, or the a-file by playing ...Rb8. In both cases our play flows very naturally in the usual way. }
11. d4 { Here however this works out very well for us. } 11... dxe4 12. Nxe5
Nxe5 13. dxe5 { Wins a pawn. } *

