1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6
{ The most common move. Black treats the position similar to an Italian. Now there are a lot of different move orders and possible plans for both sides. }
7. Re1
{ This is my recommendation. I do not want to waste time on h3 if it isn't necessary, and also not yet commit to Nbd2. }
7... Ne7
{ A typical regrouping, also popular against @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.h3  and  7.Nbd2  . }
8. d4 Bb6 9. a4
{ Generally speaking a good move to include in these positions. If Black plays ...a5, then including a4 a5 benefits White for various reasons. The b6-bishop is more vulnerable, and the rook can get into play via a3 later on. }
9... c6 10. Bf1
{ It's usually a tricky question if the bishop is better on d3 or f1, but here I like to tuck it away safely on f1. }
10... Ng6 11. Nbd2 Re8 12. h3
{ Necessary sooner or later, as ...Bg4 will be an annoying option eventually. If Black does nothing special now we can continue with moves like Qc2 and b4. }
12... d5 { The critical try, trying to liquidate everything in the centre. }
13. dxe5 Nxe5 14. exd5 Nxf3+
{ Forced, as the knight would otherwise be hanging. } 15. Nxf3 Rxe1 16. Qxe1
Qxd5 17. c4
{ We have a slight initiative no matter if Black keeps the queens or trade them with ...Qe4. Our main idea is to go a5, fixing the b7-pawn as a weakness. Together with a slight lead in development it definitely makes our position the more pleasant one, although the limited material of course makes Black's position quite solid. }
