[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "1. Arkhangelsk with ...Rb8 Old Main Line"]
[Black "9...Ba7?"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move is the start of the Arkhangelsk variation in the Ruy Lopez. Black's idea is pretty straightforward: all pieces should be developed to the most active positions, and once White occupies the centre Black is ready to attack it with all pieces. The main downsides are that Black will have to lose time by moving the bishop again @@StartBracket@@after White pushes c3 and d4@@EndBracket@@ and, more importantly, that with the bishop stuck on the queenside the Black king will miss an important defender. Therefore our idea here as White is often connected to attacking the Black king. }
7. c3
{ The most logical move, preparing to occupy the centre with d4 later on. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ A very important move. A key part of our plan here is to attack on the kingside, but first we are trying to disturb Black on the queenside. The move a4 is especially important as it forces Black to make a very tough choice of how to stop the threat of axb5 next. }
8... Rb8
{ The absolute mainline. By stepping away from the a8-square the rook is no longer hanging, meaning that Black after axb5 can safely recapture with the pawn. The downside is that the move Rb8 in itself does not really contribute to the development as much as Bb7 or Bg4 would have done. }
9. d4 Ba7
{ Seeing our next move it makes a lot of sense to ask why the bishop can't retreat all the way to a7 immediately. The reason is that Ba7 is only played after White closes the queenside. Playing it before White has played e5 would be a big mistake. }
10. axb5 axb5 11. d5
{ White is winning a piece. as the knight on c6 can't protect the bishop on a7 anymore. }
*

