[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move is the start of the Arkhangelsk variation in the Ruy Lopez. Black's idea is pretty straightforward: all pieces should be developed to the most active positions, and once White occupies the centre Black is ready to attack it with all pieces. The main downsides are that Black will have to lose time by moving the bishop again @@StartBracket@@after White pushes c3 and d4@@EndBracket@@ and, more importantly, that with the bishop stuck on the queenside the Black king will miss an important defender. Therefore our idea here as White is often connected to attacking the Black king. }
7. c3
{ The most logical move, preparing to occupy the centre with d4 later on. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ A very important move. A key part of our plan here is to attack on the kingside, but first we are trying to disturb Black on the queenside. The move a4 is especially important as it forces Black to make a very tough choice of how to stop the threat of axb5 next. }
8... Rb8
{ The absolute mainline. By stepping away from the a8-square the rook is no longer hanging, meaning that Black after axb5 can safely recapture with the pawn. The downside is that the move Rb8 in itself does not really contribute to the development as much as Bb7 or Bg4 would have done. }
9. d4 Bb6 10. a5
{ At first glance a very surprising move. On the last move we were trying to attack Black on the queenside, and now we are instead closing the queenside down. If we look at it on a move-by-move basis it does indeed seem illogical, but what matters here is our overarching strategy of attacking on the kingside. By playing 10.a5 we are achieving two very important things:    We are forcing Black's bishop even further away from the kingside.    Closing the queenside means that Black will find it much harder to generate counterplay on that side, giving us an easier time to focus only on our centre and kingside play. }
10... Ba7 { The only playable move! } 11. h3
{ An important move to remember. Black would like to increase pressure on our central d4-pawn by playing the move ...Bg4, so we take our time to stop it. An additional benefit is that we will be able to place our bishop on e3 without being disturbed by ...Ng4. }
11... O-O 12. Be3 Nxe4
{ It is also possible to play Nxe4 immediately, without trading on d4 first. }
13. Bd5 { Here we have to play as Qc2 would not attack the c6-knight. } 13...
exd4 { The only move for Black not to lose a piece. } 14. Bxe4
{ Important!  14.cxd4  Qe8  15.Re1  Nf6  16.Bg5  Nxd5!  17.Rxe8  Rxe8  is also better for White, but quite a bit trickier to play in practice as Black has very good control of the light squares as compensation for the queen. }
14... d5 15. Bxh7+
{ As both our bishops are hanging, this desperado is our strongest choice. }
15... Kxh7 16. cxd4
{ Material equality is restored and Black has the bishop pair, but the key factor here is the bishop on a7 being completely out of play, making our position very promising. Next up we can play Rc1 and put pressure on the c-file. Later on, initiating some kingside action makes sense, as it will emphasize how far off the a7-bishop is. }
