{ At first glance a very surprising move. On the last move we were trying to attack Black on the queenside, and now we are instead closing the queenside down. If we look at it on a move-by-move basis it does indeed seem illogical, but what matters here is our overarching strategy of attacking on the kingside. By playing 10.a5 we are achieving two very important things:    We are forcing Black's bishop even further away from the kingside.    Closing the queenside means that Black will find it much harder to generate counterplay on that side, giving us an easier time to focus only on our centre and kingside play. }
10... Ba7 { The only playable move! } 11. h3
{ An important move to remember. Black would like to increase pressure on our central d4-pawn by playing the move ...Bg4, so we take our time to stop it. An additional benefit is that we will be able to place our bishop on e3 without being disturbed by ...Ng4. }
11... O-O 12. Be3 Re8
{ Caruana's choice against Grischuk in the 2020 Candidates, therefore, the absolute mainline. Also Sethuraman's recommendation in his Lifetime Repertoire on the Arkhangelsk. By delaying ...Ra8 Black intends to gain some time and get an improved version of the 12...Ra8 lines. }
13. Ng5
{ This is a very advanced move. Normally the move Ng5 in similar positions is just an invitation for a repetition, but here we have a very concrete reason for doing it.  13.Re1  exd4  14.cxd4  was Grischuk-Caruana, but here Black's move order allows them to play  14...Nxe4!  which equalized in the game. }
13... Rf8 14. Re1 Ra8
{ The best move for Black, but now we have achieved our goal with the Ng5-operation - Black had to spend a move on ...Ra8. }
15. Nf3
{ Mission accomplished. Having provoked ...Ra8 we happily retreat to f3 and start to build up our position in a normal way. }
15... Bb7 { 15...Re8  16.Nbd2  Bb7  would just transpose. } 16. Nbd2 Re8
{ This is a tabyia for the 12...Re8 line. White has tried many different moves, but I would like to suggest a very direct way of starting the attack here. }
17. g4
{ A very similar move was played once by Caruana against Carlsen, but in this position I think the circumstances are better. Yes, we do weaken our own king, but with so many pieces on the kingside it's difficult for Black to punish us. Instead, the g-pawn will be a very valuable asset in our own attack. As it's a new position it's difficult to predict how the game might develop from here, but I have given a few possibilities that in my opinion are logical replies. }
17... exd4
{ Probably the best reply. Black releases the pressure on e5 so that they can transfer the c6-knight to the kingside. }
18. cxd4 Ne7
{ The best try, just getting as many defenders as possible over to the kingside. }
19. Bg5
{ Threatening to settle Black with a very sad doubled pawn.  19.Ng5  would be another very interesting option. }
19... Nd7 20. Nf1
{ White is bringing another piece over to the kingside. As Black had to step away from the centre we are now in full control, and can bring more pieces over toward the Black kingside. The one thing going for Black is that they lack pawn weaknesses around the king, making it more difficult for us to break through. On the other hand, our initiative is of a long-term nature, and just adding more pieces toward the Black kingside should be very promising. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Arkhangelsk with ...Rb8 Black's Modern Tries"]
[Black "11...Bb7 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5
{ Going for the Arkhangelsk. One of the sharpest and most dynamic ways for Black to meet the Ruy Lopez. }
6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move is the start of the Arkhangelsk variation in the Ruy Lopez. Black's idea is pretty straightforward: all pieces should be developed to the most active positions, and once White occupies the centre Black is ready to attack it with all pieces. The main downsides are that Black will have to lose time by moving the bishop again  (after White pushes c3 and d4)  and, more importantly, that with the bishop stuck on the queenside the Black king will miss an important defender. Therefore our idea here as White is often connected to attacking the Black king. }
7. c3 { Occupying the centre makes a lot of sense against the bishop on c5. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ My preferred move order, as it keeps the option of putting the d-pawn on d3 in case of ...Bg4. }
8... Rb8 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5
{ At first glance a very surprising move. On the last move we were trying to attack Black on the queenside, and now we are instead closing the queenside down. If we look at it on a move-by-move basis it does indeed seem illogical, but what matters here is our overarching strategy of attacking on the kingside. By playing 10.a5 we are achieving two very important things:    We are forcing Black's bishop even further away from the kingside.    Closing the queenside means that Black will find it much harder to generate counterplay on that side, giving us an easier time to focus only on our centre and kingside play. }
10... Ba7 11. h3 Bb7
{ This is another interesting and topical way for Black to play. Black delays ...0-0 in order to threaten the pawn on e4 one move earlier. }
12. Be3
{ 12.Re1  would commit the rook to  e1  earlier than what we generally desire here, meaning we would be tricked after  12...O-O  . Therefore we have to start with 12.Be3 and let Black execute their idea. }
12... Nxe4 13. Re1
{ Now we play for initiative along the e-file. Sometimes we get the pawn back, but not always. As we have seen in the previous chapter we can often get excellent compensation for the e4-pawn due to the weak a7-bishop.   13.d5  Bxe3  14.dxc6  Nxf2  is a sharp line that seems to be OK for Black. }
13... O-O { would lose a piece after } 14. d5
{ Black is a pawn up, but the bishop on a7 is really very bad, which is our main point. Next, we simply develop our pieces and play on the open files and on the kingside. }
14... Bxe3 15. Rxe3 { Both c6 and e4 are hanging. } *

