[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "2. Arkhangelsk with ...Rb8 Black's Modern Tries"]
[Black "11...O-O #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5
{ Going for the Arkhangelsk. One of the sharpest and most dynamic ways for Black to meet the Ruy Lopez. }
6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move is the start of the Arkhangelsk variation in the Ruy Lopez. Black's idea is pretty straightforward: all pieces should be developed to the most active positions, and once White occupies the centre Black is ready to attack it with all pieces. The main downsides are that Black will have to lose time by moving the bishop again  (after White pushes c3 and d4)  and, more importantly, that with the bishop stuck on the queenside the Black king will miss an important defender. Therefore our idea here as White is often connected to attacking the Black king. }
7. c3 { Occupying the centre makes a lot of sense against the bishop on c5. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ My preferred move order, as it keeps the option of putting the d-pawn on d3 in case of ...Bg4. }
8... Rb8 9. d4 Bb6 10. a5
{ At first glance a very surprising move. On the last move we were trying to attack Black on the queenside, and now we are instead closing the queenside down. If we look at it on a move-by-move basis it does indeed seem illogical, but what matters here is our overarching strategy of attacking on the kingside. By playing 10.a5 we are achieving two very important things:    We are forcing Black's bishop even further away from the kingside.    Closing the queenside means that Black will find it much harder to generate counterplay on that side, giving us an easier time to focus only on our centre and kingside play. }
10... Ba7 11. h3 O-O 12. Be3 exd4
{ A very modern way of playing. Black gives up the centre in the hope of creating quick counterplay against the pawns on d4 and e4. It was the choice of Caruana in the 2020 Candidates against Vachier-Lagrave, in which Caruana quickly got a comfortable position. }
13. cxd4 Nb4 14. Nc3
{ Almost whenever we have the opportunity to place the knight unhindered on c3, we should do it. From c3 the knight protect e4, but also eyes the d5-square and leaves room for the queen on d2. }
14... Bb7 15. Qd2
{ A very rare but interesting setup for White. By placing the queen on d2 we get the possibility of quickly getting a rook to d1, supporting our central play. Additionally, we indirectly protect our e4-pawn, as the knight on b4 would be hanging if Black tries to take it. The mainline is  15.Ng5  which leads to very, very forcing play where theory stretches on for many, many moves. }
15... c5
{ The only reasonable move.  15...Nxe4  16.Nxe4  Bxe4  loses a piece to  17.Qxb4  . }
16. dxc5
{ This is a rare reaction to Black's ...c5 in the Spanish, but the move we prepared by our last move Qd2. Normally speaking the trade of central pawns is in Black's favour, but here we are in time to create threats along the d-file before Black is fully developed. }
16... dxc5
{ 16...Bxc5  17.Bg5!  would let us keep the queens on and particularly leave the b3-bishop very strong as Black can never block it with c5-c4. }
17. Rad1 { Sticking to the plan of fast play in the centre. } 17... Qxd2
{ The sane choice. } 18. Rxd2
{ Even in the ending our initiative continues. The f7-pawn is a soft spot as soon as Black moves the f8-rook, and the d-file is controlled by White. But the main problem for Black is that ...c4 is never really possible to play due to the a7-bishop hanging. }
18... Nxe4
{ The critical try, picking up a pawn.   18...Rbd8  19.Rxd8  Rxd8  20.Ne5  makes it hard for Black to defend f7. }
19. Nxe4 Bxe4 20. Rd7
{ A rook on the 7th rank is usually a very good piece, and here is no exception! }
20... Rb7 21. Rfd1
{ Keeping our fantastic d7-rook. We have plenty of compensation for the pawn, and Black should really be trying to liquidate into a worse ending with  21...Rxd7  22.Rxd7  Nc6  after which both  23.Nd2  and  23.Ng5  gives White some initiative.  I slightly prefer  23.Nd2  , after which Black needs to find  23...c4!  24.Bxa7  Bf5  in order to not collapse immediately. After  25.Rd6  Nxa7  26.Rxa6  we do keep nice pressure, although of course the limited material also gives Black decent drawing chances. Still, I don't think we should complain about Black being able to find a lot of very strong defensive moves in order to probably be able to hold a slightly worse ending. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Arkhangelsk 8...b4 and 8...Bg4"]
[Black "8...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5
{ Going for the Arkhangelsk. One of the sharpest and most dynamic ways for Black to meet the Ruy Lopez. }
6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move is the start of the Arkhangelsk variation in the Ruy Lopez. Black's idea is pretty straightforward: all pieces should be developed to the most active positions, and once White occupies the centre Black is ready to attack it with all pieces. The main downsides are that Black will have to lose time by moving the bishop again  (after White pushes c3 and d4)  and, more importantly, that with the bishop stuck on the queenside the Black king will miss an important defender. Therefore our idea here as White is often connected to attacking the Black king. }
7. c3 { Occupying the centre makes a lot of sense against the bishop on c5. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ My preferred move order, as it keeps the option of putting the d-pawn on d3 in case of ...Bg4. }
8... Bg4
{ Here I would like to mention a 'rule' I was taught as a kid in the Spanish: Black should never play ...Bg4 before White has committed their d-pawn to d4. The reason is that the main aim of Bg4 is to put pressure on the d4-square. If White can still place the pawn on d3 instead, then it is very likely that the g4-bishop will be out of play. Basically, that logic is still very valid, and 8...Bg4 is indeed a rare and dubious move here. }
9. h3 { Immediately asking the bishop what the plan is. } 9... Bh5 10. axb5
{ The simplest. We open up the queenside, highlighting just how far away the h5-bishop is from the action. }
10... axb5 11. Rxa8 Qxa8 12. d3
{ As explained above, it is specifically this modest move that is the main argument against going out with the bishop to g4 too early. The inactive h5-bishop is, in fact, enough of a reason for us to be happy here. }
12... O-O 13. Bg5
{ Threatening to bury the h5-bishop completely with Bxf6 followed by g4. Black can prevent the idea by for example  13...Qd8  , but after  14.g4  Bg6  15.Nh4  we have a very nice position. Increasing kingside pressure with Nd2, Qf3 etc will be very unpleasant for Black to face. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Arkhangelsk 8...b4 and 8...Bg4"]
[Black "8...Bg4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5
{ Going for the Arkhangelsk. One of the sharpest and most dynamic ways for Black to meet the Ruy Lopez. }
6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move is the start of the Arkhangelsk variation in the Ruy Lopez. Black's idea is pretty straightforward: all pieces should be developed to the most active positions, and once White occupies the centre Black is ready to attack it with all pieces. The main downsides are that Black will have to lose time by moving the bishop again  (after White pushes c3 and d4)  and, more importantly, that with the bishop stuck on the queenside the Black king will miss an important defender. Therefore our idea here as White is often connected to attacking the Black king. }
7. c3 { Occupying the centre makes a lot of sense against the bishop on c5. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ My preferred move order, as it keeps the option of putting the d-pawn on d3 in case of ...Bg4. }
8... Bg4
{ Here I would like to mention a 'rule' I was taught as a kid in the Spanish: Black should never play Bg4 before White has committed their d-pawn to d4. The reason is that the main aim of Bg4 is to put pressure on the d4-square. If White can still place the pawn on d3 instead, then it is very likely that the g4-bishop will be out of play. Basically, that logic is still very valid, and 8...Bg4 is indeed a rare and dubious move here. }
9. h3 { Immediately asking the bishop what the plan is. } 9... Bxf3
{ The critical move. Black is giving up the bishop in order to create fast counterplay on the queenside. }
10. Qxf3 Na5 11. Bc2 b4
{ Black tries to create counterplay on the queenside, making use of the fact that our queen is not available. }
12. Qd1
{ An important move. It does look passive to retreat, but with the bishop pair we do have a long-term edge so all we need is to stop the immediate counterplay in order to claim a comfortable edge. }
12... O-O { Is playable, but does not really do anything to stop our idea. }
13. d4 exd4 { Otherwise the b4-pawn would be hanging. } 14. cxd4 Bb6 15. Be3
Re8 16. Nd2
{ We have managed to develop our pieces and kept our centre intact. If Black does not act very quickly he will just get rolled over. }
16... c5 17. Rc1
{ A very interesting positional idea. We are sacrificing a pawn in order to make our opponent's dark-squared bishop weak and our own light-squared bishop strong. A very logical continuation now would be  17...cxd4  18.Bg5  h6  19.Bxf6  Qxf6  20.Bd3  . In this position both the bishop on b6 and the knight on a5 are offside from the centre. We intend to follow up with f4 and eventually break with e5. Black's doubled extra pawn is worth very little as they will never be able to break our blockade on the light square d3. }
