13... Re8 14. Qc2
{ A useful move, protecting e4 and connecting the rooks. An additional idea we have here is the cunning move Qa2, putting pressure on the f7-pawn. I don't believe Black has strong enough pressure on our centre to compensate for the lack of space. }
14... exd4 15. cxd4 Nb4 { does not work here due to } 16. Bxf7+ Kxf7 17. Qc4+
{ winning a pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "3. Arkhangelsk 8...b4 and 8...Bg4"]
[Black "8...b4 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5
{ Going for the Arkhangelsk. One of the sharpest and most dynamic ways for Black to meet the Ruy Lopez. }
6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move is the start of the Arkhangelsk variation in the Ruy Lopez. Black's idea is pretty straightforward: all pieces should be developed to the most active positions, and once White occupies the centre Black is ready to attack it with all pieces. The main downsides are that Black will have to lose time by moving the bishop again  (after White pushes c3 and d4)  and, more importantly, that with the bishop stuck on the queenside the Black king will miss an important defender. Therefore our idea here as White is often connected to attacking the Black king. }
7. c3 { Occupying the centre makes a lot of sense against the bishop on c5. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ My preferred move order, as it keeps the option of putting the d-pawn on d3 in case of ...Bg4. }
8... b4
{ A very rare move, that I have employed myself a few times as Black, but more notably has been used by the great Vladimir Kramnik in a game against Nepomniachtchi in 2018. The idea is to immediately stop White from opening up the a-file, meaning that the a7-square will be safe for the bishop. The downside for Black is that they lose a lot of flexibility with the queenside pawns, and for instance, the c4-square is now forever in White's hands. That also means that later counterplay with ...c5 is less strong, as the typical follow-up ...c4 is not available due to the pawn already being on b4. }
9. d4 Ba7
{ The natural follow-up to 8...b4. Compared to 8...Rb8 we no longer have the option of axb5. }
10. Be3
{ I recommend playing a similar setup to what we did against 8...Rb8. However, with Black already having played ...b4 we are less concerned with ...Bg4, so we can for the time being leave h3 out. }
10... O-O 11. Nbd2 bxc3
{ Black should make this trade at some point, as Black is much more likely to use the b-file than White.  11...Bg4  12.h3  is similar to the mainline, the main difference being that White can consider taking cxb4 at some point later on if Black insists on never trading on c3. }
12. bxc3 h6 { The most solid move, stopping any Bg5's later on. } 13. h3
{ Taking the time to stop ...Bg4. Now we are just trying to strengthen up our centre with moves like Re1 and Qc2. As long as we keep it intact we should be enjoying a comfortable edge. }
13... Re8 14. Qc2
{ A useful move, protecting e4 and connecting the rooks. An additional idea we have here is the cunning move Qa2, putting pressure on the f7-pawn. I don't believe Black has strong enough pressure on our centre to compensate for the lack of space. }
14... Rb8
{ 14...exd4  15.cxd4  Nb4  does not work now, which is a big benefit of Qc2. We have the typical tactic  16.Bxf7+  Kxf7  17.Qc4+  picking up the knight on b4.   Probably the best for Black is something very slow like  14...Qe7  , just admitting being slightly worse. After 15.Rfe1  we have a stable centre and nice space advantage. Slow moves like Rac1 keeping everything under control will eventually lead to Black having to try breaking out, for which we are ready. }
15. Qa2
{ The pressure on f7 is actually harder to defend against than what it looks as first. }
15... Re7 { allows a tactical opportunity } 16. dxe5 dxe5 17. Bxf7+ Rxf7 18.
Bxa7 Nxa7 19. Nxe5
{ and due to the a2-g8 pin we get a rook and two pawns for the two pieces. Importantly we are also forcing a queen trade. }
19... Qe7 20. Qxf7+ Qxf7 21. Nxf7 Kxf7 22. Rab1
{ The last key move, as it is almost universally a good idea to trade off the opponent's remaining rook when having a rook for two pieces. Our rook and pawns are worth more than the two pieces here as the pieces lack targets. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "4. Arkhangelsk with 8...Bb7"]
[Black "10...O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5
{ Going for the Arkhangelsk. One of the sharpest and most dynamic ways for Black to meet the Ruy Lopez. }
6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This move is the start of the Arkhangelsk variation in the Ruy Lopez. Black's idea is pretty straightforward: all pieces should be developed to the most active positions, and once White occupies the centre Black is ready to attack it with all pieces. The main downsides are that Black will have to lose time by moving the bishop again  (after White pushes c3 and d4)  and, more importantly, that with the bishop stuck on the queenside the Black king will miss an important defender. Therefore our idea here as White is often connected to attacking the Black king. }
7. c3 { Occupying the centre makes a lot of sense against the bishop on c5. }
7... d6 8. a4
{ My preferred move order, as it keeps the option of putting the d-pawn on d3 in case of ...Bg4. }
8... Bb7
{ The second most popular move in the position. Black develops a piece while defending against the threat of axb5 at the same time. The downside of ...Bb7 is that the bishop is committed to b7 very early, most importantly meaning that ...Bg4 is no longer an option for Black, but also that a potential defender of the kingside is further away. In recent years Vishy Anand has been one of the main defenders of Black here, but lately many other top GMs have started playing the line, for instance, Levon Aronian. }
9. d4
{ A few months ago I tried  9.d3  against Levon Aronian myself, but occupying the centre is clearly the most ambitious way to play. }
9... Bb6 10. Be3
{ Very, very rare! Usually White plays Bg5 either here or after Re1. It does make a lot of sense to play Bg5 once Black has committed to ...Bb7, as the kingside is less defended, but the lines are long and complicated, and seem to end up OK for Black. Therefore, I am recommending this rare move. It was played once in an online game between Vachier-Lagrave and Aronian, and a few other games, but in comparison to the Bg5-setups there is almost no theory.   In some sense, Black has gained time, as ...Bb7 is developing a piece whereas a move like ...Rb8 isn't. On the other hand, we didn't have to play h3 ourselves. Overall I believe the positions to be fun and interesting for White! }
10... O-O { gives us time to defend the e4-pawn. } 11. Nbd2
{ Now, the typical way for Black to create counterplay is by opening up the diagonals for the bishops. }
11... h6 { A move such as this would be too slow. } 12. d5 Na5 13. Bxb6 cxb6
14. Bc2
{ and Black will end up with weaknesses on the queenside no matter if they take on a4 or not. The bishop on b7 is also blocked in by our solid d5-pawn. }
*

