17... c5 18. d5 c4 19. Qc3
{ A very interesting position has arisen. Black has the bishop pair, and the a7-bishop is strong, but the kingside is under pressure and the move ...g5 rarely works great for Black. The main difficulty for Black lies in the fact that there is no clear plan available, which gives us time to build up pressure on the kingside. Given time, we will either try to push e5, or more likely play Kh1, move the f3-knight and then push f4, or even g4-g5. With very accurate defense I believe Black is OK, but it looks very tricky and I like our chances in a practical game. }
19... g5 20. Nxg5 hxg5 21. Bxg5 Re5
{ 21...Nxd5  looks smart but  22.Qg3!  wins immediately as there is no way to avoid heavy material losses. }
22. Bh4
{ intending Kh1 followed by f4, shows how long term the problem of the pin is for Black. There is no defense and White is just completely winning. }
