{ We use this rook, as the other one might come in handy on the f-file in case we later sacrifice on g5 and push the e- and f-pawns. Additionally, the f2-pawn is protected which can turn out to be useful in case Black takes on d4 later. }
17... c5 18. d5 c4 19. Qc3
{ A very interesting position has arisen. Black has the bishop pair, and the a7-bishop is strong, but the kingside is under pressure and the move ...g5 rarely works great for Black. The main difficulty for Black lies in the fact that there is no clear plan available, which gives us time to build up pressure on the kingside. Given time, we will either try to push e5, or more likely play Kh1, move the f3-knight and then push f4, or even g4-g5. With very accurate defense I believe Black is OK, but it looks very tricky and I like our chances in a practical game. }
19... Rc8 { a good move, defending c4 so that Nd4 can be met by ...b4! } 20.
Kh1 { 20.h3  is also reasonable to start with. } 20... Bc5
{ Protecting d6, preparing to push ...b4 some day. } 21. h3
{ is one way of trying to make progress. We may push g4-g5 one day, but more importantly, we are giving our bishop a retreating square on h2 in case we meet ...g5 with Bg3 and Black continues with ...Nh5. }
21... b4 { Pushing our queen away from c3. } 22. Qc2 g5
{ without the queen on c3 the sacrifice on g5 is not as convincing. } 23. Bg3
{ The position is very unclear. Black has managed to finally solve the problem of the pin, but the c-pawn is weak and the kingside will be an eternal source of trouble for Black. I am not sure if 'slight edge for White' or 'unclear' is the proper evaluation, but I'd certainly enjoy playing White here! }
