[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5
{ This line is very similar tothe Arkhangelsk, and much of the same reasoning applies here as well. The bishop is more actively placed on c5 and will exercise pressure against our centre, but it will also be missed on the kingside, and Black will have to lose some time moving it again once d4 comes. This specific line has been employed numerous times by Magnus Carlsen and deserves to be treated with a lot of respect. }
6. c3 { As in the Arkhangelsk we occupy the centre. } 6... O-O
{ This is the start of the Neo-Møller. Black plays in a provocative manner, not really putting up any fight in the centre for the time being. On the other hand, Black has already managed to castle and has kept flexibility with the d-pawn. }
7. d4
{ Occupying the centre. If we manage to keep both central pawns intact we will have a very nice edge, but there will soon be heavy pressure against them. }
7... Ba7
{ This is Black's idea. As our e-pawn is hanging,  8.dxe5  Nxe4  would only be a trade which eases Black's defence. }
8. Re1
{ Defending the e-pawn. Again, all that we need is to stabilize the centre in order to claim a nice edge. }
8... d6 9. h3
{ Stopping ...Bg4, which otherwise would create unpleasant pressure againts the d4-pawn. }
9... b5 10. Bc2
{ Usually in the Spanish, when given the choice, the bishop should go to c2 in one move instead of b3. The most common exception is when we want to stop ...d5, but here the pawn has already gone to d6. Additionally, Black's main plan is to put pressure on the e4-pawn with ...Re8 and ...Bb7, so it makes good sense to overprotect e4 already now. }
10... Bb7 11. Be3 exd4
{ A better move than  11...h6  . Black is intending to play ...Nb4 as quickly as possible, winning our light-squared bishop. }
12. cxd4 Nb4 13. Nbd2 { The bishop could anyway not be saved. } 13... Nxc2 14.
Qxc2
{ We have given up our pair of bishops which always feels a sad thing to do for Ruy Lopez players. On the other hand, we have gained some time and stabilized our centre. If Black plays slowly now we can follow up with d5, trading off Black's dark-squared bishop and fixing the c7-pawn as a weakness. }
14... Rc8
{ The best move. Black gets ready to meet d5 with ...c6 after the trade of bishops. }
15. a4
{ A nice reaction, activating the rook via the a-file. The calm move  15.Qd3  , just stepping out of the c-file and again preparing d5 also looks comfortable for White and is a decent alternative if you do not want to enter the complications after  15.a4  . }
15... bxa4
{ 15...b4  would leave the b-pawn very vulnerable after  16.a5  , and if Black plays  @@StartFEN@@2rq1rk1/bbp2ppp/p2p1n2/1p6/P2PP3/4BN1P/1PQN1PP1/R3R1K1 b - - 0 15@@EndFEN@@  15...c5  then after  16.d5  they no longer have the possibility of opening up the c-file with ...c6, meaning that we have a free hand to start actions on the kingside. }
16. Bg5
{ The pin on the f6-knight is one of the eternal problems for Black when having the bishop on the a7-g1 diagonal. Here Black badly lacks defenders around the king, meaning our attack can quickly get very strong. Also note that the a1-rook quickly can swing over to the kingside via a3-g3, which shows how important it was to start with 15.a4 }
16... h6 { The only move, as the pin can't be tolerated. } 17. Bh4 g5 18. Nxg5
{ With so many of Black's pieces stuck on the queenside it feels very natural to sacrifice on g5. Very often in these positions, the sacrifice on g5 leads to at least a perpetual with chances for more, and this position is no exception. I still believe Black can survive with perfect play, but it's a rather thankless task as the maximum they can hope for is a draw. }
18... hxg5 19. Bxg5 Bxd4 { The only move to stop e5. } 20. Ra3
{ An important resource, bringing another piece into the attack. The Greek theoretician Simeonidis wrote a nice book on the Neo-Møller, here instead of giving the options  20.Nf3  and  20.Rxa4  for White, claiming Black is surviving. While I do agree it still probably is defensible with very, very good play from Black, it is certainly not an enviable task in a practical game, and White's pressure will continue for a long time.  Something like  20.Ra3  Re8  21.Rg3  Kf8  22.Nf3  c5  23.Nxd4  cxd4  24.Qxa4  after which the Black king is stuck in the centre and all of our pieces are taking part in the attack. One of the main ideas for White is to play a well-timed e5, opening up for all pieces towards the Black king. }
