[White "5. The Neo-Møller"]
[Black "6...0-0 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5
{ This line is very similar tothe Arkhangelsk, and much of the same reasoning applies here as well. The bishop is more actively placed on c5 and will exercise pressure against our centre, but it will also be missed on the kingside, and Black will have to lose some time moving it again once d4 comes. This specific line has been employed numerous times by Magnus Carlsen and deserves to be treated with a lot of respect. }
6. c3 { As in the Arkhangelsk we occupy the centre. } 6... O-O
{ This is the start of the Neo-Møller. Black plays in a provocative manner, not really putting up any fight in the centre for the time being. On the other hand, Black has already managed to castle and has kept flexibility with the d-pawn. }
7. d4
{ Occupying the centre. If we manage to keep both central pawns intact we will have a very nice edge, but there will soon be heavy pressure against them. }
7... Ba7
{ This is Black's idea. As our e-pawn is hanging,  8.dxe5  Nxe4  would only be a trade which eases Black's defence. }
8. Re1
{ Defending the e-pawn. Again, all that we need is to stabilize the centre in order to claim a nice edge. }
8... d6 9. h3
{ Stopping ...Bg4, which otherwise would create unpleasant pressure againts the d4-pawn. }
9... Re8
{ In my opinion the strongest move, and also the move Warmerdam played against me in 2021. Black avoids playing ...b5, not letting us protect the e4-pawn for free with Bc2. The downside is that it steps into the a4-e8 pin, but it turns out not to be a big problem for Black. }
10. Be3
{ I played the more direct move  10.d5  against Warmerdam, but after  10...b5  11.dxc6  bxa4  12.c4  Be6  13.Qxa4  Qc8  Black has pretty decent compensation for the pawn, and I went on to lose the game as White. }
10... exd4
{ The critical try, highlighting the fact that we did not defend  e4  on the previous move.  10...b5  11.Bc2  would be very likely to transpose to the9...b5 line. We follow up in exactly the same way with Nbd2 and a3, if allowed. }
11. Nxd4
{ Slightly unusual, but due to the pin on the a4-e8 diagonal it is important that we put pressure on c6 immediately.  11.cxd4  would generally be the desired recapture, but here Black can play  11...Rxe4  after which I am not too convinced by our compensation. }
11... Bxd4 12. cxd4 Rxe4
{ This does win a pawn for Black, but giving up the dark-squared bishop is a big concession for Black as we are going to play d5 and improve our e3-bishop. }
13. Nc3 Re8 14. d5 { is good for us. The only move not to lose material is }
14... b5 { but after } 15. dxc6 bxa4 16. Qxa4
{ we have a great position. Our bishop will be very strong on d4, and the c6-pawn cannot be attacked, therefore it is a strength. }
