14... Ne5 { 14...Nb8  15.Bg5  would be similar but even worse for Black. } 15.
Bg5
{ The key move. The pin is very annoying for Black, and we have good chances of settling Black with a very weak kingside structure. Black's extra pawn on the queenside is absolutely not felt, whereas our kingside initiative is a big factor.  If Black tries to defend the f6-knight with  15...Ned7  then  16.Ne4  is very strong, threatening both Bxd7 and Nxf6. Therefore the best move for Black is @@StartFEN@@r1bq2k1/1pp1rppp/p2p1n2/3Pn1B1/B7/2N4P/PP3PP1/R2QR1K1 b - - 2 15@@EndFEN@@  15...Bf5  that at least keeps our knight away from e4. A good continuation then is  16.g4!  Bd7  17.Bxf6  gxf6  18.Bxd7  Nxd7  19.Ne4  with a very nice initiative for the pawn. We will simply bring all our pieces to the kingside with moves like Qf3, and after some moves either f6 will become indefensible or we will reroute our knight via g3 to the juicy squares on f5 or h5. }
