[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ This move signals the start of the Open Spanish. Black immediately captures a central pawn, and the game takes on a more forcing character. By nature, the Open Spanish is a rather forcing opening, in which Black is immediately trying to fight for the initiative. However, Black's activity also has downsides - pushing a lot of pawns creates weaknesses, and if we manage to push Black back, then we can often end up with a big positional edge. A lot of contemporary and historical top players have used the Open Spanish as Black and it is a very well-respected opening overall. }
6. d4
{ Fighting for the centre and trying to open up the e-file before Black has castled. }
6... b5
{ The real Open Spanish. By removing the bishop from the a4-e8 diagonal Black gets ready to push ...d5. }
7. Bb3 d5
{ Black's idea. By placing a pawn on d5, supported by a bishop on e6, Black stabilizes the knight on e4. The game will now revolve quite a lot around the e4-knight - if we conveniently manage to trade it off we usually get a nice edge, but if it survives then it can form the basis of strong counterplay. }
8. dxe5 { Regaining the pawn and opening up the d-file. } 8... Be6
{ Now the d5-pawn is well defended and we are actually running the risk of ending up with a bad bishop on b3. }
9. c3
{ My suggestion. The most common move is  9.Nbd2  but  9.Be3  and  9.Qe2  are very well respected alternatives as well. The reason I prefer 9.c3 is that it's the most flexible move - for instance, we still keep the option of playing Be3 before Nbd2. We will need c3 for two reasons:  it is giving us control of the d4-square, blocking black's d-pawn which otherwise could threaten to move forward at a later stage.  we want to be able to play Bc2 later on, in order to put pressure on the e4-knight. }
9... Bc5
{ Black's most active option. The bishop is placed on the a7-g1 diagonal and puts pressure on f2. The big downside of Bc5 is that if White later on manages to play Nbd2-b3, then the bishop will likely have to move again. Most sources recommend 9...Bc5 as the best antidote to 9.c3 and I think it's the most likely move you will face in your games. }
10. Nbd2 { Developing and putting pressure on the e4-knight. } 10... O-O
{ 10...Nxd2  now or on the next move would make us happy.  11.Qxd2  is a nice response, intending Qd3 next to force a weakness around the Black king. Next, we can develop the dark-squared bishop and bring our a1-rook to the d-file. Without the e4-knight it is very difficult for Black to generate active counterplay. }
11. Bc2 Bf5
{ is slightly trickier and was played by Ivanchuk against Nepomniachtchi in 2020. }
12. Nb3 Bg6 { and now an important and strong move is } 13. Nfd4
{ Freeing up the f-pawn and restricting the c5-bishop. } 13... Bxd4 14. Nxd4
{ This position was reached in numerous games, for example, Leko-Korchnoi in 1994. }
14... Qd7 15. f4
{ Black got the e4-knight stable, but we have gotten the bishop pair and can follow up with simple developing moves like Be3. If Black ever takes on d4, we can recapture with the c-pawn and put pressure on the c-file. }
