12. Rxf2 f6
{ The most common move. Black is opening up the f-file to get counterplay as quickly as possible before we have time to get our king back to safety and develop our queenside.  12...Bxf2+  13.Kxf2  f6  14.Nf1  transposes to the mainline. }
13. Nf1
{ A key move. We should not capture on f6, as it would speed up Black's counterplay. Instead, we are giving up a second pawn in order to develop comfortably. Next, we threaten Be3 so Black has to take our rook immediately. }
13... Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 fxe5 15. Kg1
{ Stepping out of the f-file with the king. Now we've reached the tabyia of the Dilworth Open Spanish. We have two pieces for a rook and two pawns, which is some sort of material equality. Black has a healthy pawn structure for the time being, but it also lacks a bit of flexibility.   We would like to provoke either ...d4 or ...e4, which in both cases gives us a nice square in the centre @@StartBracket@@e4 and d4 respectively@@EndBracket@@. If Black isn't so helpful, then we will try to bring our last pieces into the game with Be3, Qd2 and Rd1 or Re1. Long term we are trying to attack Black's king with moves like Ng3 and Ng5, but first and foremost we are trying to blockade Black's central pawns. }
15... Qd6
{ A natural move. The queen overprotects both central pawns and Black prepares to bring the a8-rook to the centre. }
16. Be3 { Simply developing the bishop, continuing our plan. } 16... h6
{ The most common move, stopping Ng5 and fighting for the dark squares. 16...Rad8 17.Qe1 is nice for White - we place our queen on e1 to step out of the way of Black's d8-rook, and can follow up with Rd1 next. }
17. Bf2
{ A nice move. We avoid Black every playing ...d4 with tempo, and can transfer the bishop to g3 later on. But for the time being it is also well placed on f2, where it controls the c5-square. An additional point is that  17...Bg4  can again be met by  18.Ne3  , just like on move 15. }
17... Rad8 18. Qe2
{ 18.Qe1  is a good alternative, but then we have to consider  18...Bg4  as the f3-knight is only protected once.   After  18.Qe2  Bg4  is still pointless as we can play our usual  19.Ne3  . If Black does nothing we increase pressure with Rd1 on the next move, after which the Black centre really starts to become weak. Therefore Black should probably try the most active move  @@StartFEN@@3r1rk1/2p3p1/p1nqb2p/1p1pp3/8/2P2N2/PPB1QBPP/R4NK1 b - - 3 18@@EndFEN@@  18...d4  . Black creates the threat of ...d3, but this is also a step forward for us, as Black has now lost flexibility with the pawns and we have gotten the e4-square.   I like the calm  19.Qe1  , just stepping out of the fork, and then play N1d2-e4, with a very nice blockade. It will still not be easy to make progress as Black has everything protected, but with the pawns blocked we are running no risk and can increase pressure with moves like Bb3, Rd1 and Bg3. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "6. Dilworth Open Spanish"]
[Black "11...Nxf2 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ This move signals the start of the Open Spanish. Black immediately captures a central pawn, and the game takes on a more forcing character. By nature, the Open Spanish is a rather forcing opening, in which Black is immediately trying to fight for the initiative. However, Black's activity also has downsides - pushing a lot of pawns creates weaknesses, and if we manage to push Black back, then we can often end up with a big positional edge. A lot of contemporary and historical top players have used the Open Spanish as Black and it is a very well-respected opening overall. }
6. d4
{ Fighting for the centre and trying to open up the e-file before Black has castled. }
6... b5
{ The real Open Spanish. By removing the bishop from the a4-e8 diagonal Black gets ready to push ...d5. }
7. Bb3 d5
{ Black's idea. By placing a pawn on d5, supported by a bishop on e6, Black stabilizes the knight on e4. The game will now revolve quite a lot around the e4-knight - if we conveniently manage to trade it off we usually get a nice edge, but if it survives then it can form the basis of strong counterplay. }
8. dxe5 { Regaining the pawn and opening up the d-file. } 8... Be6
{ Now the d5-pawn is well defended and we are actually running the risk of ending up with a bad bishop on b3. }
9. c3
{ My suggestion. The most common move is  9.Nbd2  but  9.Be3  and  9.Qe2  are very well respected alternatives as well. The reason I prefer 9.c3 is that it's the most flexible move - for instance, we still keep the option of playing Be3 before Nbd2. We will need c3 for two reasons:  it is giving us control of the d4-square, blocking black's d-pawn which otherwise could threaten to move forward at a later stage.  we want to be able to play Bc2 later on, in order to put pressure on the e4-knight. }
9... Bc5
{ Black's most active option. The bishop is placed on the a7-g1 diagonal and puts pressure on f2. The big downside of Bc5 is that if White later on manages to play Nbd2-b3, then the bishop will likely have to move again. Most sources recommend 9...Bc5 as the best antidote to 9.c3 and I think it's the most likely move you will face in your games. }
10. Nbd2 { Developing and putting pressure on the e4-knight. } 10... O-O
{ 10...Nxd2  now or on the next move would make us happy.  11.Qxd2  is a nice response, intending Qd3 next to force a weakness around the Black king. Next, we can develop the dark-squared bishop and bring our a1-rook to the d-file. Without the e4-knight it is very difficult for Black to generate active counterplay. }
11. Bc2 Nxf2
{ By far the best move. Black sacrifices two pieces for a rook and a pawn, but our king is a bit vulnerable and we are behind in development.   11...Nxd2  12.Qxd2  is just great - we have kingside potential and the d5-pawn is weak. }
12. Rxf2 f6
{ The most common move. Black is opening up the f-file to get counterplay as quickly as possible before we have time to get our king back to safety and develop our queenside.  12...Bxf2+  13.Kxf2  f6  14.Nf1  transposes to the mainline. }
13. Nf1
{ A key move. We should not capture on f6, as it would speed up Black's counterplay. Instead, we are giving up a second pawn in order to develop comfortably. Next, we threaten Be3 so Black has to take our rook immediately. }
13... Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 fxe5 15. Kg1
{ Stepping out of the f-file with the king. Now we've reached the tabyia of the Dilworth Open Spanish. We have two pieces for a rook and two pawns, which is some sort of material equality. Black has a healthy pawn structure for the time being, but it also lacks a bit of flexibility.   We would like to provoke either ...d4 or ...e4, which in both cases gives us a nice square in the centre @@StartBracket@@e4 and d4 respectively@@EndBracket@@. If Black isn't so helpful, then we will try to bring our last pieces into the game with Be3, Qd2 and Rd1 or Re1. Long term we are trying to attack Black's king with moves like Ng3 and Ng5, but first and foremost we are trying to blockade Black's central pawns. }
15... Qd7
{ I believe this is Black's most accurate setup. Qd7 is very similar to Qd6, but the big advantage is that the square g4 is covered, meaning that ...Bg4 is a possibility next without having to worry about the Bxh7+ tactic that was very good against the queen on d6. The one downside of placing the queen on d7 is that it does not protect the e5-pawn, and that the queen is not defended by the c-pawn @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. }
16. a4 Kh8
{ Was played in the only game to have reached this position - a correspondence game Hof-Salcedo Mederos in 2020. It does not fall into our trap, but gives us time to develop our pieces. }
17. Be3 Bg4 18. axb5
{ Deviating from the correspondence game, which continued  18.Qe1  . By trading pawns on b5 we remove Black's rook from the f-file, making the pressure on f3 go away. }
18... axb5 19. Rxa8 Rxa8 20. h3 { Forcing the bishop to make a choice. } 20...
Bxf3 { 20...Bh5  21.Ng3  would also force the pin away. } 21. Qxf3
{ The position has stabilized. Black has managed to trade off a pair of rooks which generally is advantageous to the side with two rooks. But in compensation for having traded our good rook, we have won the pure bishop pair and gotten rid of any pressure against our position. The relatively limited material gives Black decent drawing chances, but there is no doubt we are putting pressure here. Now we should try to activate our light pieces and increase the pressure bit by bit. Ng3 and Qh5 are obvious next moves, but also Bc5 and Bf5 are useful. The queens should be kept on the board in order to have possibilities for an attack against the Black king later on. }
*

