10. Nbd2 { Developing and putting pressure on the e4-knight. } 10... O-O
{ 10...Nxd2  now or on the next move would make us happy.  11.Qxd2  is a nice response, intending Qd3 next to force a weakness around the Black king. Next, we can develop the dark-squared bishop and bring our a1-rook to the d-file. Without the e4-knight it is very difficult for Black to generate active counterplay. }
11. Bc2 Nxf2
{ By far the best move. Black sacrifices two pieces for a rook and a pawn, but our king is a bit vulnerable and we are behind in development.   11...Nxd2  12.Qxd2  is just great - we have kingside potential and the d5-pawn is weak. }
12. Rxf2 f6
{ The most common move. Black is opening up the f-file to get counterplay as quickly as possible before we have time to get our king back to safety and develop our queenside.  12...Bxf2+  13.Kxf2  f6  14.Nf1  transposes to the mainline. }
13. Nf1
{ A key move. We should not capture on f6, as it would speed up Black's counterplay. Instead, we are giving up a second pawn in order to develop comfortably. Next, we threaten Be3 so Black has to take our rook immediately. }
13... Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 fxe5 15. Kg1
{ Stepping out of the f-file with the king. Now we've reached the tabyia of the Dilworth Open Spanish. We have two pieces for a rook and two pawns, which is some sort of material equality. Black has a healthy pawn structure for the time being, but it also lacks a bit of flexibility.   We would like to provoke either ...d4 or ...e4, which in both cases gives us a nice square in the centre @@StartBracket@@e4 and d4 respectively@@EndBracket@@. If Black isn't so helpful, then we will try to bring our last pieces into the game with Be3, Qd2 and Rd1 or Re1. Long term we are trying to attack Black's king with moves like Ng3 and Ng5, but first and foremost we are trying to blockade Black's central pawns. }
15... Qd7
{ I believe this is Black's most accurate setup. Qd7 is very similar to Qd6, but the big advantage is that the square g4 is covered, meaning that ...Bg4 is a possibility next without having to worry about the Bxh7+ tactic that was very good against the queen on d6. The one downside of placing the queen on d7 is that it does not protect the e5-pawn, and that the queen is not defended by the c-pawn @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. }
16. a4 b4
{ The most natural move, and the reason we did not play 16.a4 with the queen on d6. }
17. Ng5
{ Attacking both e6 and h7. We would be very happy to win the bishop on e6, as our two bishops would then become very strong on the open board. }
17... Bf5 { Defending against both threats. } 18. Bxf5 Rxf5 19. Ne3
{ Temporarily sacrificing a piece, but it will all be clear on the next move... }
19... Rxg5 20. Nxd5
{ This constitutes the big difference between having the queen on d7 and d6. With the queen on d7 we not only threaten the rook on g5, but also a discovered attack by our knight, to win the d7-queen. Had it been on d6, the discovered attack would not have worked, both because the queen would cover f6, but also because it would be protected by the c7-pawn! }
20... Qg4 21. Bxg5 Qxg5 22. Nxc7
{ Material equality is restored, but we have a nice edge as the black pawns on a6 and b4 are very weak and the c6-knight is dominated by the pawn on c3, whereas our c7-knight can either jump to d5 or pick up the a6-pawn. }
