9... Nc5
{ This is a very popular response to @@StartFEN@@r2qkb1r/2p2ppp/p1n1b3/1p1pP3/4n3/1B3N2/PPP2PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w kq - 1 9@@EndFEN@@  9.Nbd2  , but one of the main advantages of our move order with 9.c3 is that 9...Nc5 does not come with the same effect as we have prepared a safe square on c2 for our bishop. }
10. Bc2 Bg4
{ The only move that really makes an argument for 9...Nc5. By removing our bishop from b3 Black is able to move the bishop from e6, as it no longer needs to defend the d5-pawn. Black is claiming that the g4-d1 pin is annoying for us, but practice has shown that it really isn't as annoying as it looks. This used to be a played a fair bit, but has gone completely out of fashion. }
11. Re1
{ Protecting the e5-pawn. We are not yet committing our b1-knight and c1-bishop, as it isn't entirely clear yet where they belong. }
11... Be7 { Continuing the development. } 12. b4
{ I like this direct approach. We are kicking the knight back, after which we intend to play a4 and attack the b5-pawn. Slower moves like  12.Nbd2  are possible and also better for White, though. }
12... Ne4
{ Does not make a whole lot of sense as the knight just came from here, but I would just like to stress that the knight should absolutely NOT be taken by our beautiful c2-bishop. }
13. a4 { is an excellent move, just continuing with our plan. } *

