15... Qd7 16. Qd3
{ Attacking b5, but also importantly stopping Black from castling. Additionally, we get the option of Rd1, putting pressure on the d5-pawn. }
16... Ncd8
{ This makes sense as it protects both d5 and b5, but in such an active opening as the Open Spanish, passive moves like ...Nd8 are rarely the way to go. }
17. Nd4
{ Trading off the important e6-knight. It looks like Black will get the d8-knight to e6 thereafter, but it turns out that they are never quite in time. }
17... Nxd4 18. Qxd4
{ It would have been nicer to take with the pawn on d4, but unfortunately b4 is hanging. }
18... O-O
{ Black has managed to castle, but we still have the more active position by far. }
19. Qd3 { is a typical way of starting the initiative here, provoking ...g6. }
19... g6 20. Bh6
{ A nice tempo. Also note that the bishop never moved from c1, meaning we have gained even more time. }
20... Re8 21. Qg3
{ One of many tempting moves. We attack the g4-bishop, making ...Ne6 impossible for Black. Next up we have many plans, for instance kicking the bishop back with h3, followed by either h4-h5 or simply Rad1, bringing the last piece to the game and pressuring d5. Black has a weak king, a weak d5-pawn but most importantly no real counterplay. }
