12... Ne6 13. a4
{ It is actually surprisingly tricky for Black to protect the b5-pawn in a good way. This is due to the fact that the c6-knight struggles to find a decent square to go to. }
13... Rb8
{ The only reasonable way to defend b5, but now we have won the a-file. } 14.
axb5 axb5 15. Na3
{ 16.Ra6  was also tempting, but I prefer to stick to our idea of attacking b5. We also set a small trap, which never hurts. }
15... Qd7 16. Qd3
{ Attacking b5, but also importantly stopping Black from castling. Additionally, we get the option of Rd1, putting pressure on the d5-pawn. }
16... Bh5 { Intending to play ...Bg6 in order to be able to castle. } 17. Rd1
d4 { The only move to save the pawn. } 18. h3
{ A cunning waiting move. For the time being we can't win any material, for instance,  18.Nxb5  Bg6!  wins a piece for Black as the queen can't defend both c2 and b5, but Black is also struggling to find useful moves. }
18... Bg6 { The most normal move, making O-O a possibility in the future. } 19.
Qe2 Qd5 { Protecting b5.  19...O-O  20.Bxg6  hxg6  21.Nxb5  wins a pawn. } 20.
Bxg6 hxg6 21. Nc2
{ We no longer have pressure on b5, but instead the d4-pawn is dropping off. }
21... O-O 22. Ncxd4
{ leaves us a pawn up. Black does have some drawing chances, but a pawn is a pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Open Spanish 9.c3 - 9...Be7, and 9...Nc5"]
[Black "9...Be7 10.Bc2 0-0 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ This move signals the start of the Open Spanish. Black immediately captures a central pawn, and the game takes on a more forcing character. By nature, the Open Spanish is a rather forcing opening, in which Black is immediately trying to fight for the initiative. However, Black's activity also has downsides - pushing a lot of pawns creates weaknesses, and if we manage to push Black back, then we can often end up with a big positional edge. A lot of contemporary and historical top players have used the Open Spanish as Black and it is a very well-respected opening overall. }
6. d4
{ Fighting for the centre and trying to open up the e-file before Black has castled. }
6... b5
{ The real Open Spanish. By removing the bishop from the a4-e8 diagonal Black gets ready to push ...d5.   6...exd4  is too dangerous, as it opens up the e-file prematurely.  7.Re1  d5  8.c4!  Already creates very, very difficult problems for Black to solve. }
7. Bb3 d5
{ Black's idea. By placing a pawn on d5, supported by a bishop on e6, Black stabilizes the knight on e4. The game will now revolve quite a lot around the e4-knight - if we conveniently manage to trade it off we usually get a nice edge, but if it survives then it can form the basis of strong counterplay. }
8. dxe5 { Regaining the pawn and opening up the d-file. } 8... Be6
{ Now the d5-pawn is well defended and we are actually running the risk of ending up with a bad bishop on b3. }
9. c3
{ My suggestion. The most common move is  9.Nbd2  but  9.Be3  and  9.Qe2  are very well respected alternatives as well. The reason I prefer 9.c3 is that it's the most flexible move - for instance, we still keep the option of playing Be3 before Nbd2. We will need c3 for two reasons:  it is giving us control of the d4-square, blocking black's d-pawn which otherwise could threaten to move forward at a later stage.  we want to be able to play Bc2 later on, in order to put pressure on the e4-knight. }
9... Be7
{ This is Black's other main move. The advantage compared to  9...Bc5  is that the bishop won't get attacked, and that the c5-square is still available for the e4-knight. }
10. Bc2
{ My choice. Bc2 is part of our plan, but most people prefer to start with  10.Nbd2  instead. However, that allows the line  10...Nc5  11.Bc2  d4  which is very, very deeply analyzed with theory that stretches well past move 20. While there certainly still is a lot of theory after 10.Bc2, the theoretical burden is much smaller than after 10.Nbd2. The downside of playing 10.Bc2 so early, is that we no longer exercise pressure on the d5-pawn. This gives Black freedom to move the e6-bishop to g4, which is one of Black's best moves. }
10... O-O { The old mainline. Black is simply trying to develop calmly. } 11.
Nbd2
{ The natural follow-up, putting pressure on the e4-knight. Now we have reached a position that is more often reached via 9.Nbd2, but our move order has eliminated some of Black's other options. }
11... Nxd2
{ This is similar to the position with the bishop on c5 rather than e7. } 12.
Qxd2
{ Again the correct recapture. Next, we play Qd3, provoking g6 and then Bh6 and bring our rooks to the centre. Without the e4-knight Black lacks any dynamic counterplay. }
*

