7. Bb3 d5
{ Black's idea. By placing a pawn on d5, supported by a bishop on e6, Black stabilizes the knight on e4. The game will now revolve quite a lot around the e4-knight - if we conveniently manage to trade it off we usually get a nice edge, but if it survives then it can form the basis of strong counterplay. }
8. dxe5 { Regaining the pawn and opening up the d-file. } 8... Be6
{ Now the d5-pawn is well defended and we are actually running the risk of ending up with a bad bishop on b3. }
9. c3
{ My suggestion. The most common move is  9.Nbd2  but  9.Be3  and  9.Qe2  are very well respected alternatives as well. The reason I prefer 9.c3 is that it's the most flexible move - for instance, we still keep the option of playing Be3 before Nbd2. We will need c3 for two reasons:  it is giving us control of the d4-square, blocking black's d-pawn which otherwise could threaten to move forward at a later stage.  we want to be able to play Bc2 later on, in order to put pressure on the e4-knight. }
