7. Bb3 d5
{ Black's idea. By placing a pawn on d5, supported by a bishop on e6, Black stabilizes the knight on e4. The game will now revolve quite a lot around the e4-knight - if we conveniently manage to trade it off we usually get a nice edge, but if it survives then it can form the basis of strong counterplay. }
8. dxe5 { Regaining the pawn and opening up the d-file. } 8... Be6
{ Now the d5-pawn is well defended and we are actually running the risk of ending up with a bad bishop on b3. }
9. c3
{ My suggestion. The most common move is  9.Nbd2  but  9.Be3  and  9.Qe2  are very well respected alternatives as well. The reason I prefer 9.c3 is that it's the most flexible move - for instance, we still keep the option of playing Be3 before Nbd2. We will need c3 for two reasons:  it is giving us control of the d4-square, blocking black's d-pawn which otherwise could threaten to move forward at a later stage.  we want to be able to play Bc2 later on, in order to put pressure on the e4-knight. }
9... Be7
{ This is Black's other main move. The advantage compared to  9...Bc5  is that the bishop won't get attacked, and that the c5-square is still available for the e4-knight. }
10. Bc2
{ My choice. Bc2 is part of our plan, but most people prefer to start with  10.Nbd2  instead. However, that allows the line  10...Nc5  11.Bc2  d4  which is very, very deeply analyzed with theory that stretches well past move 20. While there certainly still is a lot of theory after 10.Bc2, the theoretical burden is much smaller than after 10.Nbd2. The downside of playing 10.Bc2 so early, is that we no longer exercise pressure on the d5-pawn. This gives Black freedom to move the e6-bishop to g4, which is one of Black's best moves. }
10... O-O { The old mainline. Black is simply trying to develop calmly. } 11.
Nbd2
{ The natural follow-up, putting pressure on the e4-knight. Now we have reached a position that is more often reached via 9.Nbd2, but our move order has eliminated some of Black's other options. }
11... f5
{ Supporting the strong e4-knight, around which a lot of Black's play is built. }
12. Nb3
{ The mainline. We intend to get a knight to d4, hitting the e6-bishop and freeing up the f-pawn to kick Black's knight out.   Recently the move  12.exf6  has also gotten popular, but I believe it gives Black more counter chances than the line we choose. }
12... Qd7 { Defending e6 in anticipation of our next move. } 13. Nfd4
{ It does not matter with which knight we are going to d4, as we are anyway intending to recapture with the other knight. }
13... Nxd4 14. Nxd4 c5 { Necessary, as Black needs to force White's hand. } 15.
Nxe6 Qxe6 16. f3 { Finally kicking the knight away from e4. } 16... Ng5
{ The only square, but a little bit clumsy. This position has been reached in thousands of games and is one of the absolute main positions of the Open Spanish. We have the bishop pair, but for the time being our bishops are pretty blocked and there is no obvious way of opening up for them. One of the main ideas is therefore to trade on g5, trying to prove that the light-squared bishop is stronger than Black's dark-squared one. This is true, but often White's advantage proves too small to really play for the win. }
17. Bf4
{ I want to suggest this very rare move. One of the main points is that out of the thousands of games that have been played, 17.Bf4 was tried in less than five, so it is likely to surprise your opponent. Chess-wise the point is mainly one of flexibility. We are not averse to the idea of capturing on g5, but want to wait for a better moment to do so. We also introduce the idea of Qd2, hitting the g5-knight. Another very important point is that we stop Black from playing ...f4 themselves, which would stop us both from Bxg5 and from f4.   If Black moves the queen, say  17...Qc6  , we play  18.Bxg5!  and it might look like we have lost a tempo, but in reality, we have won one, as the queen is better on  e6  here! }
17... Rad8 { The most natural move, supporting the d5-pawn. } 18. Kh1
{ Another waiting move. One of Black's main ideas it to push ...c4 followed by a check either by Qb6+ or Bc5+ to be able to push ...d4. Therefore we prophylactically step out of the way with our king. already now. Some time in the future the idea of breaking up the kingside with g4 can also be effective, for which the king is much safer tucked away on h1.   18.Qd2  would be well met by  18...Qg6  , when  19.g4  does not work due to  19...Nh3+  . }
18... Qb6
{ 18...c4  would be too early, as we can play  19.Qd4!  taking control of the important a7-g1 diagonal. }
19. Bxg5 { Now we take, as the queen is worse off on b6 than e6! } 19... Bxg5
20. f4 Be7 21. g4
{ With our king already on h1 and Black's queen a bit offside on the queenside we have a good opportunity for this push. The opposite coloured bishops make the light squares in Black's camp very vulnerable potentially, and now we are immediately trying to hit them.   21.Qe2  is a less forcing option that also could be tried as White. }
21... d4
{ By far the strongest move - Black really needs to get counterplay. Instead  21...fxg4  22.Qxg4  gives us a very dangerous attack on the light squares. We can follow up with Rg1 and both the g7- and h7-pawns are very weak, while the e7-bishop struggles to partake in the defence. }
22. Bxf5 { Picking up an important pawn. } 22... dxc3
{ With a discovered attack. } 23. Qb3+ Kh8 24. Qxc3
{ We have won a pawn, but the move g4 makes our f4-pawn quite weak, giving Black some compensation. Still, the maximum Black can hope for is to win back the extra pawn to make a draw in the ending. It is not entirely unlikely they will succeed, but it's also not such a bad worst-case scenario! }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "7. Open Spanish 9.c3 - 9...Be7, and 9...Nc5"]
[Black "9...Be7 10.Bc2 Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4
{ This move signals the start of the Open Spanish. Black immediately captures a central pawn, and the game takes on a more forcing character. By nature, the Open Spanish is a rather forcing opening, in which Black is immediately trying to fight for the initiative. However, Black's activity also has downsides - pushing a lot of pawns creates weaknesses, and if we manage to push Black back, then we can often end up with a big positional edge. A lot of contemporary and historical top players have used the Open Spanish as Black and it is a very well-respected opening overall. }
6. d4
{ Fighting for the centre and trying to open up the e-file before Black has castled. }
6... b5
{ The real Open Spanish. By removing the bishop from the a4-e8 diagonal Black gets ready to push ...d5.   6...exd4  is too dangerous, as it opens up the e-file prematurely.  7.Re1  d5  8.c4!  Already creates very, very difficult problems for Black to solve. }
7. Bb3 d5
{ Black's idea. By placing a pawn on d5, supported by a bishop on e6, Black stabilizes the knight on e4. The game will now revolve quite a lot around the e4-knight - if we conveniently manage to trade it off we usually get a nice edge, but if it survives then it can form the basis of strong counterplay. }
8. dxe5 { Regaining the pawn and opening up the d-file. } 8... Be6
{ Now the d5-pawn is well defended and we are actually running the risk of ending up with a bad bishop on b3. }
9. c3
{ My suggestion. The most common move is  9.Nbd2  but  9.Be3  and  9.Qe2  are very well respected alternatives as well. The reason I prefer 9.c3 is that it's the most flexible move - for instance, we still keep the option of playing Be3 before Nbd2. We will need c3 for two reasons:  it is giving us control of the d4-square, blocking black's d-pawn which otherwise could threaten to move forward at a later stage.  we want to be able to play Bc2 later on, in order to put pressure on the e4-knight. }
9... Be7
{ This is Black's other main move. The advantage compared to  9...Bc5  is that the bishop won't get attacked, and that the c5-square is still available for the e4-knight. }
10. Bc2
{ My choice. Bc2 is part of our plan, but most people prefer to start with  10.Nbd2  instead. However, that allows the line  10...Nc5  11.Bc2  d4  which is very, very deeply analyzed with theory that stretches well past move 20. While there certainly still is a lot of theory after 10.Bc2, the theoretical burden is much smaller than after 10.Nbd2. The downside of playing 10.Bc2 so early, is that we no longer exercise pressure on the d5-pawn. This gives Black freedom to move the e6-bishop to g4, which is one of Black's best moves. }
10... Bg4
{ Immediately making use of the fact that d5 is no longer under attack.  10...Nc5  would be completely pointless here as without the knight on d2 Black lacks enough firepower to support ...d4. For instance  11.Re1  and Nc5 has made no sense. }
11. Qe1
{ Don't worry if you think this move looks odd - I also thought so the first time I saw it. But in fact, it is quite smart. We step out of the annoying pin which gives us the possibility of playing Nd4 next. Getting the knight to d4 is a huge achievement here, as the threat of f3 attacking both the e4-knight and the g4-bishop would be very unpleasant for Black to face.   11...O-O  would be dubious as it allows  12.Nd4!  when f3 is a very unpleasant threat for Black to face. }
11... Bxf3
{ This is the most obvious question after 11.Qe1. Black ruins our kingside structure, but in doing so they also give up their strong bishop, leaving us with a potentially very dangerous bishop pair. }
12. gxf3 Nc5 13. b4 Ne6 14. f4
{ Black is pushed back. Next, we can follow up with a4 and start attacking the b5-pawn. The doubled f-pawns are a bit annoying, but Black does not have enough pieces on the kingside in order to make use of it. Instead it is more likely that we will be able to play f5 ourselves at a later stage, creating an initiative also on the kingside. }
