{ Don't worry if you think this move looks odd - I also thought so the first time I saw it. But in fact, it is quite smart. We step out of the annoying pin which gives us the possibility of playing Nd4 next. Getting the knight to d4 is a huge achievement here, as the threat of f3 attacking both the e4-knight and the g4-bishop would be very unpleasant for Black to face.   11...O-O  would be dubious as it allows  12.Nd4!  when f3 is a very unpleasant threat for Black to face. }
11... Bxf3
{ This is the most obvious question after 11.Qe1. Black ruins our kingside structure, but in doing so they also give up their strong bishop, leaving us with a potentially very dangerous bishop pair. }
12. gxf3 Qd7
{ A cunning move, with the idea that capturing the e4-knight leads to perpetual check. }
13. Qe2 { Threatening to take the knight. } 13... Nc5 14. f4
{ This is a better version for Black than the immediate 12...Nc5, but still comfortable for us. With the queen already on e2 we ready for Rd1, putting pressure on the d5-pawn. The queen has a nice square on f3. Long term we of course want to develop with Be3 and Nd2. Black does have the better structure, but once we develop all our pieces then the bishop pair will be very strong. }
