11... Nc5
{ The best move. Black realizes that the knight on e4 will be vulnerable after our Nd4 next, therefore the knight is transferred to the very nice blockading square on e6. }
12. Nd4
{ Continuing with our plan. We free up the f-pawn force black to improve our central pawn structure. }
12... Nxd4 13. cxd4 Ne6
{ The structure has changed. With the pawn on d4 instead of c3 our e5-pawn is never weak, but we do have to protect the d4-pawn. Black will be aiming for counterplay connected to either ...f6, hitting e5, or ...c5, hitting d4. We should be trying to develop our pieces and eventually, if allowed, push f4-f5. }
14. Qd2 c5
{ An interesting alternative, trying to hit our centre as soon as possible. }
15. dxc5
{ Settling black with an isolated d-pawn. It is not that big of a weakness, but still something for us to play against. If we can force it forward to d4, we get a very nice square for a knight on e4, and a safe blockade on d3.   15.h3  Bh5  16.f4  is a much sharper alternative, which can be investigated by the braver of you. }
15... Bxc5 16. Nc3 d4 { would be a big position mistake } 17. Ne4
{ and Black has lost a lot of their dynamic potential. After blocking the d-pawn with Bd3 we can follow up with f4-f5, with a very promising initiative. }
