{ Don't worry if you think this move looks odd - I also thought so the first time I saw it. But in fact, it is quite smart. We step out of the annoying pin which gives us the possibility of playing Nd4 next. Getting the knight to d4 is a huge achievement here, as the threat of f3 attacking both the e4-knight and the g4-bishop would be very unpleasant for Black to face.   11...O-O  would be dubious as it allows  12.Nd4!  when f3 is a very unpleasant threat for Black to face. }
11... Nc5
{ The best move. Black realizes that the knight on e4 will be vulnerable after our Nd4 next, therefore the knight is transferred to the very nice blockading square on e6. }
12. Nd4
{ Continuing with our plan. We free up the f-pawn force black to improve our central pawn structure. }
12... Nxd4 13. cxd4 Ne6
{ The structure has changed. With the pawn on d4 instead of c3 our e5-pawn is never weak, but we do have to protect the d4-pawn. Black will be aiming for counterplay connected to either ...f6, hitting e5, or ...c5, hitting d4. We should be trying to develop our pieces and eventually, if allowed, push f4-f5. }
14. Qd2 O-O
{ The main move, and what was tried by theory expert Anish Giri in his game with Vachier-Lagrave in 2019. }
15. Nc3
{ Developing the knight, making ...c5 harder to achieve as the d5-pawn would be hanging. }
15... f5 { Was the choice of Giri, but it is less flexible than the mainline. }
16. Qd3
{ Opening up for the c1-bishop. Next, we play f3, followed by either Be3 or Ne2-f4, trading off the strong blockading knight on e6. Long term we will either create pressure on the c-file @@StartBracket@@once the knights are traded@@EndBracket@@ or even push our kingside pawns, though that requires careful preparation. Black's main problem is that the only available pawn break, ...c5, mainly creates a weakness on d5. }
