{ We have sacrificed a piece, but the d- and e-pawns start rolling and will win back the material. }
21... Qd7 { The only move to keep e6 protected. } 22. d5 Nd4
{ Again the only move. Black wins a tempo due to the counterthreat Ne2+. Now there are many tempting options for White, and it is difficult to decide which one is the most promising. }
23. Rfe1
{ 23.Rae1  Qd8  24.d6  cxd6  25.Bxf7+  Kxf7  26.e6+  Nxe6  27.Rxe6  Kxe6  28.Re1+  Kd7  29.Qe3  is also an interesting try. }
23... Qd8 24. Rac1
{ I think it's time for us to stop here, as the options are getting increasingly out of control. The verdict is not really changing - a strong computer playing Black will be able to make a draw here with Black. But for a human, I think the task is almost impossible. At the same time, we are playing with relatively small risk, as we can always win back material by pushing our central pawns.   24.e6!?  is another promising option. After  24.Rac1  Bb4  is the only move. And now out of many interesting options, I can mention  25.e6  @@StartBracket@@25.d6 also forces Black to play incredibly well to make a draw@@EndBracket@@  25...Re7  26.Qh4  Nxb3  27.Qxb4  Nxc1  28.Rxc1  Qd6  29.Rc5  with a very unusual position where we have a very strong bind in the dark squares and without central pawns, but are a whole rook down. I suspect it's balanced, but certainly looks like a fun position to play! }
