[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 exd4
{ This is known as the Riga Variation. Black opens up the e-file before having gotten the king into safety and we can punish them badly for that by some powerful moves. }
7. Re1 { Already creating serious threats along the e-file. } 7... d5 8. c4
{ The key move. Just like in the mainlines of the Open Spanish we are trying to destabilize Black's e4-knight. The main difference is that if the knight gets kicked out here, the king on e8 will be very vulnerable thereafter. }
8... Bb4 { An attempted counterattack that does not work out well. } 9. cxd5
{ Another very strong move. We are temporarily giving up some material, but winning it back with interest by force. }
9... Bxe1 10. Qxe1 { Still attacking two pieces, so Black's reply is forced. }
10... Qxd5 11. Bb3
{ The point. The only square for the queen to protect the e4-knight is from f5, but then the e4-knight can no longer be protected by the f-pawn. }
11... Qf5 12. Bc2
{ We are winning a full piece on e4 on the next move. After  12...O-O  13.Qxe4  black is still doing OK materially speaking with rook and two pawns for the two pieces, but our pieces will be very strong. Bf4 will create unpleasant pressure on c7, and the knight can never really move from c6 due to the weak d4-pawn, meaning that the pawn majority can never really get moving. }
