1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 exd4
{ This is known as the Riga Variation. Black opens up the e-file before having gotten the king into safety and we can punish them badly for that by some powerful moves. }
7. Re1 { Already creating serious threats along the e-file. } 7... d5 8. c4
{ The key move. Just like in the mainlines of the Open Spanish we are trying to destabilize Black's e4-knight. The main difference is that if the knight gets kicked out here, the king on e8 will be very vulnerable thereafter. }
8... dxc3
{ Natural as it removes the threat of cxd5, but opening up the centre even more and allowing our knight to enter the game with tempo. }
9. Nxc3
{ We are two pawns down, but will win back one immediately in the centre, and for the other one, we have a devastating attack. }
9... Be6
{ Blocking the e-file like this would leave the king in the centre for too long. }
10. Ne5 { This makes it very hard for Black to defend the c6-square. } 10...
Nxc3 { Black has tried this in a few games. } 11. bxc3 Qd6 12. Rb1
{ Out of many very good options, I like this one best. } 12... b5 13. Rxb5 axb5
14. Bxb5
{ Now Black is unable to defend c6 and not in time to bring the king into safety. After we capture on c6 the attack will play itself. }
