{ An interesting line for Black. The point is to play ...b5 on the next move, tricking White into a suboptimal version of the Open Spanish. For a long time it was considered highly dubious, but after Mamedyarov used it to beat Aronian in an important game in the 2018 Olympiad it has gotten a lot more popular, even being played by Magnus Carlsen more than once. It is highly provocative, but not bad at all and leads to some very unusual positions. }
7. Re1 { Again questioning the e4-knight. } 7... b5
{ Just like in the usual Open Spanish Black needs to flick in ... b5 before ...d5, so that the c6-knight is not pinned. }
8. Rxe4
{ This is the difference! Due to Black having spent a move on ...Be7 we no longer have to retreat the a4-bishop. Instead  8.Bb3  d5  9.dxe5  Be6  would give us an Open Spanish where we have played the move 9.Re1 instead of our preferred 9.c3. }
8... d5 9. Nxe5 { The tactics continue! } 9... Nxe5
{ The only move, as Black needs to have time to pick up the a4-bishop next. }
10. Rxe5 bxa4
{ A very interesting and strategically imbalanced position has arisen. Black's structure on the queenside is dubious and the king is stuck in the centre, but they do have a bishop pair that can potentially be very strong. We should not get materialistic here and go for the a4-pawn, but rather act quickly in the centre before Black gets their king to safety. }
11. Qe2
{ An important move, creating an unpleasant pin on the e7-bishop and stopping O-O. }
11... Be6
{ This is the second most popular move, but in some sense the most logical one. Black tries to solve the problems on the e-file while developing at the same time. }
12. f4
{ Again we must act quickly before Black gets castled. The threat of f5 is surprisingly unpleasant for Black to meet. }
12... g6 { Stopping f5, but creating additional weaknesses on the kingside. }
