{ A very interesting idea. Again we are trying to act before Black gets their king to safety. It does cost a pawn, but in these positions activity is often much more important. }
13... gxf5 { 13...Bxf5  14.Nc3  Be6  15.Nxa4  is a worse version for Black. }
14. Nc3 a3 { Usually a useful move for Black to include after Nc3. } 15. b3
{ Not ruining our structure. Black's king is still stuck in the centre, and castling long would be very, very dangerous. }
15... Rg8 16. Bf4
{ Just developing calmly. Next, we want to bring our a1-rook into the game and then find an active route for the c3-knight. Most probably it will go via e2 to the kingside.   The main problem for Balck is that the king is eternally weak, and the bishops are blocked in by the d5- and f5-pawns. The minus pawn for White is absolutely not felt, as it's a very weak doubled pawn on the f-file. However, we should not underestimate the bishop pair, and have to be careful when opening up the position. All in all, I believe the position is very rich, and much easier for White to play. }
