[White "9. Martinez Variation 6.d3 - 6...b5 7.Bb3 d6 8.c3 Na5"]
[Black "10...cxd4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ The mainline.   Black can also delay ...Be7 in favor of  5...b5  6.Bb3  d6  attempting to move order us into  7.d3  , when Black can hunt down our bishop with ...Na5.  But we play  7.c3  instead, and after  7...Be7  we can transpose back into out repertoire with  8.d3  . }
6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... b5
{ The main move. Black defends against the threat of Bxc6 followed by Nxe5. Importantly ...b5 is played before we had time for c3, meaning the c2-square is not yet available for our bishop. The downside of the move ...b5 is that it creates a target for us to attack later on, with a4. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ The most flexible move, getting ready to meet  8.a4  with  8...Bd7  . } 8. c3
{ Highly controversial! The mainline for some years has instead been a setup with  8.a3  and 9.Nc3  , which leads to a different style of play. While that is interesting, I believe sticking to the setup with a pawn on c3, as we do in almost all of our lines, makes for a nice coherent repertoire. Move orders are very important, though. }
8... Na5 { Black insists on getting the Na5+c5 setup. } 9. Bc2 c5
{ In time before we had time to play b4. } 10. d4
{ This looks strange. We are losing a tempo by going d3 and later d4. It is not as stupid as it looks, though. We have not yet had to play h3 and Re1, which both are useful moves but perhaps not the most important ones already here. Secondly, and I think more important, is that Black has already committed the knight to a5, which means that the Marshall, Breyer and Zaitsev are no longer available. }
10... cxd4
{ The choice of Ding Liren when he beat Magnus Carlsen in 2019. Black loses some flexibility but rules out the possibility of us playing d5 with a big space advantage. }
11. cxd4 O-O { A cunning move, not bothering to defend the e5-pawn. } 12. h3
{ 12.dxe5  dxe5  13.Nxe5  Qc7  shows why it's so important for Black to trade on d4 first - with the c-file open the bishop on c2 is hanging loose and Black gets a lot of counterplay on the c- and d-files. }
12... exd4
{ 12...Re8  was Carlsen-Ding, and now Carlsen prematurely closed the centre with  d5  . After the simple  13.Nc3  Black should play  13...exd4  which transposes to our line after  14.Nxd4  . }
13. Nxd4 Re8 14. Nc3 Bb7 { This weakens the f5 square. } 15. Nf5
{ Black can't be happy with us getting such a magnificent outpost. } *

