13. Nxd4 Bd7 { The most flexible move, not yet committing the rook to e8. } 14.
b3
{ We are trying to get the same setup as after the13...Re8 move order, but we need to start by b3, Bb2 in order to have the knight defended on c3. }
14... Rc8 15. Bb2 Nc6 16. Nc3
{ This is very similar to the13...Re8 move order, but Black can try to make use of the extra tempo gained by omitting ...Re8. }
16... b4 { Kicking the knight away. } 17. Nce2 d5
{ The point. Black is trying to equalize by brute force. } 18. Nxc6
{ 18.exd5  Nxd5  19.Nf5!?  is an interesting, more concrete option. } 18...
Bxc6 19. e5
{ A standard reaction to the d5-push. Black gets a passed d-pawn, but we have a very nice blockade on d4 and a potentially dangerous kingside majority. }
19... Ne4 20. Bd3
{ The position has stabilized. We have slightly the better structure, but Black is pretty active. As long as we control the d4-square the activity shouldn't lead to a lot, and I believe we will be able to kick Black back bit by bit. Slow moves like Rc1, Bd4 and eventually preparing f3 to get rid of the e4-knight. It's not as good as it looks at first sight, but it's definitely a little something. }
