[White "10. Martinez Variation 6.d3 - 8...O-O, Other 9th Moves"]
[Black "9...Bd7 10.Bc2 b4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ The mainline.   Black can also delay ...Be7 in favor of  5...b5  6.Bb3  d6  attempting to move order us into  7.d3  , when Black can hunt down our bishop with ...Na5.  But we play  7.c3  instead, and after  7...Be7  we can transpose back into out repertoire with  8.d3  . }
6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... b5
{ The main move. Black defends against the threat of Bxc6 followed by Nxe5. Importantly ...b5 is played before we had time for c3, meaning the c2-square is not yet available for our bishop. The downside of the move ...b5 is that it creates a target for us to attack later on, with a4. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ The most flexible move, getting ready to meet  8.a4  with  8...Bd7  . } 8. c3
{ Highly controversial! The mainline for some years has instead been a setup with  8.a3  and 9.Nc3  , which leads to a different style of play. While that is interesting, I believe sticking to the setup with a pawn on c3, as we do in almost all of our lines, makes for a nice coherent repertoire. Move orders are very important, though. }
8... O-O { The main move. Black simply continues with the development. } 9. a4
{ The move a4 is a vital part of our strategy - the move ...b5 has created a hook for us to try to attack, and we are well placed for fighting for the light squares on the queenside. However, as so often in the Ruy Lopez, timing is of utmost importance. The reason we have included c3 for us and O-O for Black will be shown on the next move.   A logical question to ask is what happens after  9.Bc2  , as it also steps out of ...Na5. Without the inclusion of a4 Bd7 Black has a much more harmonious position, as the bishop on d7 is somewhat clumsily placed. The more concrete differences are: Black finds it easier to push ...d5 as the queen controls the centre.  Black can make use of the Breyer maneuver ...Nb8-d7, which frequently is a harmonious regrouping. }
9... Bd7
{ The most common move, although both  9...Bb7  and  9...b4  are relevant alternatives. }
10. Bc2
{ This is the whole point! We step out of Black's ...Na5 followed by ...c5 idea. The reason we are making such a fuss about the c6-knight is that it really is quite misplaced for a long time. Without Black being able to play ...c5 we will always have the d4-push available later on. Bc2 does however lose some time, and Black's position is still very solid. The general trend among the strongest players lately has been to stay away from this position as Black, but I don't think there is any particular reason to do so. }
10... b4
{ Black gives up flexibility and the control over the light squares on c4 and a4 @@StartBracket@@if we push a5 later@@EndBracket@@. In return, the possibility of axb5 disappears for us. }
11. Re1
{ Our main plan is to push d4, so we need the rook to protect the e4-pawn. Additionally, we dissuade Black even further from playing ...d5. }
11... Rb8
{ Another benefit of ...b4. Black can play Rb8 without giving White the a-file. }
12. h3
{ In practical play, the immediate Nbd2 has been a bit more popular, but in my view h3 is more flexible. One reason is that the knight still controls c3, and another that the c1-bishop can still get out. }
12... d5
{ This would have been decent with our knight already on d2, but here it is premature. }
13. exd5 Nxd5 14. d4 { The difference! Now c3 is protected. } 14... bxc3 15.
Nxc3
{ We are well equipped for the opening of the centre whereas Black would like to have the rook on e8 and preferably the bishop on e6. After }
15... Nxc3 16. bxc3
{ we have more space and the more active position. An additional point is that after }
16... exd4 { the move } 17. Bf4 { is really interesting, the idea being that }
17... dxc3 { runs into } 18. Qd3 g6 19. Rad1
{ with heavy pressure along the d-file and the centre. These sort of ideas shows why 12...d5 was premature. }
*

