{ The move a4 is a vital part of our strategy - the move ...b5 has created a hook for us to try to attack, and we are well placed for fighting for the light squares on the queenside. However, as so often in the Ruy Lopez, timing is of utmost importance. The reason we have included c3 for us and O-O for Black will be shown on the next move.   A logical question to ask is what happens after  9.Bc2  , as it also steps out of ...Na5. Without the inclusion of a4 Bd7 Black has a much more harmonious position, as the bishop on d7 is somewhat clumsily placed. The more concrete differences are: Black finds it easier to push ...d5 as the queen controls the centre.  Black can make use of the Breyer maneuver ...Nb8-d7, which frequently is a harmonious regrouping. }
9... Bd7
{ The most common move, although both  9...Bb7  and  9...b4  are relevant alternatives. }
10. Bc2
{ This is the whole point! We step out of Black's ...Na5 followed by ...c5 idea. The reason we are making such a fuss about the c6-knight is that it really is quite misplaced for a long time. Without Black being able to play ...c5 we will always have the d4-push available later on. Bc2 does however lose some time, and Black's position is still very solid. The general trend among the strongest players lately has been to stay away from this position as Black, but I don't think there is any particular reason to do so. }
10... Re8
{ The main move. Black is taking it slowly, intending ...h6, ...Bf8 and eventually ...d5 later on. }
11. Re1
{ Again we prefer to wait with Nbd2, keeping the possibility of developing the dark-squared bishop. }
11... h6 { Black prepares ...Bf8 by preventing Bg5 first. } 12. Nbd2
{ As Black has stopped Bg5, we have no reason not to develop our knight. }
12... Bf8 { Continuing the plan. } 13. h3
{ An interesting subtlety. The most common move is  13.Nf1  , but then Black does quite well by breaking in the centre with  13...d5  . Keeping the knight on d2 makes it riskier for Black to play ...d5 early on, as we will see. An additional point of keeping the knight on d2 is that we are still ready to jump to c4, if Black rushes with ...b4. }
13... Ne7
{ This has been the most common move in practice, played by for instance Leko and Tomashevsky, two great experts of the Ruy Lopez. It's a logical way of solving the problem of the c6-knight, but on the other hand, giving us the opportunity to seize the centre. }
14. d4 Ng6 15. Nf1
{ We continue with natural play. The knight belongs to g3, where it defends e4 and keeps out of the way of the c1-bishop. }
15... c5 { Attacking our centre and forcing a decision. } 16. d5
{ I believe this is simple enough. In a perfect world, Black would also have a bad knight on a5 or b7, but here it is sensibly placed on g6. That makes our space advantage slightly less useful than in for instance the Chigorin lines, but it is still definitely an asset. Without the a5-knight Black's queenside is also slightly more vulnerable, and we do have good possibilities of entering on the a-file. In Karjakin-Leko 2011, Black now played }
16... Nh7 17. Be3 Be7
{ in order to trade knights on g5. Karjakin now played b4, but I believe the simplest would have been }
18. Qd2 Ng5 19. N1h2 Nxf3+ 20. Nxf3 Nh4 21. Nxh4 Bxh4
{ and now the key move is } 22. Ra3
{ with the idea of doubling on the a-file before trading on b5. We will be able to enter on the a-file, and although it certainly does not win the game, it does give us a very safe and long-term advantage. }
