{ An ambitious move, played by strong players such as Adams, Akopian and a young Esipenko. However, as mentioned before it is a little bit riskier to push ...d5 before we have moved our knight from d2. }
14. d4
{ Immediately creating a lot of tension in the centre, for which Black is not yet 100% ready. }
14... exd4 15. e5
{ The point. As we have firm control of the e4-square the knight on f6 does not really have anywhere good to go. }
15... dxc3 { Winning a pawn, but we get excellent compensation. } 16. bxc3 Nh7
{ Sadly, the only available square. } 17. Nf1
{ Attacking d5, but mainly bringing another piece towards the kingside. } 17...
Be6
{ Now we have many tempting options. An important thing is that we do not really need to hurry that much, as Black isn't really threatening any counterplay soon. }
18. Bd2
{ I quite like this slow move with the intention of playing either Qb1!?, or, if Black plays g6, Qc1 to attack h6. One knight will go to g3 and the other one is ready to go to d4 as soon as the c6-knight moves. It looks super scary for Black }
