{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... b5
{ The main move. Black defends against the threat of Bxc6 followed by Nxe5. Importantly ...b5 is played before we had time for c3, meaning the c2-square is not yet available for our bishop. The downside of the move ...b5 is that it creates a target for us to attack later on, with a4. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ The most flexible move, getting ready to meet  8.a4  with  8...Bd7  . } 8. c3
{ Highly controversial! The mainline for some years has instead been a setup with  8.a3  and 9.Nc3  , which leads to a different style of play. While that is interesting, I believe sticking to the setup with a pawn on c3, as we do in almost all of our lines, makes for a nice coherent repertoire. Move orders are very important, though. }
8... O-O { The main move. Black simply continues with the development. } 9. a4
{ The move a4 is a vital part of our strategy - the move ...b5 has created a hook for us to try to attack, and we are well placed for fighting for the light squares on the queenside. However, as so often in the Ruy Lopez, timing is of utmost importance. The reason we have included c3 for us and O-O for Black will be shown on the next move.   A logical question to ask is what happens after  9.Bc2  , as it also steps out of ...Na5. Without the inclusion of a4 and Bd7 Black has a much more harmonious position, as the bishop on d7 is somewhat clumsily placed. The more concrete differences are: Black finds it easier to push ...d5 as the queen controls the centre.  Black can make use of the Breyer maneuver ...Nb8-d7, which frequently is a harmonious regrouping. }
9... b4
{ Always one of the natural reactions we need to take into account when playing a4 in the d3-Spanish. Black removes all tension on the a-file and against the b5-pawn, and does not have to commit the bishop to the slightly inferior b7 or d7 squares, keeping the option of going to e6. It has been played numerous times at the highest level, and was the choice of Sergey Karjakin against me a few months ago. }
10. a5
{ Our standard response. The pawn on a5 is almost universally useful after Black has played ...b4, as we separate the a6 and b4-pawns from each other. A downside of placing our pawn on a5 is that it can be attacked via the maneuver Rb8-b5, but here we are ready to protect the pawn with a quick Nbd2-c4. Next up we should develop our pieces with Nbd2-c4, Re1, h3, and then try a well-timed d4-push. }
10... Rb8 { Almost universally played, as the b4-pawn needs support. } 11. Nbd2
{ Important! We don't want to trade the light-squared bishops yet, and now we are in time to meet ...Be6 with Nc4. }
11... Be6 12. Nc4
{ Just in time! Trading the bishops on e6 is not in itself a bad idea, but it would take the game into a completely different territory, much more often arising from the Anti-Marshall and outside the scope of our repertoire. }
12... h6
{ This is what Karjakin played against me, and also chosen by players like Adams, Harikrishna, and Kamsky. It's a logical and useful move, but slightly inaccurate here. }
13. d4
{ This is the problem for Black. Normally speaking Black wants to trade on c3 before taking on d4, but here the threat of d5 forces Black to trade immediately on d4. }
13... exd4 14. cxd4 d5 { The only move to stop d5. } 15. Nce5
{ A small tactical trick that forces Black backward. } 15... Nxe5 16. Nxe5
{ The threat of Nc6 is very unpleasant. } *

