{ Important! We don't want to trade the light-squared bishops yet, and now we are in time to meet ...Be6 with Nc4. }
11... Be6 12. Nc4
{ Just in time! Trading the bishops on e6 is not in itself a bad idea, but it would take the game into a completely different territory, much more often arising from the Anti-Marshall and outside the scope of our repertoire. }
12... bxc3
{ The most popular move in practical play so far, and for instance played in the famous game Svidler-Carlsen in the Candidates tournament 2013. }
13. bxc3 h6
{ The most common and natural move. Black removes any Ng5 threats and intends to continue Qc8 and Rd8, slowly getting ready for the ...d5 push. }
14. Re1
{ We are in the long run intending to push d4, but it will take a long time to prepare. In the meantime we need to make sure Black is not able to push ...d5 conveniently. The rook is almost universally very useful on e1 in these positions. }
14... Nh7
{ Popular in correspondence chess. Black intends ...Ng5 to trade a few pieces and ease up on the pressure. }
15. Ba4
{ A useful idea to keep in mind, especially once Black's f6-knight has left the centre. By trading the knights on the c-file we remove our bishop from the vulnerable b3-square and make it easier to play d4. }
15... Bxc4 16. Bxc6 Bb5 17. Bd5
{ was played in Cumming-Becker, 2018. Next, we either play for d4, and if Black stops it with ...c5 we maneuver our knight via d2 to c4 where it will have an excellent square. Long term we can still aim for d4, but also playing slowly for the weak squares makes a lot of sense. Bd2, Qc2 and some day Ne3-f5 or Ne3-d5 makes sense, and if the Black bishop moves from b5 we can play Reb1, fighting for the b-file. }
*

