27. Bc5 { Again putting Black under pressure. } 27... Ra8
{ looks very natural, but turns out to be a big mistake! } 28. Rc1 Bxa5 29. Ra1
{ utilizes Black's weak back rank, and after } 29... Bc3 30. Rxa6
{ we are breaking through. While Black tries to get out with the king we will pick up the c7-pawn. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "11. Martinez Variation 6.d3 - 8...O-O 9.a4 b4"]
[Black "10...Rb8 11.Nbd2 Be6 12.Nc4 Qc8 #10"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ The mainline.   Black can also delay ...Be7 in favor of  5...b5  6.Bb3  d6  attempting to move order us into  7.d3  , when Black can hunt down our bishop with ...Na5.  But we play  7.c3  instead, and after  7...Be7  we can transpose back into out repertoire with  8.d3  . }
6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... b5
{ The main move. Black defends against the threat of Bxc6 followed by Nxe5. Importantly ...b5 is played before we had time for c3, meaning the c2-square is not yet available for our bishop. The downside of the move ...b5 is that it creates a target for us to attack later on, with a4. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ The most flexible move, getting ready to meet  8.a4  with  8...Bd7  . } 8. c3
{ Highly controversial! The mainline for some years has instead been a setup with  8.a3  and 9.Nc3  , which leads to a different style of play. While that is interesting, I believe sticking to the setup with a pawn on c3, as we do in almost all of our lines, makes for a nice coherent repertoire. Move orders are very important, though. }
8... O-O { The main move. Black simply continues with the development. } 9. a4
{ The move a4 is a vital part of our strategy - the move ...b5 has created a hook for us to try to attack, and we are well placed for fighting for the light squares on the queenside. However, as so often in the Ruy Lopez, timing is of utmost importance. The reason we have included c3 for us and O-O for Black will be shown on the next move.   A logical question to ask is what happens after  9.Bc2  , as it also steps out of ...Na5. Without the inclusion of a4 and Bd7 Black has a much more harmonious position, as the bishop on d7 is somewhat clumsily placed. The more concrete differences are: Black finds it easier to push ...d5 as the queen controls the centre.  Black can make use of the Breyer maneuver ...Nb8-d7, which frequently is a harmonious regrouping. }
9... b4
{ Always one of the natural reactions we need to take into account when playing a4 in the d3-Spanish. Black removes all tension on the a-file and against the b5-pawn, and does not have to commit the bishop to the slightly inferior b7 or d7 squares, keeping the option of going to e6. It has been played numerous times at the highest level, and was the choice of Sergey Karjakin against me a few months ago. }
10. a5
{ Our standard response. The pawn on a5 is almost universally useful after Black has played ...b4, as we separate the a6 and b4-pawns from each other. A downside of placing our pawn on a5 is that it can be attacked via the maneuver Rb8-b5, but here we are ready to protect the pawn with a quick Nbd2-c4. Next up we should develop our pieces with Nbd2-c4, Re1, h3, and then try a well-timed d4-push. }
10... Rb8 { Almost universally played, as the b4-pawn needs support. } 11. Nbd2
{ Important! We don't want to trade the light-squared bishops yet, and now we are in time to meet ...Be6 with Nc4. }
11... Be6 12. Nc4
{ Just in time! Trading the bishops on e6 is not in itself a bad idea, but it would take the game into a completely different territory, much more often arising from the Anti-Marshall and outside the scope of our repertoire. }
12... Qc8
{ A very tricky move to face. By not trading pawns on c3 Black keeps the option of pushing ...b3 if we have to retreat our bishop. The downside is the same as with  12...h6  , that we can push d4 before Black had time to trade on c3, but Qc8 is then a more active move than h6. }
13. d4
{ Our problem is that after a natural move like  13.Re1  Black plays  13...Qb7  , threatening bxc3 followed by Qxb3, and after  14.Bc2  the possibility  14...b3  is very annoying. After  15.Bb1  we are running the risk of our b1-bishop never getting into the game. }
13... bxc3
{ Allowing us to play d5, but Black has a very advanced idea in mind. } 14. d5
Bh3
{ An amazing idea. Black is sacrificing a piece, making use of the fact that many of our pieces are loose. The bishop on b3, the pawn on b2 and the pawn on e4 are all tactical liabilities. }
15. gxh3 Qxh3 16. dxc6
{ The most practical choice, leading the game into an ending where we force Black to make some very good moves to hold. }
16... Qg4+ { The only correct move order! } 17. Kh1 Rxb3 18. Ne3
{ Preventing a perpetual. } 18... c2 { The only move! } 19. Nxg4
{ Now follows a forced sequence. } 19... cxd1=Q 20. Nxf6+ Bxf6 21. Rxd1 Rxf3
22. Be3
{ Cutting the Black rook out of the queenside. Now we are intending to quickly push on the queenside before the f3-rook gets back into the game. }
22... Be7 { The only move to give the rook a retreating square. } 23. Kg2 Rf6
24. b4
{ We are a pawn down, but Black's pawn majority on the queenside is very far from meaning anything at all whereas our a-pawn could very quickly promote. }
24... d5
{ This is the only move for Black to survive! Black desperately needs to get the f6-rook and e7-bishop into the game. }
25. Rxd5 Bxb4 26. Rb1 { Continuing to ask some tricky questions. } 26... Bc3
27. Bc5 { Again putting Black under pressure. } 27... Rc8 { The only move! }
28. Rb6 { A fancy try, again making use of the weak back rank. } 28... h6
{ If  28...cxb6?  then  29.c7  wins immediately due to the back rank problems. }
29. Rxa6
{ Winning back the pawn, but the position is unfortunately still within the drawing margin, as Black will be able to liquidate into a drawn rook ending with a well-timed ...Bd4. Still, it's not yet a dead draw, and more importantly I think very, very few players would be able to get all the way here in a practical game. That being said, if you believe it to be too drawish, then there is also the chaos starting with 16.Bc2. }
*

