15. gxh3 Qxh3 16. Bc2
{ This is the more ambitious choice, but the positions are very, very messy. }
16... Nb4 17. Ng5 { Stepping out of the threat with tempo. } 17... Qh4 18. f4
{ The only move, to have the rook protecting the knight once it retreats to f3. }
18... exf4 19. Nf3 Qh5
{ Black has three pawns for the piece, and the position is very messy. If we manage to get our pieces active we could very quickly get a strong attack ourselves, but with accurate play Black seems to have enough counterplay everywhere. Still, White is definitely not worse and if you prefer slightly more chaotic @@StartBracket@@fun and interesting!@@EndBracket@@ chess then this is certainly an interesting way. }
20. Kh1 Nxc2 21. Qxc2
{ We are not getting mated, but materially Black is kind of OK. } 21... cxb2
{ Not the best for Black as it allows us to untangle our pieces just in time. }
22. Bxb2
{ With the bishop out of the way we can bring the rook into play and in this position our extra piece will likely count for more than the pawns. }
