[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Martinez Variation 6.d3 - 8...O-O 9.a4 Bb7"]
[Black "10.Re1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ The mainline.   Black can also delay ...Be7 in favor of  5...b5  6.Bb3  d6  attempting to move order us into  7.d3  , when Black can hunt down our bishop with ...Na5.  But we play  7.c3  instead, and after  7...Be7  we can transpose back into out repertoire with  8.d3  . }
6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... b5
{ The main move. Black defends against the threat of Bxc6 followed by Nxe5. Importantly ...b5 is played before we had time for c3, meaning the c2-square is not yet available for our bishop. The downside of the move ...b5 is that it creates a target for us to attack later on, with a4. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ The most flexible move, getting ready to meet  8.a4  with  8...Bd7  . } 8. c3
{ Highly controversial! The mainline for some years has instead been a setup with  8.a3  and 9.Nc3  , which leads to a different style of play. While that is interesting, I believe sticking to the setup with a pawn on c3, as we do in almost all of our lines, makes for a nice coherent repertoire. Move orders are very important, though. }
8... O-O { The main move. Black simply continues with the development. } 9. a4
{ The move a4 is a vital part of our strategy - the move ...b5 has created a hook for us to try to attack, and we are well placed for fighting for the light squares on the queenside. However, as so often in the Ruy Lopez, timing is of utmost importance. The reason we have included c3 for us and O-O for Black will be shown on the next move.   A logical question to ask is what happens after  9.Bc2  , as it also steps out of ...Na5. Without the inclusion of a4 and Bd7 Black has a much more harmonious position, as the bishop on d7 is somewhat clumsily placed. The more concrete differences are: Black finds it easier to push ...d5 as the queen controls the centre.  Black can make use of the Breyer maneuver ...Nb8-d7, which frequently is a harmonious regrouping. }
9... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to b7 rather than d7. In a normal Ruy Lopez, such as the Breyer or the Zaitsev, the bishop on b7 would exercise pressure against the pawn on e4. Here our pawn is still on d3, meaning e4 will never really get weak. But the bishop on b7 could become very useful if Black manages to push ...d5 later on, which is also an easier thing to do as the queen controls d5, unlike with the bishop on d7 instead.   The downsides of the bishop on b7 are that b5 is now more vulnerable, both because the bishop does not protect the pawn itself, but also because the b-file is blocked, and that the bishop no longer has the possibility of going to e6 later on, meaning that our own b3-bishop could become quite strong. }
10. Re1
{ This is the other very natural move, and interesting to compare with our mainline. }
10... Na5
{ is by far the most natural and common move for Black, as pushing ...c5 is such a great achievement for Black. }
11. Ba2
{ This is our idea, fighting for the light squares in the centre. Please note that with the bishop on d7 rather than b7 this would have been met by ...bxa4! winning a pawn. }
11... c5 12. Bg5
{ Our positional concept is based on finally getting a good knight on d5 versus the bad bishop on e7 for Black. }
12... h6
{ The only move that has been played in practical play, and the universally recommended reaction Bg5's in this structure. }
13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. axb5
{ Important, as otherwise, Black could block the queenside. 14.Nbd2 b4! would be positionally desirable for Black as our rooks are struggling to find anything useful to do, and Black will be able to safely guard the b4-pawn with ...a5 later on. }
14... axb5 15. Nbd2
{ Our idea is to play Nd2-f1-e3 followed by Bd5 and trade the light-squared bishops, after which our knight will be excellently placed on d5. This plan is basically impossible for Black to prevent, which makes the position quite easy to play for White. However, chess is @@StartBracket@@luckily!@@EndBracket@@ rarely so easy...   15...Qd7  is possible, but  16.Nf1  Black would at some point be forced to play the same maneuver anyway, as the knight on a5 really need to take part in the fight for the d5-square.   15...b4  is much less appealing without the a-pawns on the board, as the pawn is more vulnerable and the a5-knight looser. After  16.Bd5  we have nice pressure on the light squares, and  16...bxc3  17.bxc3  does not solve Black's problems, as the d6-pawn is weak and the dark-squared bishop is still very passive. }
15... Nc6 { Intending to place the knight on e7, covering d5. } 16. Bd5
{ A natural response, having been given the opportunity. } 16... Rxa1
{ Trading a set of rooks, at the same time preventing both Qb3 and the queen maneuver to the kingside. }
17. Qxa1 Qd7 18. Nf1 { Continuing with our strategic plan. } 18... Ra8 19. Qd1
{ Black having the a-file really isn't important at all for us, as the rook lacks good entry points. }
19... Ne7
{ As it's not possible to avoid the trade of light-squared bishops, Black might as well allow it immediately. }
20. Bxb7 Qxb7 21. Ne3
{ A very typical position and something that is in fact very likely to arrive after 10.Re1. We have managed to trade the light-squared bishops, and Black's remaining bishop is still passive, but our main problem is that we have two knights and only one good square @@StartBracket@@d5@@EndBracket@@. If we remove the f3-knight and the e7-knight we would have a clear positional edge, but here it is almost impossible to do. Our main idea, therefore, consists of trying to create something on the kingside, either with Ng4, or if Black prevents it, then h4-h5 or even pushing g4-g5. But Black is very solid, and we are quite far from creating dangerous threats.   It is a playable position and if given a choice I would pick White, but as an opening repertoire I think we should try to be a bit more ambitious. }
*

