15. Bd5
{ A key idea! With Re1 Qd7 included this could be calmly met by ...Nc6, but here Black lacks a tempo. }
15... Qd7 { The most solid move. Black prepares the Na5-c6-e7 maneuver again. }
16. Qe2
{ Connecting the rooks, possibly preparing to double on the a-file, but also awaiting a decision from Black }
16... Bxd5
{ Would again be possible, and slightly smarter than on the previous move. }
17. exd5 Nb7
{ Starting the fight for the a-file. Next Black intends Rfb8 and Qd8 to trade everything on the a-file. }
18. Rfb1 { Preparing Qd1, but also the knight maneuver with Ne1!?. } 18... Rfb8
19. Ne1
{ This is one of many interesting ways to play the position. The knight goes to c2, from where it is covering the b4- and a1-square, but more importantly can continue towards a3 and put pressure on the b5-pawn, which would be especially important if Black trades all rooks on the a-file. Additionally, removing the knight from f3 gives the white queen access to the kingside, and starting play there with something like Ne4 and even g4!? becomes a possibility in the future. }
