{ The most common move in practical play, not caring too much about what we are up to and just continuing with the normal, natural plan. }
11. Ba2 c5 12. Nbd2
{ Compared to 10. Re1 we are a little bit faster, as the rook didn't really do all that much on e1. It might not look that way at first, but it turn out that the tempo gained is really very important! }
12... h6
{ The most logical move, and what Black is doing with Re1 instead of Nbd2 played. }
13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. axb5
{ Important. Having given up the bishop on f6 we should prevent Black from playing ...b4, blocking the queenside. }
14... axb5
{ A critical position for the understanding of our 10.Bg5 move order. We haven't yet wasted a move on Re1, but to make use of the extra tempo requires very precise play. }
15. Bd5
{ A key idea! With Re1 Qd7 included this could be calmly met by ...Nc6, but here Black lacks a tempo. }
15... Qd7 { The most solid move. Black prepares the Na5-c6-e7 maneuver again. }
16. Qe2
{ Connecting the rooks, possibly preparing to double on the a-file, but also awaiting a decision from Black }
16... Nc6
{ The most logical move, but importantly we have already moved our queen away from d1, meaning we can always recapture on a1 with a rook rather than misplacing our queen on there. }
17. h4
{ Again making use of the not yet wasted Re1-tempo, putting pressure on Black's kingside before Black has had time to liquidate with ...Ne7. }
17... h5 18. Ng5 { would already be a serious initiative. } 18... g6 19. Rxa8
{ Wins the a-file as the f8-rook needs to defend f7. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "12. Martinez Variation 6.d3 - 8...O-O 9.a4 Bb7"]
[Black "10.Bg5 Na5 11.Ba2 c5 12.Nbd2 h6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ The mainline.   Black can also delay ...Be7 in favor of  5...b5  6.Bb3  d6  attempting to move order us into  7.d3  , when Black can hunt down our bishop with ...Na5.  But we play  7.c3  instead, and after  7...Be7  we can transpose back into out repertoire with  8.d3  . }
6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... b5
{ The main move. Black defends against the threat of Bxc6 followed by Nxe5. Importantly ...b5 is played before we had time for c3, meaning the c2-square is not yet available for our bishop. The downside of the move ...b5 is that it creates a target for us to attack later on, with a4. }
7. Bb3 d6
{ The most flexible move, getting ready to meet  8.a4  with  8...Bd7  . } 8. c3
{ Highly controversial! The mainline for some years has instead been a setup with  8.a3  and 9.Nc3  , which leads to a different style of play. While that is interesting, I believe sticking to the setup with a pawn on c3, as we do in almost all of our lines, makes for a nice coherent repertoire. Move orders are very important, though. }
8... O-O { The main move. Black simply continues with the development. } 9. a4
{ The move a4 is a vital part of our strategy - the move ...b5 has created a hook for us to try to attack, and we are well placed for fighting for the light squares on the queenside. However, as so often in the Ruy Lopez, timing is of utmost importance. The reason we have included c3 for us and O-O for Black will be shown on the next move.   A logical question to ask is what happens after  9.Bc2  , as it also steps out of ...Na5. Without the inclusion of a4 and Bd7 Black has a much more harmonious position, as the bishop on d7 is somewhat clumsily placed. The more concrete differences are: Black finds it easier to push ...d5 as the queen controls the centre.  Black can make use of the Breyer maneuver ...Nb8-d7, which frequently is a harmonious regrouping. }
9... Bb7
{ Developing the bishop to b7 rather than d7. In a normal Ruy Lopez, such as the Breyer or the Zaitsev, the bishop on b7 would exercise pressure against the pawn on e4. Here our pawn is still on d3, meaning e4 will never really get weak. But the bishop on b7 could become very useful if Black manages to push ...d5 later on, which is also an easier thing to do as the queen controls d5, unlike with the bishop on d7 instead.   The downsides of the bishop on b7 are that b5 is now more vulnerable, both because the bishop does not protect the pawn itself, but also because the b-file is blocked, and that the bishop no longer has the possibility of going to e6 later on, meaning that our own b3-bishop could become quite strong. }
10. Bg5
{ Very rare. Usually, we are not too keen on trading the dark-squared bishop for the knight on f6, but here we are intending to put pressure on Black's b5-pawn and forcing it to b4, after which the light squares will be really weak. The other main reason is that we are getting ready for Black's most natural response, ...Na5 followed by c5, by immediately fighting for the d5-square. }
10... Na5
{ The most common move in practical play, not caring too much about what we are up to and just continuing with the normal, natural plan. }
11. Ba2 c5 12. Nbd2
{ Compared to 10. Re1 we are a little bit faster, as the rook didn't really do all that much on e1. It might not look that way at first, but it turn out that the tempo gained is really very important! }
12... h6
{ The most logical move, and what Black is doing with Re1 instead of Nbd2 played. }
13. Bxf6 Bxf6 14. axb5
{ Important. Having given up the bishop on f6 we should prevent Black from playing ...b4, blocking the queenside. }
14... axb5
{ A critical position for the understanding of our 10.Bg5 move order. We haven't yet wasted a move on Re1, but to make use of the extra tempo requires very precise play. }
15. Bd5
{ A key idea! With Re1 Qd7 included this could be calmly met by ...Nc6, but here Black lacks a tempo. }
15... Qd7 { The most solid move. Black prepares the Na5-c6-e7 maneuver again. }
16. Qe2
{ Connecting the rooks, possibly preparing to double on the a-file, but also awaiting a decision from Black }
16... Nc6
{ The most logical move, but importantly we have already moved our queen away from d1, meaning we can always recapture on a1 with a rook rather than misplacing our queen on there. }
17. h4
{ Again making use of the not yet wasted Re1-tempo, putting pressure on Black's kingside before Black has had time to liquidate with ...Ne7. }
17... h5 18. Ng5 { would already be a serious initiative. } 18... Bxg5 19. hxg5
g6 20. Qf3
{ Again gives a nice initiative. Black has traded off the dark-squared bishop, but had to play ...g6 to hold onto the h5-pawn meaning the f6-square is very weak. Importantly Black also never had time to trade the other bishops with ...Ne7. }
