{ Saving the b-pawn, but weakening the c3-pawn in the meantime. We do keep our extra pawn for the time being, but our passive pieces give Black enough compensation. We should be ready to give up the d5-pawn in order to activate our knight, if given the chance.   Black's most direct continuation is  22...e4  , after which we play  23.Nd4  Qxd5  24.Qa6!?  Due to the weak d6-pawn Black can't liquidate immediately on d4, but the limited material still makes a draw the heavy favorite. If you trust your opponent to find their way all the way up to here, then either you can congratulate them, or try a slower move early on, for instance, 12.Bd5 or even the less ambitious 10.Re1. But we are 10 moves away from anything that has ever been played before, and Black had to show both good understanding and excellent calculating skills, so I hope you will forgive me for not giving an edge in the final position. }
*

