{ In the Ruy Lopez we always have to be extra observant when Black delays ...d6, as the pawn could go to ...d5 in one move. This position is no exception. The lines here are frequently transposing to 7...d6, but there are a few ways in which Black can deviate, which we will have a look at here. }
8. a4
{ Highlighting the drawback of delaying ...d6 - Black does not have ...Bd7 as a possible reply here.  8.c3  d5!  would be fine for Black. }
8... b4 9. a5 d6 10. c3
{ is a direct transposition to 7...d6 8.c3 0-0 9.a4 b4 10.a5. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "13. Martinez Variation 6.d3 - 6...b5 7.Bb3 O-O"]
[Black "8...b4 9.a5 d5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7
{ The mainline.   Black can also delay ...Be7 in favor of  5...b5  6.Bb3  d6  attempting to move order us into  7.d3  , when Black can hunt down our bishop with ...Na5.  But we play  7.c3  instead, and after  7...Be7  we can transpose back into out repertoire with  8.d3  . }
6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... b5
{ The main move. Black defends against the threat of Bxc6 followed by Nxe5. Importantly ...b5 is played before we had time for c3, meaning the c2-square is not yet available for our bishop. The downside of the move ...b5 is that it creates a target for us to attack later on, with a4. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ In the Ruy Lopez we always have to be extra observant when Black delays ...d6, as the pawn could go to ...d5 in one move. This position is no exception. The lines here are frequently transposing to 7...d6, but there are a few ways in which Black can deviate, which we will have a look at here. }
8. a4
{ Highlighting the drawback of delaying ...d6 - Black does not have ...Bd7 as a possible reply here.  8.c3  d5!  would be fine for Black. }
8... b4 9. a5 d5
{ is too ambitious - generally speaking Black only pushes ...d5 once White has committed the pawn to c3, as after exd5 Nxd5 the knight would then have something to attack. }
10. exd5 Nxd5 11. Re1 { Is simply a good version for us. } 11... f6 12. d4
{ in fact, this just wins. Everything is pinned and hanging for Black in the centre. }
*

