{ The main move. Black defends against the threat of Bxc6 followed by Nxe5. Importantly ...b5 is played before we had time for c3, meaning the c2-square is not yet available for our bishop. The downside of the move ...b5 is that it creates a target for us to attack later on, with a4. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ In the Ruy Lopez we always have to be extra observant when Black delays ...d6, as the pawn could go to ...d5 in one move. This position is no exception. The lines here are frequently transposing to 7...d6, but there are a few ways in which Black can deviate, which we will have a look at here. }
8. a4
{ Highlighting the drawback of delaying ...d6 - Black does not have ...Bd7 as a possible reply here.  8.c3  d5!  would be fine for Black. }
8... b4 9. a5 Bc5
{ This is an interesting idea with Nbd2 played instead of a5 for White. Black loses a tempo but puts the bishop much more actively outside the pawn chain before playing ...d6. However, not having played Nbd2 gives us extra options. }
10. Be3
{ Simple and strong. Black either has to get an ugly doubled c-pawn, or open up the f-file for us. }
10... Bxe3 11. fxe3
{ Quite frequently allowing fxe3 is fine for Black, but here they lost time with Be7-c5 and the pawn on b4 is much weaker than usual. }
11... d6 12. Nbd2 Ne7 13. Nh4
{ Is nice. Our b3-bishop is strong, we have possibilities for an exchange sacrifice on f6, and as soon as Black plays ...Ng6 we can jump Nf5. Next up could also be Qe2 and doubling rooks on the f-file. The main problem for Black is the lack of counterplay. }
