9. axb5 axb5 10. Nc3
{ Jumping to d5. The inclusion of a4 and axb5 means that Black no longer has the reply ...Na5 available, and our knight will be quite annoying on d5. }
10... d6 11. Nd5 Nxd5 12. Bxd5 Nb4 13. Bb3 c5
{ Normally getting ...c5 in is a success for Black, but here our control of the d5-square combined with the a-file gives us a slight but pleasant edge. There is only one trick we need to avoid. }
14. Bd2
{ Kicking the knight back, preparing c3. The immediate  14.c3  would allow  14...Nxd3!  15.Qxd3  c4  16.Bxc4  bxc4  17.Qxc4  Be6  which gives Black decent compensation for the pawn due to our weak light squares. }
14... Nc6 15. c3
{ We have a slight, but very pleasant edge. Next, we can place our bishop on d5, then either Qb3, Be3 or entering on the a-file. Meanwhile Black is lacking counterplay. }
