6... b5
{ The main move. Black defends against the threat of Bxc6 followed by Nxe5. Importantly ...b5 is played before we had time for c3, meaning the c2-square is not yet available for our bishop. The downside of the move ...b5 is that it creates a target for us to attack later on, with a4. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ In the Ruy Lopez we always have to be extra observant when Black delays ...d6, as the pawn could go to ...d5 in one move. This position is no exception. The lines here are frequently transposing to 7...d6, but there are a few ways in which Black can deviate, which we will have a look at here. }
8. a4
{ Highlighting the drawback of delaying ...d6 - Black does not have ...Bd7 as a possible reply here.  8.c3  d5!  would be fine for Black. }
8... Bb7 { Still keeping the option of ...d5 in one move. } 9. Nc3
{ Here we slightly change track. After ...Bb7 it's hard for Black to protect the b5-pawn in a comfortable way.  9.c3  d5!  would still give Black counterplay. }
