{ The mainline.   Black can also delay ...Be7 in favor of  5...b5  6.Bb3  d6  attempting to move order us into  7.d3  , when Black can hunt down our bishop with ...Na5.  But we play  7.c3  instead, and after  7...Be7  we can transpose back into out repertoire with  8.d3  . }
6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... b5
{ The main move. Black defends against the threat of Bxc6 followed by Nxe5. Importantly ...b5 is played before we had time for c3, meaning the c2-square is not yet available for our bishop. The downside of the move ...b5 is that it creates a target for us to attack later on, with a4. }
7. Bb3 O-O
{ In the Ruy Lopez we always have to be extra observant when Black delays ...d6, as the pawn could go to ...d5 in one move. This position is no exception. The lines here are frequently transposing to 7...d6, but there are a few ways in which Black can deviate, which we will have a look at here. }
8. a4
{ Highlighting the drawback of delaying ...d6 - Black does not have ...Bd7 as a possible reply here.  8.c3  d5!  would be fine for Black. }
8... Bb7 { Still keeping the option of ...d5 in one move. } 9. Nc3
{ Here we slightly change track. After ...Bb7 it's hard for Black to protect the b5-pawn in a comfortable way.  9.c3  d5!  would still give Black counterplay. }
9... Na5
{ This is interesting. Just like after 9...Nd4 we do not want to allow Nxb3. }
10. Bd5
{ Giving up the light-squared bishop is very rare for the Ruy Lopez! But here we gain a lot of time, and the Black a5-knight will look clumsy. }
10... Nxd5 11. Nxd5 Bd6
{ Keeping control of the b4-square and having the maneuver Nc6-e7 in mind. }
12. Ne3 Re8 { Protecting the e5-pawn so that the bishop can retreat to f8. }
13. Nf5 Bf8 14. Ng5
{ The whole line with 8...Na5 isn't too relevant from a theoretical perspective, but I am still showing it due to what happens next here. With Ng5 we are intending both Qh5 and f4, which would give us a very strong initiative. }
14... h6 { The only reasonable try, trying to kick us back. } 15. Qg4
{ Very strong! It turns out that Black does not have enough pieces to defend their king. The immediate threat is Nxh6+ gxh6 Ne6+. }
15... hxg5 16. Bxg5 f6 17. Nh6+
{ the second very nice move. The knight can't be taken due to Bxf6+ } 17... Kh7
18. Qf5+ { forcing ...g6, to secure the h6-knight. } 18... g6 19. Qh3 Kg7 20.
f4
{ The final key move, bringing the rook into the game. Now Black collapses quickly }
20... fxg5 21. fxg5 Bc5+ 22. Kh1 Rf8 23. Nf7
{ The rest I am showing purely out of aesthetic reasons. } 23... Rxf7 24. Qh6+
Kg8 25. Rxf7 Kxf7 26. Rf1+ Ke7 27. Qg7+ Kd6 28. Rf6+ Qxf6 29. Qxf6#
{ Very cute! } *

