{ A move order that has gone out of fashion. As usual in chess openings, one of the most important things is flexibility. By placing the bishop on b7 Black loses the option of developing it on the c8-h3 diagonal later on. }
7. Nc3
{ Perhaps a slight surprise. The usual rule of thumb against ...Bb7 is that d3 is a good reply, protecting the e4-pawn and restricting the bishop. With 7.Nc3 we can still play d3 later on, but keeping the option of playing d4 in one move if circumstances allow it. }
7... Be7 { The solid and most popular choice. } 8. d3 d6
{ Now Black can no longer play ...d5 in one move, and basically has gotten no no benefit from starting with ...Bb7. }
9. a4 { Attacking b5. } 9... Na5 10. Ba2
{ We very rarely want to allow Nxb3, even if it would win us a pawn on b5. }
10... b4 { The only move that makes any sense. } 11. Ne2 c5 12. Ng3
{ A very similar position with Re1 and 0-0 included has been played quite a bit, and I even had it myself more than once. There White is considered to be a bit better, but our version is better than that. While Re1 is a useful move it is not the most pressing one in the current position, and we can push delay it for a few more moves. }
12... O-O 13. c3
{ This is our main plan. We want to push d4, taking control of the centre. Black's bishop on b7 is a bit misplaced and ours on a2 is a monster. Later on, Nf5 could be a good move, but for the time being we should protect e4 so that d4 is possible. Black does not really have any useful counterplay. }
13... bxc3 14. bxc3 c4
{ would be one of the few possibilities Black has to disturb our setup, but }
15. Re1 cxd3 16. Qxd3
{ is quite a good structure for us. With Black's bishop on e6 the c4-square could become an issue for us, but here we have both that square and the pawn on c3 firmly under control. In fact, it's the d6-pawn that is the weaker of the two. We can increase pressure with Ba3, Nf5 and perhaps bringing the rooks to b1 and d1. Black is certainly in for a tough defense. }
*

