[Black "7...Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bb7
{ A move order that has gone out of fashion. As usual in chess openings, one of the most important things is flexibility. By placing the bishop on b7 Black loses the option of developing it on the c8-h3 diagonal later on. }
7. Nc3
{ Perhaps a slight surprise. The usual rule of thumb against ...Bb7 is that d3 is a good reply, protecting the e4-pawn and restricting the bishop. With 7.Nc3 we can still play d3 later on, but keeping the option of playing d4 in one move if circumstances allow it. }
7... Bd6
{ Sometimes people play this move in similar positions. It looks funny, but the idea is to play O-O, Re8 and Bf8, after which it's possible to push ...d5 in one move. Here however it does not fit too well in with having pushed ...b5 and placed the bishop on b7. }
8. d3 Na5 9. d4
{ Another typical idea. We lose a tempo, but the threat of e5 is very unpleasant for Black }
9... exd4 10. Qxd4 O-O 11. Bg5
{ 11.e5  does not yet win a piece as Black is doing great after  11...Nc6  , but after 11.Bg5 we have a space advantage and many threats. }
