[Black "7...Bc5 8.Nd5 O-O #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O b5 6. Bb3 Bb7
{ A move order that has gone out of fashion. As usual in chess openings, one of the most important things is flexibility. By placing the bishop on b7 Black loses the option of developing it on the c8-h3 diagonal later on. }
7. Nc3
{ Perhaps a slight surprise. The usual rule of thumb against ...Bb7 is that d3 is a good reply, protecting the e4-pawn and restricting the bishop. With 7.Nc3 we can still play d3 later on, but keeping the option of playing d4 in one move if circumstances allow it. }
7... Bc5 { Trying to claim that we no longer have the possibility of c3, d4. }
8. Nd5
{ The point of 7.Nc3. It turns out that we are very likely to get in d4 in after all! }
8... O-O 9. c3
{ Continuing to offer up the e4-pawn. Black has to take, otherwise, we just play d4 with the best Arkhangelsk version ever. }
9... Nxe4 10. Qc2
{ Somewhat unusual, but very important. It surprisingly turns out that the Black king is very weak. }
10... Bxf2+ { does not work. } 11. Rxf2 Nxf2 12. d4
{ Another key move. We open up for the bishop, preparing Bg5 next. Taking the knight on f2 would have given Black time to defend, but now the attack is very strong. }
12... Ng4 { would be the only move saving the knight, but } 13. Bg5 Qc8 14. h3
{ still wins it, without losing any momentum for the attack. The two pieces will easily outpower the rook. }
