{ The mainline, preventing Bg5 and preparing to push d5 later on, but also awaiting White's reaction. In fact, this is even given an exclamation mark by Svidler. }
11. Ng3 d5 { Is possible here as well, but risky. } 12. Bxc6
{ Forces a doubled pawn, which will soon be isolated as well. } 12... bxc6 13.
exd5
{ The point. Structurally Black would very much like to play cxd5, but that would lose the e5-pawn. }
13... Qxd5
{ The position is still not so clear, as the ugly c-pawns are compensated for by the bishop pair. Still, we are somewhat ahead in development and can utilize this by putting pressure on the e5-pawn. }
14. c4 Qd6 15. b3
{ This is a good setup, as the bishop will be well placed on b2. Next up is Bb2, followed by Re3, Qe2 and Re1, after which the pressure on the e5-pawn is very real. Black likely has to defend it with ...f6 later on, but that gives us some juicy squares on f5 and g6 for our knight. }
