6... d6
{ The big alternative to 6...b5. The advantage of delaying ...b5 is that we can't attack the b5-pawn, and the disadvantage is that after a later ...b5 we are able to retreat our bishop to c2 in one go. Generally speaking, 6...d6 is considered slightly less solid than 6...b5 for Black, but on the other hand also gives slightly more winning chances. The play often becomes quite similar to the Breyer or the Zaitsev variations of the normal Ruy Lopez. While 6...b5 is relatively straightforward with move orders and ideas, the lines after 6...d6 are a bit messier and we have to be quite observant not to get tricked. }
7. c3 { Now we will almost always retreat our bishop to c2 in one go. } 7...
O-O 8. Re1
{ The first move order nuance. We want to play both Re1 and Nbd2, but starting with Re1 keeps the option of playing Be3 before Nbd2, which becomes relevant in case Black plays the rare  8...Nd7  . }
8... Re8
{ The mainline. Black keeps flexible with the b-pawn and prepares ...Bf8. The rook will almost universally be useful on e8, as the main Black idea is to push ...d5 later on. }
9. Nbd2
{ Many people start with h3 instead, but we are trying to avoid that for as long as possible. In many lines we are in fact never obliged to do it, meaning we will have won a tempo. }
9... Bf8
{ This was Svidler's recommendation in his excellent Chess24 video series on the line, and it is by far the most common move. As we have the knight on d2 already Black does not have to worry about Bg5, therefore h6 can wait. }
10. Nf1 h6
{ The mainline, preventing Bg5 and preparing to push d5 later on, but also awaiting White's reaction. In fact, this is even given an exclamation mark by Svidler. }
11. Ng3 { Continuing with our plan and still not committing to h3. } 11... b5
{ 11...d5  is possible here as well, but risky.  12.Bxc6  forces a doubled pawn, which will soon be isolated. }
12. Bb3
{ Pay special attention to this position, as it is one of very, very few cases in which we do not retreat all the way to c2. The reason is that Black is perfectly placed to push ...d5, so we need our bishop on b3 to fight against it. }
12... Na5
{ By far the most common move, and the most natural reaction against 12.Bb3  . Black prepares the ...c5-setup. }
13. Bc2 c5 14. d4
{ Again h3 is the more popular move, but again I don't see any clear need for it yet. }
14... exd4 { 14...cxd4  15.cxd4  exd4  16.Nxd4  transposes to the same. } 15.
cxd4 Bg4
{ The most critical move, trying to punish us for not having played h3. } 16.
d5
{ Necessary, as Black was threatening cxd4. The space advantage is now pretty useful for us, and Black has to act quickly to compensate for that. }
16... Nc4
{ The best move. Black avoids ending up with a terrible knight on a5 @@StartBracket@@if we get to play b3@@EndBracket@@ and at the same time threaten Ne5xf3. }
17. h3 { Forcing a declaration of the bishop. } 17... Bxf3
{ The critical move. } 18. gxf3
{ A double-edged and very interesting structure has arisen. We have won the bishop pair and have a space advantage, but our dark squares are a bit weak and our pawn structure is compromised. A very important factor is that our knight is already o g3, as otherwise Black would be able to get an initiative with Nh5. Another thing that helps us is that the black h-pawn is already on h6, which quite seriously weakens the light squares on the kingside. Next, we should first evacuate the long diagonal and then prepare a kingside pawn push.   18.Qxf3  Nxd5  would be unfortunate. }
18... g6 19. Kg2
{ 19.b3  was played in all games so far, for instance by Leko against Bassem Amin in 2015, but I don't think we need to be scared of the c4-knight and therefore shouldn't weaken our dark squares. }
19... Bg7 20. Rb1
{ Evacuating the long diagonal, overprotecting the b2-pawn. Now we are ready to start actions on the kingside, with h4-f5 or f4-f5, or both! Black has many moves so it is very difficult to predict exactly what will happen, but our plan is pretty straightforward and very difficult to stop. }
20... Qa5 { is too greedy } 21. Re2 Qxa2 22. b3 Ne5 23. f4 Ned7 24. Bb2
{ gives us a huge initiative with e5 on the next move. } *

