{ The big alternative to 6...b5. The advantage of delaying ...b5 is that we can't attack the b5-pawn, and the disadvantage is that after a later ...b5 we are able to retreat our bishop to c2 in one go. Generally speaking, 6...d6 is considered slightly less solid than 6...b5 for Black, but on the other hand also gives slightly more winning chances. The play often becomes quite similar to the Breyer or the Zaitsev variations of the normal Ruy Lopez. While 6...b5 is relatively straightforward with move orders and ideas, the lines after 6...d6 are a bit messier and we have to be quite observant not to get tricked. }
7. c3 { Now we will almost always retreat our bishop to c2 in one go. } 7...
O-O 8. Re1
{ The first move order nuance. We want to play both Re1 and Nbd2, but starting with Re1 keeps the option of playing Be3 before Nbd2, which becomes relevant in case Black plays the rare  8...Nd7  . }
8... b5 9. Bc2 Bb7
{ With this move Black is intending to go for a Breyer or Zaitsev setup. The most important thing for us to remember is to never commit the pawn to h3, as that move is no longer needed. }
10. Nbd2 Re8 11. Nf1 { Continuing wiht our usual plan. } 11... Bf8
{ 11...Nb8  is possible also here, but  12.Ng3  is very likely to transpose as Black will need Bf8 anyway at some point. }
12. Ng3 Nb8 { Going for a Breyer setup. } 13. d4
{ With the knight on g3 we are finally ready for this push. Compared to a normal Breyer we have lost one move with the d-pawn, but our bishop got to c2 without having to first stop at b3. That means that the tempi are the same, and if we want to we could play h3 on our next move and a real Breyer would appear on the board. Needless to say, I believe we have more useful moves than h3 in the position, though. }
13... Nbd7 14. Bd2
{ One of many interesting ways to make use of the saved h3-tempo. Black's main plan includes playing the move ... g6 next to activate the f8-bishop, so we are getting ready to meet it with Qc1 and Bh6. }
14... g6 { The most natural move, continuing with the Breyer setup. } 15. Qc1
Bg7 16. Bh6
{ is just depressing for Black, as trading the bishops removes a lot of Black's dynamic potential and weakens the king quite severely. }
