{ The mainline.   Black can also delay ...Be7 in favor of  5...b5  6.Bb3  d6  attempting to move order us into  7.d3  , when Black can hunt down our bishop with ...Na5.  But we play  7.c3  instead, and after  7...Be7  we can transpose back into out repertoire with  8.d3  . }
6. d3
{ Playing d3 instead of Re1 leads to somewhat calmer play, where understanding is more important than concrete knowledge. It is still very much a challenging line, and its status as one of the main tries for White is certainly well-deserved. Additionally, we avoid annoying lines such as the Marshall attack. }
6... d6
{ The big alternative to 6...b5. The advantage of delaying ...b5 is that we can't attack the b5-pawn, and the disadvantage is that after a later ...b5 we are able to retreat our bishop to c2 in one go. Generally speaking, 6...d6 is considered slightly less solid than 6...b5 for Black, but on the other hand also gives slightly more winning chances. The play often becomes quite similar to the Breyer or the Zaitsev variations of the normal Ruy Lopez. While 6...b5 is relatively straightforward with move orders and ideas, the lines after 6...d6 are a bit messier and we have to be quite observant not to get tricked. }
7. c3 { Now we will almost always retreat our bishop to c2 in one go. } 7...
O-O 8. Re1
{ The first move order nuance. We want to play both Re1 and Nbd2, but starting with Re1 keeps the option of playing Be3 before Nbd2, which becomes relevant in case Black plays the rare  8...Nd7  . }
8... b5 9. Bc2 d5
{ When the 6.d3 line started to appear on top level, this was one of the most popular ways for Black to handle it. It is a logical way to play as with our bishop on c2 we can't really put immediate pressure at the Black centre, but bit by bit people realized that the positions arising still contains quite a bit of venom for Black. }
10. Nbd2 { Calmly continuing our development. } 10... d4
{ A very aggressive move. Instead of trying to equalize with dxe4 Black intends to take over the initiative. It has been played quite a bit by especially Levon Aronian, who always tries to fight for the initiative with both colours. But at the same time it is a very risky approach, as Black might take more space than they can control. }
11. h3
{ A modest-looking but quite venomous move. We prevent ...Bg4 and get ready to react to what Black is doing next. Our main idea is to break open the queenside with a4 next. }
11... Nd7
{ Almost everybody plays this. The knight is much more needed on the queenside to protect all the space. }
12. a4 { Fighting for the light squares. } 12... Rb8 13. Nb3
{ Increasing the pressure. } 13... dxc3 14. bxc3 b4 15. Bb2
{ is similar to what we have seen many times before. The pawn on e5 is weaker than the one on d3 and our pieces are more active. }
*

