{ When the 6.d3 line started to appear on top level, this was one of the most popular ways for Black to handle it. It is a logical way to play as with our bishop on c2 we can't really put immediate pressure at the Black centre, but bit by bit people realized that the positions arising still contains quite a bit of venom for Black. }
10. Nbd2 { Calmly continuing our development. } 10... d4
{ A very aggressive move. Instead of trying to equalize with dxe4 Black intends to take over the initiative. It has been played quite a bit by especially Levon Aronian, who always tries to fight for the initiative with both colours. But at the same time it is a very risky approach, as Black might take more space than they can control. }
11. h3
{ A modest-looking but quite venomous move. We prevent ...Bg4 and get ready to react to what Black is doing next. Our main idea is to break open the queenside with a4 next. }
11... Nd7
{ Almost everybody plays this. The knight is much more needed on the queenside to protect all the space. }
12. a4 { Fighting for the light squares. } 12... Rb8 13. Nb3
{ Increasing the pressure. } 13... Nb6 14. axb5 axb5 15. cxd4 exd4
{ This position has been reached a few times in grandmaster practice. White is a bit better with many moves, but the most interesting is }
16. Na5 Nxa5 17. Rxa5
{ Hitting b5 and activating the rook on the a-file. In order not to be depressingly worse Black must play ...Bb4. }
17... Bb4 18. Rxb5 Bxe1 19. Qxe1
{ But this gives us very nice compensation for the exchange. We have a pawn, and Black's d4-pawn is very weak. Our dark-squared bishop will be very strong and we have a nice grip in the centre, especially after following up with b4. }
