7. c3 { Now we will almost always retreat our bishop to c2 in one go. } 7...
O-O 8. Re1
{ The first move order nuance. We want to play both Re1 and Nbd2, but starting with Re1 keeps the option of playing Be3 before Nbd2, which becomes relevant in case Black plays the rare  8...Nd7  . }
8... b5 9. Bc2 d5
{ When the 6.d3 line started to appear on top level, this was one of the most popular ways for Black to handle it. It is a logical way to play as with our bishop on c2 we can't really put immediate pressure at the Black centre, but bit by bit people realized that the positions arising still contains quite a bit of venom for Black. }
10. Nbd2 { Calmly continuing our development. } 10... dxe4
{ The main move. Black is aiming for a symmetrical position. } 11. dxe4 Be6
{ Despite having played ...b5 the bishop is much better on the c8-h3 diagonal, as it would hit into a very well-guarded e4-pawn from b7. }
12. h3
{ In most games White is trying to put pressure on the b5-pawn with  12.a4  followed by Qe2 and Bd3, but Black can defend the passively with Qb7 and Rab8, after which it's hard to make progress on the queenside. Therefore I recommend immediately starting our play on the kingside instead. }
12... Nd7
{ is the other way of preventing Ng5, but it does look a bit too passive. } 13.
Nf1 Nc5 14. Qe2 { avoiding the queen trade. } 14... Bc4 15. Qe3
{ It is very rare for the Ruy Lopez, but in these lines with dxe4 dxe4 the queen is often surprisingly well-placed on e3. We are anyway not intending to develop our c1-bishop anytime soon, and from e3 the queen will both cover the weak d3-square and be able to transfer to the kingside later on. Next, we play Ng3, followed by either Nf5 with pressure on the kingside. }
