[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. 4th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4...b5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Na5
{ The Norwegian Variation. Black is making sure they win our b3-bishop, but forgetting about their development. }
6. Nc3
{ Not the most popular move, but a very interesting one. We are keeping the option of O-O-O in case the centre opens up quickly. }
6... Nxb3 7. axb3 Bb7
{ Another way for Black to play, keeping the d7-pawn flexible. } 8. O-O
{ Committing our king, but more importantly forcing Black to defend the e5-pawn before we play d4. }
8... d6 9. d4 exd4 10. Qxd4
{ gives us central dominance and a lead in development in return for the bishop pair. I would be surprised if Black manages to survive this for long. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. 4th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4...b5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Na5
{ The Norwegian Variation. Black is making sure they win our b3-bishop, but forgetting about their development. }
6. Nc3
{ Not the most popular move, but a very interesting one. We are keeping the option of O-O-O in case the centre opens up quickly. }
6... d6 7. d4
{ Very logical play. We are opening up the position before Black has time to develop their forces. }
7... exd4 8. Qxd4 Bb7 9. Bg5 f6 10. Bxg8 { This avoids ...c5-c4 with tempo. }
10... Rxg8 11. Be3
{ To be followed up with O-O-O, Rhe1 and an attack in the centre. Black's king will not run away. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. 4th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4...b5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 b5 5. Bb3 Na5
{ The Norwegian Variation. Black is making sure they win our b3-bishop, but forgetting about their development. }
6. Nc3
{ Not the most popular move, but a very interesting one. We are keeping the option of O-O-O in case the centre opens up quickly. }
6... d6 7. d4
{ Very logical play. We are opening up the position before Black has time to develop their forces. }
7... exd4 8. Qxd4 Bb7 9. Bg5 Qd7
{ Intending to win a piece by ...c5-c4. Here there are many good moves, for instance,  10.Nd5  , but I would like to show a continuation that emphasizes just how bad the Black position is. }
10. O-O-O { Going for the kill. } 10... c5 11. Qe3 c4 12. Ba4
{ Not necessary, but quite beautiful. The point is simply to give up the bishop for a more valuable pawn than the one on c4. }
12... bxa4 13. Qb6 Nc6 { The only move to keep the knight. } 14. e5
{ Opening up the centre completely. Now we have a lot of different threats, for instance, Rhe1 or Nd5, but also Ne4xd6. Black will not survive for long... }
*

