[White "17. 4th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4...f5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 f5
{ A very provocative way of playing. Black is trying some sort of delayed Jaenisch Gambit, but the inclusion of ...a6 Ba4 generally favours us, as the b5-bishop often ends up being attacked in the normal Jaenisch. }
5. d4 { Not what we want in the Jaenisch, but here it works very well. } 5...
fxe4 6. Nxe5 Nxe5 7. dxe5
{ Normally Black can now play ...c6 hitting the bishop on b5, and once it moves Qa5+ wins the e5-pawn. Here that does not exist, so Black's position is just a ruin. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. 4th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4...f5 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 f5
{ A very provocative way of playing. Black is trying some sort of delayed Jaenisch Gambit, but the inclusion of ...a6 Ba4 generally favours us, as the b5-bishop often ends up being attacked in the normal Jaenisch. }
5. d4 { Not what we want in the Jaenisch, but here it works very well. } 5...
exd4 { The only reasonable move in this version. } 6. e5
{ Temporarily sacrificing a pawn, but here Black struggles greatly with the f5-pawn, making the king very vulnerable. Additionally, our e5-pawn prevents ...Nf6, making it trickier for Black to develop their kingside. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 Bb7
{ This is how Tari played against Duda in Norway Chess 2020. Black is again intending ...Na5 followed by c5-c4. }
8. a4
{ The key move, giving the bishop a square on a2 allowing it to stay on the key a2-g8 diagonal. }
8... Bc5 9. O-O
{ is very bad for Black as the king will never be able to castle. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. 4th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4...f5 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 f5
{ A very provocative way of playing. Black is trying some sort of delayed Jaenisch Gambit, but the inclusion of ...a6 Ba4 generally favours us, as the b5-bishop often ends up being attacked in the normal Jaenisch. }
5. d4 { Not what we want in the Jaenisch, but here it works very well. } 5...
exd4 { The only reasonable move in this version. } 6. e5
{ Temporarily sacrificing a pawn, but here Black struggles greatly with the f5-pawn, making the king very vulnerable. Additionally, our e5-pawn prevents ...Nf6, making it trickier for Black to develop their kingside. }
6... b5 7. Bb3 Bb7
{ This is how Tari played against Duda in Norway Chess 2020. Black is again intending ...Na5 followed by c5-c4. }
8. a4
{ The key move, giving the bishop a square on a2 allowing it to stay on the key a2-g8 diagonal. }
8... Na5 9. Ba2 c5
{ Trying to get some sort of development with ...Qb6, and the possibility of playing ...c4 later on. }
10. O-O Qb6 11. Re1
{ One of many good moves. We are a pawn down, but Black's king is stuck forever in the centre. }
11... Ne7 { Intending to block up the diagonal with Nd5 or Bd5 next. } 12. b4
{ Initiating some very forceful play. First we break the pawn chain so that we can win the d4-pawn. }
12... cxb4 13. e6 { Then we try to open up even more towards the Black king. }
13... d6
{ The only move to attempt to keep at least some of the centre blocked. } 14.
Nxd4
{ We are a pawn down, but that is not felt whatsoever. To me, Black's position looks like someone picked up a handful of pawns and pieces and dropped them randomly on the board. To make progress we can try Be3 to force the black queen away from the b5-pawn, or Bg5 to attack the f5-pawn. Later we'll bring out our b1-knight, perhaps even by c3, opening up further. It looks like a nightmare for me to play as Black. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "17. 4th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4...Bc5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Bc5
{ A line favoured by the israeli grandmaster Tamir Nabaty, and recently picked up by Jorden Van Foreest on his way to win the Tata Steel Masters. As a surprise weapon it worked very well, but objectively speaking it looks rather dodgy. }
5. c3 Nge7
{ The idea. The knight goes to g6 to support the e5-pawn, and avoids the possibility of a Bg5-pin later on. The downside is that it costs an additional move and that the knight isn't contributing to the fight for the centre from g6. }
6. O-O
{ We want to push d4, but by starting with O-O we avoid Black's Bb4+ after the trade of pawns in the centre.   6.d4  exd4  7.cxd4  Bb4+  followed by d5 isn't as clear. }
6... Ng6 7. d4 Ba7 { Black keeps the stronghold on e5. } 8. Bg5
{ A small subtlety, provoking ...f6. } 8... f6 9. Be3 O-O 10. Nbd2
{ Van Foreest's opponent Aryan Tari instead got tempted to push d5-d6, but that is not necessary. By making normal, natural developing moves instead of trying too hard to punish Black we will get a solid edge. }
10... d6 11. Re1 exd4 12. Nxd4 Nxd4 13. cxd4 f5 14. exf5 Bxf5 15. Qb3+
{ is one of the reasons why Kh8 is useful. } *

