[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Deferred Steinitz Defence"]
[Black "5...Bg4 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Deferred Steinitz variation. Black solidifies the e5-pawn and prepares to develop with ...Bd7. In the old days Black often followed up with Bd7, Nf6 and Be7, but modern theory suggests it's a bit too passive. Therefore Black nowadays usually plays in a sharper fashion, either fianchettoing the f8-bishop or going for concrete counterplay. }
5. O-O
{ In my own practice I have almost always played  5.c3  , but nowadays I believe the Siesta Variation,  5...f5  , is surprisingly solid for Black. }
5... Bg4 { Aggressive, but dubious. } 6. h3 h5
{ This is Black's idea. Retreating the bishop to h5 would as usual misplace the bishop and leave us with a comfortable game, but 6... h5 is something completely different. Black intends to play ...Qf6 after which we struggle to defend f3. However, by playing ...Bg4 and ...h5 Black neglects their kingside development, which we should punish by quickly opening the centre. }
7. Bxc6+
{ Giving up the bishop in order to push d4.  7.d4  is a sharper move, which after  7...b5  8.Bb3  Nxd4  9.hxg4  also leads to a significant White edge in the end, but 7.Bxc6+ is less risky and much simpler. }
7... bxc6 8. d4 Qf6
{ has been played 3 times by the Swedish GM Jonny Hector, but his positions haven't been inspiring. }
9. Nbd2
{ Black's problem is that it is very hard to bring more pieces into the attack. }
9... Ne7 10. Re1 { Freeing up the f1-square for the knight. } 10... Ng6 11.
hxg4 hxg4 12. Nh2 Qh4 13. Ndf1
{ is another useful defensive idea to remember. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Deferred Steinitz Defence"]
[Black "5...Bg4 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Deferred Steinitz variation. Black solidifies the e5-pawn and prepares to develop with ...Bd7. In the old days Black often followed up with Bd7, Nf6 and Be7, but modern theory suggests it's a bit too passive. Therefore Black nowadays usually plays in a sharper fashion, either fianchettoing the f8-bishop or going for concrete counterplay. }
5. O-O
{ In my own practice I have almost always played  5.c3  , but nowadays I believe the Siesta Variation,  5...f5  , is surprisingly solid for Black. }
5... Bg4 { Aggressive, but dubious. } 6. h3 h5
{ This is Black's idea. Retreating the bishop to h5 would as usual misplace the bishop and leave us with a comfortable game, but 6... h5 is something completely different. Black intends to play ...Qf6 after which we struggle to defend f3. However, by playing ...Bg4 and ...h5 Black neglects their kingside development, which we should punish by quickly opening the centre. }
7. Bxc6+
{ Giving up the bishop in order to push d4.  7.d4  is a sharper move, which after  7...b5  8.Bb3  Nxd4  9.hxg4  also leads to a significant White edge in the end, but 7.Bxc6+ is less risky and much simpler. }
7... bxc6 8. d4 Qf6
{ has been played 3 times by the Swedish GM Jonny Hector, but his positions haven't been inspiring. }
9. Nbd2
{ Black's problem is that it is very hard to bring more pieces into the attack. }
9... g5 { Hector's try in all his games. } 10. dxe5 dxe5 11. Nc4
{ Again not the only move, but a straightforward one. We threaten both the e5- and g5-pawns, forcing Black to trade on f3. }
11... Bxf3 12. Qxf3 Qxf3 13. gxf3
{ We have a very promising ending. Our doubled pawns on the kingside are very hard to attack, whereas the Black c6-pawn is likely to become a big weakness. Additionally, we are ahead in development and can try to enter on the d-file. }
*

