[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Deferred Steinitz variation. Black solidifies the e5-pawn and prepares to develop with ...Bd7. In the old days Black often followed up with Bd7, Nf6 and Be7, but modern theory suggests it's a bit too passive. Therefore Black nowadays usually plays in a sharper fashion, either fianchettoing the f8-bishop or going for concrete counterplay. }
5. O-O
{ In my own practice I have almost always played  5.c3  , but nowadays I believe the Siesta Variation,  5...f5  , is surprisingly solid for Black. }
5... Bg4 { Aggressive, but dubious. } 6. h3 h5
{ This is Black's idea. Retreating the bishop to h5 would as usual misplace the bishop and leave us with a comfortable game, but 6... h5 is something completely different. Black intends to play ...Qf6 after which we struggle to defend f3. However, by playing ...Bg4 and ...h5 Black neglects their kingside development, which we should punish by quickly opening the centre. }
7. Bxc6+
{ Giving up the bishop in order to push d4.  7.d4  is a sharper move, which after  7...b5  8.Bb3  Nxd4  9.hxg4  also leads to a significant White edge in the end, but 7.Bxc6+ is less risky and much simpler. }
7... bxc6 8. d4 Bxf3
{ Winning a central pawn and stopping our threat of hxg4. } 9. Qxf3 exd4
{ At least getting a pawn for the suffering. Otherwise, Black's position is just very bad without any upsides. }
10. e5
{ Trying to open up as much as possible before Black can develop the kingside. }
10... d5 { Keeping it blocked for the time being. } 11. c3
{ Far from the only move, but I like it. We are ready to sacrifice a pawn for quick development. Again it's all about the Black king being stuck in the centre. }
11... dxc3 12. Nxc3
{ For the pawn we have a huge lead in development. Next, we will develop the bishop, centralize the rooks and then open up something in the centre. A useful maneuver to keep in mind is Ne2-f4 or Ne2-g3, attacking the h-pawn. For instance,  12...Ne7  13.Bg5  Qd7  14.Ne2!?  Qf5  15.Qe3  , followed by either Ng3 or Nd4. I doubt Black is surviving for very long. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Deferred Steinitz Defence"]
[Black "5...Bd7 6.c3 g5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Deferred Steinitz variation. Black solidifies the e5-pawn and prepares to develop with ...Bd7. In the old days Black often followed up with Bd7, Nf6 and Be7, but modern theory suggests it's a bit too passive. Therefore Black nowadays usually plays in a sharper fashion, either fianchettoing the f8-bishop or going for concrete counterplay. }
5. O-O
{ In my own practice I have almost always played  5.c3  , but nowadays I believe the Siesta Variation,  5...f5  , is surprisingly solid for Black. }
5... Bd7 6. c3 g5
{ Very provocative, but played a few times by Mamedyarov. The main reason it looks fundamentally unsound is that we did not yet play h3 as White. Had the pawn been on h3 Black would have had a much easier time opening up the kingside, whereas here it's hard to see how Black is getting an attack. }
7. d4
{ Following the old rule that flank attacks should be met in the centre! } 7...
g4 8. Ne1 { Keeping d4 defended. The knight can later go to c2 or d3. } 8... h5
9. f4
{ The key move. By f4 we activate the f1-rook and put pressure on Black's centre. Normally Black would want to take on f3 to open files towards our king, but here it is clear that the f-file is much more useful than the g-file. }
9... gxf3 10. Nxf3
{ Reactivating the knight, intending Bg5. Black is under heavy pressure in the centre and the king is unlikely to escape.  10.Qxf3  is also good. }
*

