[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Deferred Steinitz variation. Black solidifies the e5-pawn and prepares to develop with ...Bd7. In the old days Black often followed up with Bd7, Nf6 and Be7, but modern theory suggests it's a bit too passive. Therefore Black nowadays usually plays in a sharper fashion, either fianchettoing the f8-bishop or going for concrete counterplay. }
5. O-O
{ In my own practice I have almost always played  5.c3  , but nowadays I believe the Siesta Variation,  5...f5  , is surprisingly solid for Black. }
5... Bd7 6. c3 g5
{ Very provocative, but played a few times by Mamedyarov. The main reason it looks fundamentally unsound is that we did not yet play h3 as White. Had the pawn been on h3 Black would have had a much easier time opening up the kingside, whereas here it's hard to see how Black is getting an attack. }
7. d4
{ Following the old rule that flank attacks should be met in the centre! } 7...
g4 8. Ne1 { Keeping d4 defended. The knight can later go to c2 or d3. } 8... h5
9. f4
{ The key move. By f4 we activate the f1-rook and put pressure on Black's centre. Normally Black would want to take on f3 to open files towards our king, but here it is clear that the f-file is much more useful than the g-file. }
9... exd4 { The best move, trying to keep things blocked. } 10. cxd4 d5 11. Nd3
{ is very strong, again highlighting Black's lack of development. } 11... dxe4
12. Ne5
{ Followed by Nc3xe4. If Black ever defends the e4-pawn with ...f5, the diagonal b3-g8 will be fatally weakened.   If Black tries to defend the e4-pawn with  12...Nf6  then amongst many promising options I like the look of  13.Nc3  Bg7  14.f5  followed by Bg5, with tremendous pressure. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Deferred Steinitz Defence"]
[Black "5...Bd7 6.c3 g5 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Deferred Steinitz variation. Black solidifies the e5-pawn and prepares to develop with ...Bd7. In the old days Black often followed up with Bd7, Nf6 and Be7, but modern theory suggests it's a bit too passive. Therefore Black nowadays usually plays in a sharper fashion, either fianchettoing the f8-bishop or going for concrete counterplay. }
5. O-O
{ In my own practice I have almost always played  5.c3  , but nowadays I believe the Siesta Variation,  5...f5  , is surprisingly solid for Black. }
5... Bd7 6. c3 g5
{ Very provocative, but played a few times by Mamedyarov. The main reason it looks fundamentally unsound is that we did not yet play h3 as White. Had the pawn been on h3 Black would have had a much easier time opening up the kingside, whereas here it's hard to see how Black is getting an attack. }
7. d4
{ Following the old rule that flank attacks should be met in the centre! } 7...
g4 8. Ne1 { Keeping d4 defended. The knight can later go to c2 or d3. } 8... h5
9. f4
{ The key move. By f4 we activate the f1-rook and put pressure on Black's centre. Normally Black would want to take on f3 to open files towards our king, but here it is clear that the f-file is much more useful than the g-file. }
9... exd4 { The best move, trying to keep things blocked. } 10. cxd4 Bg7 11.
Nc2 { Defending d4.  11.Be3  is a good alternative. } 11... Nce7
{ The best move, trying to block with ...d5 next. } 12. Bxd7+
{ Again the simplest.  12.Bb3  d5  13.f5!  is also very, very promising but there is no need. }
12... Qxd7 13. Nc3 d5 14. e5
{ Black has managed to block the centre, but that is far from the end of all problems. We have a nice space advantage, a lead in development and various tempting plans. One of the main problems for Black is that the king lacks a good hiding place, as castling long would allow us to push the a- and b-pawns. We should develop our bishop to a3, and long term try to push f5 with the help of Qd3, or even Nd1-e3. Black lacks counterplay. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "18. Deferred Steinitz Defence"]
[Black "5...Bd7 6.c3 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Deferred Steinitz variation. Black solidifies the e5-pawn and prepares to develop with ...Bd7. In the old days Black often followed up with Bd7, Nf6 and Be7, but modern theory suggests it's a bit too passive. Therefore Black nowadays usually plays in a sharper fashion, either fianchettoing the f8-bishop or going for concrete counterplay. }
5. O-O
{ In my own practice I have almost always played  5.c3  , but nowadays I believe the Siesta Variation,  5...f5  , is surprisingly solid for Black. }
5... Bd7 6. c3 g6
{ Fianchettoing the f8-bishop. This is by far the most serious of Black's options in the Deferred Steinitz. Black is intending some sort of King’s Indian-like setup. If you are a big fan of King’s Indian as White it could make sense to play a quick d5 and trade the light-squared bishops, but I will instead be recommending a system based on keeping the central pawns on d4 and e4, being ready to either block or open the centre depending on the circumstances. }
7. d4 Bg7 8. h3
{ Not strictly necessary at the moment, but as we intend to play h3 and Re1 it does not matter much in which move order it's done. I prefer starting with h3 as we can then sometimes save on Re1. }
8... Nge7
{ Keeps the f-pawn open but in fact ...f5 is often giving more weaknesses than advantages. }
9. dxe5
{ Is a simple reaction against ...Ne7. In the symmetrical structure that arises the knight would be much better on f6 than e7. }
9... Nxe5 10. Nxe5 dxe5 11. Be3
{ is just very pleasant for us. With the knight on f6 Black would have pressure on e4 and the d7-square protected, but here they have to spend another move solving the problem of d7, whereas we are free to develop however we want. }
*

