9. Re1 O-O 10. Bc2
{ Important!  10.Nbd2  looks more natural, but allows  10...exd4  11.cxd4  Nb4!  with some counterplay. }
10... Nh5
{ I believe that this without a doubt is the strongest move for Black. It prevents Nbd2, as the d4-pawn would then be hanging. Long term, the idea is to play ...f5 and start kingside action, for which the knight will be well placed on either h5 or f4. }
11. a4
{ Looks a bit random, but is in fact very smart. In order to understand it, we must predict the future a bit. Black is going to prepare ...f5 with Qe8 and possibly Kh8. That means Be3 is not so attractive, as a Black f-pawn would attack it with ...f4 later on. We also can't play Nbd2 as the d4-pawn would be hanging. Therefore we need to develop our knight via a3, preferably to c4. But the immediate Na3 could be met by ...b5, after which our knight would look stupid. Therefore we start with a4, securing the c4-square! Additionally, it goes well with our long-term plan of gaining space on the queenside and finally, which is surprisingly relevant, the rook can come into play via a3. }
11... Qe8 { Covering the h5-knight in order to play ...f5 next. } 12. Na3
{ 12.a5  with the idea Ba4 also makes sense, but leads to more King’s Indian style of play. }
12... f5 { Clearly the best move - Black can't afford to waste any time. } 13.
Nc4 f4
{ is a better version of the previous ...f4-setup, but still very risky to give up all central control like this. }
14. b4
{ The position is very sharp and we have to be careful, but on the other hand if we manage to stop Black's play we have a clear strategic edge. }
14... g5 { Possible now as the queen protects h5 from e8. } 15. Bb3 Kh8 16. Ra2
{ Is a nice way of coordinating our forces. The point is simply to defend the rook, so that b5 is possible next move. Additionally, the rook could swing to d2 in case the d-file opens. }
16... g4 { Trying to get counterplay as quickly as possible. } 17. hxg4 Bxg4
18. b5 Nd8 19. b6
{ This is our key idea. By getting our pawn to b6 we attack the base of Black's central pawn chain. If the c7-d6-e5-pawn chain falls, the whole Black position crumbles. }
19... Qg6 { This is the best bid for counterplay. } 20. bxc7 Nf7 21. dxe5
{ Stabilizing the situation in the centre. } 21... dxe5 22. Kf1
{ Not at all necessary, but quite instructive. By removing our king from the dangers on the g-file we also remove a lot of Black's counterplay. Next, we can follow up with our own play, for instance, Ba3 and Rd2 and we are never getting mated. We have had to make a few strong moves, but by this point it is fair to say that Black's strategy has not worked out at all. }
