1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6
{ The Deferred Steinitz variation. Black solidifies the e5-pawn and prepares to develop with ...Bd7. In the old days Black often followed up with Bd7, Nf6 and Be7, but modern theory suggests it's a bit too passive. Therefore Black nowadays usually plays in a sharper fashion, either fianchettoing the f8-bishop or going for concrete counterplay. }
5. O-O
{ In my own practice I have almost always played  5.c3  , but nowadays I believe the Siesta Variation,  5...f5  , is surprisingly solid for Black. }
5... Bd7 6. c3 g6
{ Fianchettoing the f8-bishop. This is by far the most serious of Black's options in the Deferred Steinitz. Black is intending some sort of King’s Indian-like setup. If you are a big fan of King’s Indian as White it could make sense to play a quick d5 and trade the light-squared bishops, but I will instead be recommending a system based on keeping the central pawns on d4 and e4, being ready to either block or open the centre depending on the circumstances. }
7. d4 Bg7 8. h3
{ Not strictly necessary at the moment, but as we intend to play h3 and Re1 it does not matter much in which move order it's done. I prefer starting with h3 as we can then sometimes save on Re1. }
8... Nf6 { The best move. The knight is needed to put pressure on our centre. }
9. Re1 O-O 10. Bc2
{ Important!  10.Nbd2  looks more natural, but allows  10...exd4  11.cxd4  Nb4!  with some counterplay. }
10... Nh5
{ I believe that this without a doubt is the strongest move for Black. It prevents Nbd2, as the d4-pawn would then be hanging. Long term, the idea is to play ...f5 and start kingside action, for which the knight will be well placed on either h5 or f4. }
11. a4
{ Looks a bit random, but is in fact very smart. In order to understand it, we must predict the future a bit. Black is going to prepare ...f5 with Qe8 and possibly Kh8. That means Be3 is not so attractive, as a Black f-pawn would attack it with ...f4 later on. We also can't play Nbd2 as the d4-pawn would be hanging. Therefore we need to develop our knight via a3, preferably to c4. But the immediate Na3 could be met by ...b5, after which our knight would look stupid. Therefore we start with a4, securing the c4-square! Additionally, it goes well with our long-term plan of gaining space on the queenside and finally, which is surprisingly relevant, the rook can come into play via a3. }
11... Qe8 { Covering the h5-knight in order to play ...f5 next. } 12. Na3
{ 12.a5  with the idea Ba4 also makes sense, but leads to more King’s Indian style of play. }
12... f5 { Clearly the best move - Black can't afford to waste any time. } 13.
Nc4 fxe4
{ The best move, but it does give up the hope of a King’s Indian style mating attack. }
14. Rxe4
{ Very interesting and unusual. Basically, we are getting ready to sacrifice an exchange in order to control the centre and stop all counterplay.  14.Bxe4  Qf7  15.dxe5  looks smart as the c4-knight is taboo, but  15...Be6!  becomes very messy. }
14... Bf5 15. Bb3
{ A strong intermediate move, not letting Black trade the light-squared bishops. }
15... d5 { The only move. } 16. Rxe5
{ This is our idea. We give up an exchange for a pawn, but Black will struggle to get coordination. }
16... Nxe5 17. Ncxe5
{ A very interesting position. At first glance, it might not look so impressive for us, but when looking a bit deeper it turns out that the position is in fact very unpleasant for Black. The e5-knight is very, very strong, basically making sure that Black can't make use of the rooks in an efficient manner. Next we simply develop our dark-squared bishop and queen, to get a rook to e1. After that we will have all sorts of tricks on the e-file, and in combination with Ng5-possiblities it is quite tricky for Black to handle. Most of our moves come naturally, whereas the position is very difficult for Black to play. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Cozio & Delayed Cozio Defence"]
[Black "3...a6 4.Ba4 b5 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ In this chapter we will have a look at systems in which Black plays ...g6 and Nge7. There are many different move orders for Black to reach that setup, so we have to be a bit careful not to get tricked into something we don't want. Most of Black's different move orders are aimed at limiting White's options, but luckily we are anyway trying to play the same setup whenever possible. }
3... a6 4. Ba4 b5
{ This is one of the lines in which we have to pay special attention. Black plays ...b5 before we had time for c3, meaning our bishop will have to go to b3 instead. }
5. Bb3 g6 6. a4
{ This shows the downside of playing ...b5 too early - we are able to attack the b5-pawn. }
6... Rb8 7. axb5 axb5 8. d4 exd4 9. Nxd4
{ is very good for us - the reason a4 and axb5 was included is that Black now does not have the vital response ...Na5. }
*

