[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ In this chapter we will have a look at systems in which Black plays ...g6 and Nge7. There are many different move orders for Black to reach that setup, so we have to be a bit careful not to get tricked into something we don't want. Most of Black's different move orders are aimed at limiting White's options, but luckily we are anyway trying to play the same setup whenever possible. }
3... a6 4. Ba4 b5
{ This is one of the lines in which we have to pay special attention. Black plays ...b5 before we had time for c3, meaning our bishop will have to go to b3 instead. }
5. Bb3 g6 6. a4
{ This shows the downside of playing ...b5 too early - we are able to attack the b5-pawn. }
6... b4 7. c3 { A rather simple solution.  7.h4!?  is a more aggressive try. }
7... Bg7 8. d4 exd4 9. cxd4 Na5 10. Ba2 { Is a nice diagonal for the bishop. }
10... Ne7 11. O-O O-O 12. Re1
{ We have gotten a pleasant position. Next up developing with Bg5 and Nbd2. Black lacks the usual fast counterplay against the centre due to having been forced to play ...b4 earlier than preferred. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "19. Cozio & Delayed Cozio Defence"]
[Black "3...Nge7 4.Nc3 g6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ In this chapter we will have a look at systems in which Black plays ...g6 and Nge7. There are many different move orders for Black to reach that setup, so we have to be a bit careful not to get tricked into something we don't want. Most of Black's different move orders are aimed at limiting White's options, but luckily we are anyway trying to play the same setup whenever possible. }
3... Nge7
{ This is known as the Cozio Defence, and is the most important deviation from the mainlines. It has also been recommended by both Erwin L'Ami and Simon Williams in their respective Chessable courses.  4.c3  d5  is the point, which is quite OK for Black. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  would not get into our mainlines, as after for example  4...g6  5.c3  a6  6.Ba4  Bg7  7.d4  exd4  8.cxd4  b5  9.Bc2  d5  we have already committed to castling, which is something we want to delay. }
4. Nc3
{ Therefore we have to treat the line independently, and then 4. Nc3 is the best move. The point is to play d4 next, but first force Black to make a decision. }
4... g6
{ Logical, and the recommendation of Simon Williams in his Chessable course. }
5. d4 exd4 6. Nxd4
{ According to L'Ami, this leads to a pleasant edge for White. I can only agree!  6.Nd5  is sharper, but exactly the sort of thing Black hopes for when trying to be provocative with 3...Nge7. }
6... Bg7 7. Be3 O-O 8. Nxc6
{ Is the line given by L'Ami. By taking on c6 already here we make it harder for Black to push ...d5. }
8... Nxc6 9. Qd2
{ Intending O-O-O and h4-h5. With such nice control of the centre we do not have to fear any counterattack by Black. }
*

