1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ In this chapter we will have a look at systems in which Black plays ...g6 and Nge7. There are many different move orders for Black to reach that setup, so we have to be a bit careful not to get tricked into something we don't want. Most of Black's different move orders are aimed at limiting White's options, but luckily we are anyway trying to play the same setup whenever possible. }
3... Nge7
{ This is known as the Cozio Defence, and is the most important deviation from the mainlines. It has also been recommended by both Erwin L'Ami and Simon Williams in their respective Chessable courses.  4.c3  d5  is the point, which is quite OK for Black. @@StartFEN@@r1bqkb1r/ppppnppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R w KQkq - 4 4@@EndFEN@@  4.O-O  would not get into our mainlines, as after for example  4...g6  5.c3  a6  6.Ba4  Bg7  7.d4  exd4  8.cxd4  b5  9.Bc2  d5  we have already committed to castling, which is something we want to delay. }
4. Nc3
{ Therefore we have to treat the line independently, and then 4. Nc3 is the best move. The point is to play d4 next, but first force Black to make a decision. }
4... Ng6 { L'Ami's suggestion. } 5. d4
{ It's possible to play more ambitiously with  5.h4  , but again I prefer to meet provocations with solid, central play. }
5... exd4 6. Nxd4 Bc5
{ does trade an extra set of pieces, but leaves Black very passive. } 7. Be3
Bxd4 8. Bxd4 Qg5
{ was actually tried in Nepomniachtchi-Carlsen, 2020, but isn't great. } 9. g3
Nxd4 10. Qxd4 Ne5 11. Be2 Nc6 12. Qc4
{ Gave Nepomniachtchi a very nice edge in the game. Again, Black has no compensation for the lack of space. }
