[Black "3...g6 4.c3 Bg7 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ In this chapter we will have a look at systems in which Black plays ...g6 and Nge7. There are many different move orders for Black to reach that setup, so we have to be a bit careful not to get tricked into something we don't want. Most of Black's different move orders are aimed at limiting White's options, but luckily we are anyway trying to play the same setup whenever possible. }
3... g6
{ 3...a6  4.Ba4  g6  5.c3  Nge7  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  5.c3  g6  , are alternative move orders simply transposing into the same line. }
4. c3 Bg7
{ This has been the most popular route to the mainline recently, but all of the move orders are likely to transpose. }
5. d4
{ Again it is important that we delay O-O, as we often have more pressing matters to do in the centre. }
5... exd4 6. cxd4 a6
{ Black can't really do without this move in the long run. } 7. Ba4 b5 8. Bc2
{ Always our preferred square when given the option. The bishop protects e4, but most importantly it does not give Black a tempo with ...Na5 later on. With the knight still on c6 Black can't push c5, which often is the key plan. }
8... d5 9. Bg5
{ Rare, but important! We do not have time to castle, and the move  9.e5  , which is quite strong when Black plays Nge7 instead of Bg7, works less well here. Black responds  9...Bg4  10.Be3  f6!  and the bishop protects the f6-square. After  11.exf6  Bxf6  we are not in time to play both Nbd2 and h3, as our d4-pawn is hanging. }
9... Nge7 10. Nc3 { Threatening Nxd5. } 10... h6
{ The best move, saving the d5-pawn without playing the ugly ...f6. } 11. Bxe7
Nxe7 12. e5
{ Compared to previous versions of this pawn structure we have given up the bishop pair. On the one hand that is a concession, but on the other hand, we have gained some time, meaning that Black's counterplay against our centre comes slower. It is especially useful that the knight had to leave c6, meaning d4 is not under attack. Another important point is that Black's b-pawn is already on b5, which makes it much harder for Black to prepare ...c5. }
12... Bg4
{ Probably the best move. Black gives up the bishop pair to achieve ...c5. }
13. h3 Bxf3 14. Qxf3 O-O 15. O-O
{ The most solid choice.  15.O-O-O  is also very interesting, and much more ambitious. }
15... f6 16. Qg3 fxe5 17. dxe5 { Leaves Black with a very weak king. } *

