[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5
{ In this chapter we will have a look at systems in which Black plays ...g6 and Nge7. There are many different move orders for Black to reach that setup, so we have to be a bit careful not to get tricked into something we don't want. Most of Black's different move orders are aimed at limiting White's options, but luckily we are anyway trying to play the same setup whenever possible. }
3... g6
{ 3...a6  4.Ba4  g6  5.c3  Nge7  or @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/1ppp1ppp/p1n5/4p3/B3P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 1 4@@EndFEN@@  4...Nge7  5.c3  g6  , are alternative move orders simply transposing into the same line. }
4. c3 Bg7
{ This has been the most popular route to the mainline recently, but all of the move orders are likely to transpose. }
5. d4
{ Again it is important that we delay O-O, as we often have more pressing matters to do in the centre. }
5... exd4 6. cxd4 a6
{ Black can't really do without this move in the long run. } 7. Ba4 b5 8. Bc2
{ Always our preferred square when given the option. The bishop protects e4, but most importantly it does not give Black a tempo with ...Na5 later on. With the knight still on c6 Black can't push c5, which often is the key plan. }
8... d6
{ The most popular move. Black develops naturally, at the same time preventing us from pushing our d-pawn too far. }
9. d5 Na5 { The most common, and best move. } 10. O-O Nc4
{ was tried once by Mamedyarov, but commits the knight to c4 a bit too early. }
11. Nc3 Ne7 12. Bd3
{ Was what Caruana did, and is a nice way to show why ...Nc4 was too early. }
12... Nb6 13. a4 { Hitting the queenside, forcing further weaknesses. } 13...
b4 14. Ne2
{ White had a very nice edge in Caruana-Mamedyarov, 2018. Next could be Ned4, perhaps followed by Bg5. Black has spent two moves getting the knight to b6, where it is probably a bit worse than on a5. }
