[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ This is a rare guest in top level practice, but still seen from time to time as a surprise weapon. Black is intending ... Nd4 to trade a set of knights. }
4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 Nd5 7. O-O
{ Again not allowing Bb4+. The position is already pretty miserable for Black, having given up the centre and having to move both the bishop and knight twice. }
7... O-O 8. cxd4 Be7 9. Qb3 Nb6 10. d5 { is a complete disaster for Black. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. 3rd Move Alternatives"]
[Black "3...Bc5 4.c3 Nf6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Bc5
{ This is a rare guest in top level practice, but still seen from time to time as a surprise weapon. Black is intending ... Nd4 to trade a set of knights. }
4. c3 Nf6 5. d4 exd4 6. e5 Nd5 7. O-O
{ Again not allowing Bb4+. The position is already pretty miserable for Black, having given up the centre and having to move both the bishop and knight twice. }
7... Be7 { The only reasonable move. } 8. cxd4 d6 9. exd6 Qxd6 10. Re1
{ We have gotten an isolated pawn, but some lead in development. Next up we again want the typical idea Nc3-e4, forcing the queen away and then Bxc6. Black does not have a lousy bishop on b6 this time, but the doubled c-pawns will still be enough for a comfortable edge. }
10... a6
{ 10...Be6  and  10...O-O  would be met in the same way, with a similar conclusion. }
11. Ba4 Be6 12. Nc3 O-O 13. Ne4 Qd8 14. Bxc6 bxc6 15. h3
{ We have a small edge due to the weak c6-pawns. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. 3rd Move Alternatives"]
[Black "3...d6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ This is the real Steinitz defense, but it does not really make much sense as we can grab the centre immediately. }
4. d4
{ We take the opportunity to push in the centre immediately. Without the inclusion of ...a6 Ba4 Black doesn't have the option of ...b5 here, meaning that e5 is very hard to defend. }
4... Bd7 5. Bxc6
{ Looks slightly surprising, but is in fact quite smart. We give the bishop pair, but gain a lot of time in return. }
5... Bxc6 6. Nc3
{ Again the problem for Black is that the e5-pawn can't be defended in a good way. }
6... exd4 { 6...Nf6  7.Qe2  exd4  8.Nxd4  transposes into the same line. } 7.
Nxd4 Nf6 8. Qe2 { Defending e4, but also preparing O-O-O. } 8... Be7 9. Be3
{ Followed by O-O-O gives us a huge attack for free. The reason our attack is so strong is that we have firm control over the centre, making it very hard for Black to transfer their pieces between the kingside and queenside.   Note, the pawn is tactically protected as  9...Nxe4??  loses material to  10.Nxc6  Nxc3  11.Nxd8  Nxe2  12.Nxb7  Rb8  13.Na5  Rxb2  14.Kxe2  and @@StartFEN@@r2qk2r/ppp1bppp/2bp1n2/8/3NP3/2N1B3/PPP1QPPP/R3K2R b KQkq - 4 9@@EndFEN@@  9...Bxe4  is also markedly worse for Black after  10.Nxe4  Nxe4  11.Qb5+  Kf8  12.Qxb7  . }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. 3rd Move Alternatives"]
[Black "3...d6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ This is the real Steinitz defense, but it does not really make much sense as we can grab the centre immediately. }
4. d4
{ We take the opportunity to push in the centre immediately. Without the inclusion of ...a6 Ba4 Black doesn't have the option of ...b5 here, meaning that e5 is very hard to defend. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7
{ This kind of play was fairly popular some 100 years ago, but to the modern eye Black has just given up the centre without getting anything at all in return. }
6. O-O { Calmly developing. } 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Nxd4 8. Bxd7+ Qxd7 9. Qxd4
{ Does not change much. Theoretically the trade of two sets of pieces makes our space advantage less valuable, but it is still there and Black has no way of ever breaking free. Just developing our pieces and grabbing more space should increase our advantage in the long run. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "21. 3rd Move Alternatives"]
[Black "3...d6 #3"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 d6
{ This is the real Steinitz defense, but it does not really make much sense as we can grab the centre immediately. }
4. d4
{ We take the opportunity to push in the centre immediately. Without the inclusion of ...a6 Ba4 Black doesn't have the option of ...b5 here, meaning that e5 is very hard to defend. }
4... exd4 5. Nxd4 Bd7
{ This kind of play was fairly popular some 100 years ago, but to the modern eye Black has just given up the centre without getting anything at all in return. }
6. O-O { Calmly developing. } 6... Nf6 7. Nc3 Be7 8. Nxc6
{ A simple solution. Keeping the tension is also possible and definitely better for White, but I like to clarify our structural advantage immediately. }
8... bxc6 9. Bd3 O-O 10. f4
{ Black has both a passive position and structural problems. Meanwhile, our kingside attack will flow very naturally with moves like Qf3, Be3 and Rae1, perhaps one day followed by the e5-break. }
*

