[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3
{ I am offering this as an alternative to the 6.d3 Martinez Variation. The move 5.d3 can transpose to6.d3 lines, but more often Black tries to deviate.   The main reason for playing 5.d3 is that we reduce the amount of theory, cutting out some very big openings. The most important one is the Open Spanish, but also the Arkhangelsk and the normal lines with ...Be7 plays out quite differently. The downside is that by committing our pawn to d3 before Black has played ...Be7, we give Black additional options with the bishop. One is to put it on c5, another to fianchetto it on g7.   Generally speaking, I would say that the move order with 5.d3 is less ambitious, but also a lot less theory to learn, making it a very practical weapon. An advantage is that the structures arising are often quite similar to what we have seen before, which makes it an attractive alternative if you already studied the main lines as well. }
5... d6 6. c3 g6
{ An interesting attempt. In the g6-lines of the normal Spanish we always wanted to play d4 in one move, which is no longer possible. Therefore we have to go for another slower setup. }
7. O-O Bg7 8. Re1
{ Pay attention to this move order! We are trying to be as flexible as possible. Specifically we are not yet deciding if we want Be3, or the immediate Nbd2. It depends on which plan Black chooses. If Black is intending to push ...f5, then the bishop will be vulnerable on e3, meaning we should prefer the immediate Nbd2. If Black instead aims for central play with ...d5, then Be3 is a useful developing move fighting for the central squares. }
8... O-O 9. h3
{ Continuing the waiting game. We still have no information from Black, so we keep both Nbd2 and Be3 options open. }
9... Bd7
{ Another natural and popular developing move, but without a clear plan. With the bishop on d7 the push ...d5 makes less sense, but it is also harder to make ...f5 work as the f6-knight can't retreat to d7. }
10. Be3 { Makes sense, as ...f5 is not coming anytime soon. } 10... Nh5
{ Is a more challenging but also riskier approach. } 11. d4 Qe8
{ Beware of this! Black threatens a nasty tactic with Nxd4. } 12. Bb3
{ Stepping out of Nxd4 and stopping ...f5 for a move longer. } 12... Kh8 13.
Nbd2
{ The thing to remember now is to take on e5 as soon as Black plays ...f5, so that the e3-bishop does not get trapped. }
13... Rd8 14. Qe2
{ Just waiting for Black to commit to ...f5, meanwhile preparing to bring the rook to d1. }
14... f5 { The only reasonable plan at Black's disposal. } 15. dxe5 Nxe5 16.
Nxe5 dxe5 17. Nf3
{ Is pleasant. Black is not really building up any serious pressure on the kingside and the e-pawn could easily become vulnerable. Meanwhile, we have easy play with Rad1 and pressure on the d- and e-files. }
*

