8... O-O 9. h3
{ Continuing the waiting game. We still have no information from Black, so we keep both Nbd2 and Be3 options open. }
9... h6
{ I believe this is Black's best move. Basically it continues the waiting game initiated by 9.h3, but is also a useful move in itself. }
10. a3
{ Very fancy, counterwaiting! a3 is useful for two reasons: it prepares to play b4, but also after a later d4 exd4 cxd4 the move ...Nb4 is prevented.   If  10.Be3  Black would have played  10...Nd7  , intending ...f5.  10.Nbd2  Re8  11.Nf1  is possible, but then Black pushes  11...b5  12.Bc2  a5  and I am not sure the knight is so great on f1. }
10... b5
{ A natural move, as our a4-reaction will lose a tempo later on.   10...Re8  11.Be3  d5  12.Nbd2  b5  13.Bc2  a5  leads to the same line. }
11. Bc2 a5 { Gaining space. } 12. Be3 d5
{ 12...Re8  13.Nbd2  d5  14.Qc1  is an alternate move order. } 13. Nbd2 Re8
{ Natural play from Black, gaining space and centralizing the pieces. } 14. Qc1
{ An cunning move, hitting  h6  and potentially creating threats on the c-file.  14.b4  is another natural move, but Black is in time for  14...Be6  15.Nb3  Nd7  , covering both the d5-pawn and the c5-square. Still, that would also be a very playable position for White. }
14... Kh7 { The best move, prophylactically protecting h6! } 15. d4
{ The most concrete move, opening up in the centre. } 15... dxe4 16. Nxe4 Bf5
17. Ng3 { Keeping more pieces on the board. } 17... Bxc2 18. Qxc2
{ The position has slowed down a bit. Black has managed to trade a passive bishop for our slightly more active one, but we have gained some space in the centre. Next up we will play Rad1. An interesting long-term plan would be to play h4-h5, creating some tension towards Black's king. }
