[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Alternative: Anderssen Variation - 5.d3, 5...b5"]
[Black "6...Bc5 7.Bg5 h6 8.Bh4 Be7 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This is considered to be one of the main downsides of 5.d3 instead of 6.d3. Normally against the Arkhangelsk we want to push c3 and d4, but here that is no longer a tempting option, as it would lose a very important tempo. The fact that Jan Gustafsson recommends this in his Lifetime Repertoire on 1.e4 e5 is a testimony to how solid it is. }
7. Bg5
{ An interesting concept. We want to play c3 and reach our desired structure, but start with Bg5 in order to stop ...d5.   In recent year the mainline has instead been  7.Nc3  intending a quick Nd5, but Black has solved their issues there and although it can definitely be tried, I find the systems with c3 a little bit trickier for Black to handle. }
7... h6 8. Bh4 Be7
{ Was the choice of Mamedyarov when he faced Aronian in the recent New in Chess Classics. It might look strange to lose a tempo, but it is a very typical idea known from for instance the Italian. The point is that the trade of dark-squared bishops eases up Black's defense so much, that it is worth losing a tempo on it. }
9. a4 Rb8 10. axb5
{ Aronian continued calmer with Nbd2, but I quite like this more direct approach. }
10... axb5 11. Nc3
{ Making use of the fact that we have not yet played c3.  11.Bg3  d6  12.h3!?  is another interesting try, saving the dark-squared bishop. }
11... d6 12. Bxf6
{ Giving up the bishop pair in order to establish a strong knight on d5. }
12... Bxf6 13. Nd5 O-O 14. O-O
{ I believe we are doing quite well here. The position is quite similar to many of the 6.d3 b5 lines, where we also give up the bishop pair to gain more control over the light squares. Next, we can follow up with c3, h3, Qe2 and then long-term either push d4 or enter on the a-file, depending on what Black does. }
