{ An important part of our strategy. Our overarching idea is to execute a well-timed d4 push later on, but by playing a4 first we are forcing Black to make some unpleasant choices. The move ...b4 would weaken the c4-square, but staying put with ...Rb8 gives us a choice between winning the a-file or pushing a5 ourselves at an appropriate moment. }
12... Rb8 13. O-O
{ It might look strange to castle into the 'attack' of the h- and g-pawns, and in some sense it is true. The reason we do it is twofold: the kingside is too small an area for us to make great progress anyway, and castling helps us prepare d4, for instance by allowing Re1. }
13... Na5
{ A typical reaction from Black, preparing ...Nh5.  13...b4  14.h3  would transpose to the mainline. }
14. Ba2
{ An additional benefit of the move a4 - we keep our bishop on the most active diagonal! }
14... Nh5 15. d4
{ The most aggressive, and also most logical choice. We hit in the centre immediately after Black has left with the knights.  15.Kh1  is another tempting move, but I think it gives Black fewer practical problems. }
15... Nxg3 16. fxg3
{ Pay attention to this recapture! In this structure, with Black having already played h6 and g5, taking with the f-pawn is usually a good idea. It opens up the f-file, creating pressure on f7, but also makes our own king much safer once tucked away on h1. }
