{ A typical regrouping to get counterplay. Black prepares ...Qf6 and ...h5-h4. }
14. h3 Qf6 15. Bd5
{ Quite a rare idea for these positions, but looks promising. Another, more typical reaction would be  15.d4!?  exd4  16.cxd4  Bxd4  17.Nxd4  Nxd4  18.Bd5  , followed by Re1 and Rc1 with typical compensation for the pawn in the form of the bishop pair and the weakened Black king. Looks interesting for White, although objectively Black should be OK there. }
15... Rae8 16. axb5 axb5 17. Bxc6
{ A very strange-looking move, but with a clear plan. } 17... Bxc6 18. b4
{ This is it! We intend to play Qc2 followed by c4-c5, simply trapping the b6-bishop. Surprisingly, it looks very hard for Black to stop it! }
