dxe5 { and we take on f6 with check! } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "23. Alternative: Anderssen Variation - 5.d3, 5...b5"]
[Black "6...Bc5 7.Bg5 d6 8.c3 h6 9.Bh4 Bb6 #9"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 b5 6. Bb3 Bc5
{ This is considered to be one of the main downsides of 5.d3 instead of 6.d3. Normally against the Arkhangelsk we want to push c3 and d4, but here that is no longer a tempting option, as it would lose a very important tempo. The fact that Jan Gustafsson recommends this in his Lifetime Repertoire on 1.e4 e5 is a testimony to how solid it is. }
7. Bg5
{ An interesting concept. We want to play c3 and reach our desired structure, but start with Bg5 in order to stop ...d5.   In recent year the mainline has instead been  7.Nc3  intending a quick Nd5, but Black has solved their issues there and although it can definitely be tried, I find the systems with c3 a little bit trickier for Black to handle. }
7... d6 { By far the main move. } 8. c3
{ 8.Nc3 is not as strong here, as the bishop on c5 is much more active than on e7. }
8... h6
{ Overwhelmingly most popular. In such positions, it is almost universally a good idea for Black to include h6 Bh4, as it gives the option of ...g5 later on. }
9. Bh4
{ It might look calm with us having played d3 and c3, but in fact the position is quite sharp. We are trying to prove that the h4-d8 pin is annoying for Black, and if they play ...g5 that the king is weak. Meanwhile, we are likely castling and trying to find a good moment to push d4. }
9... Bb6
{ The most common move, and the recommendation of Jan Gustafsson in his LTR. Black prophylactically retreats the bishop to b6, to dissuade us from pushing d4 which makes it much easier for Black to execute the maneuver Nc6-e7-g6. }
10. a4
{ As explained previously, playing a4 is generally useful for us here. Timing-wise it makes a lot of sense to do it after Black has played ...Bb6, as the b-file is then blocked. }
10... g5 { The best move, and the recommendation of Sethuraman in his LTR. }
11. Bg3 b4
{ Black's most usual response. The queenside is kept close, but we get a nice square on c4 for our knight. }
12. Nbd2 Rb8
{ Again a very useful move that Black will struggle without. Black is keeping everything protected and flexible, and awaits how we are going to fight for the initiative. An additional and quite important point is that Nc4 can now be met by ...Na5, when the b6-bishop is defended. }
13. O-O O-O
{ The position is very complex and strategically sharp. Our main idea still consists of pushing d4, but it does require some preparation and finesse to get it to work. If we are not able, then we are running the risk of our g3-bishop being out of the game, only attacking a solidly defended e5-pawn. But for Black things are also not so easy. The most natural way to play would be ...Ne7-g6, and ...Nh7 both intending to push the h- and g-pawns. However, both these moves move away from the centre and makes it much more likely for us to be able to push d4. }
14. h3
{ A patient move. Black did not intend to play ...g4 immediately, but if we are to push d4 later then ...g4 is an annoying reply. It also asks Black to make a move, which isn't the easiest thing to do either! The immediate  14.Rc1  is also an interesting option in the same spirit. }
14... Ba7
{ Continuing the waiting tactics. ...Ba7 is useful in that it opens up the b-file, making ...Na5 an option on the next move, as b4 is protected. }
15. Rc1
{ A useful move, and prophylaxis against 15...Na5.   The immediate  15.d4  is interesting, as Black loses a tempo with the bishop after  15...bxc3  16.bxc3  exd4  17.cxd4  Nxd4  18.Nxd4  Bxd4  , but although we have compensation after  19.Rb1  followed by Nf3, I don't really believe we are pushing for an edge. }
15... Kg7
{ This is very slow. Likewise,  15...Ne7  would allow  16.d4  with a great position too. }
16. d4 { is very strong } 16... exd4 17. e5
{ gives as a huge initiative, not the least because Black's king has stepped into the e5-g7 pin. }
*

