14... Kg7
{ Sethuraman's suggestion. Black continues the trench war, waiting for us to do something. h8 might look like a more natural square for the king, keeping the g-file open, but the problem then is that the f7-pawn will not be protected. }
15. Bc4
{ Another 'small' move, but this one is a little more difficult to understand at first glance. There are two reasons the bishop is useful on c4: one is that the a6-pawn is under attack, which makes it more difficult to play ...g4 hxg4 Bxg4. The other is that once we manage to play d4 later on, the bishop can come back to e2, helping us with the defense of our king. }
15... Rg8
{ This is a more direct move. Black prepares to play g4 after which the rook will be attacking along the g-file. }
16. d4
{ Time for action! When we open up the centre the rook is doing nothing on g8, and ...Re8 would lose a tempo. }
16... bxc3 17. bxc3 exd4 18. e5 { Opening up even further. } 18... dxe5 19.
Nxe5 Nxe5 20. Bxe5 dxc3 21. Ne4 { wins immediately. } *

