13. Bg5 { is a very nice version of these positions for White. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Alternative: Anderssen Variation - 5.d3, 5...Bc5 "]
[Black "6...d6 7.O-O O-O 8.h3 b5 9.Bc2 Bb6 #4"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5
{ Another of the supposed downsides of the 5.d3 move order, but quite different from 5...b5 6.Bb3 Bc5. By not committing to ...b5 Black does not give us a target for attack, but on the other hand, we are now in time to play c3 and then retreat our bishop to c2 in one go. In fact, the position is very likely to become an Anti-Berlin. It is not exactly the same version as the ones I am offering as ...a6 Ba4 is included, but it still means that if Black plays it, they are less likely to be into the details. After all, if you are a Berlin player, you would normally play 3...Nf6... }
6. c3 { Not giving Black a second chance to force our bishop to b3. } 6... d6
7. O-O O-O 8. h3
{ Now we have reached a position much more frequently seen after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.c3  O-O  6.O-O  d6  7.h3  a6  8.Ba4  . In the Berlin, I advocated the move orderwith 7.Re1 instead of 7.h3, but as explained there it was due to Black playing a quick ...Ne7 intending c6 and d5. With a6 already on the board such a plan is less strong, as Black won't get a tempo on our bishop.   On the other hand, in our Berlin repertoire after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Re1  a6  I advocate  8.Bxc6  , which is no longer possible here. Those two things combined explain why I am here giving 8.h3 rather than 8.Re1. Yes, all these move orders are a bit tricky to keep track of, I know, but I also promise you it will increase your understanding of the positions and of chess in general! }
8... b5 9. Bc2 Bb6
{ This is Fressinet's second recommendation in his Chess24 Repertoire on the Berlin. Black is trying to save on the move ...h6. }
10. a4 { The typical response. } 10... Bd7
{ The most challenging move. Black is not committing the pawn to b4. } 11. Bg5
{ Setting up a positional threat. } 11... h6
{ Allowing us to execute our threat: } 12. axb5 axb5 13. Rxa8 Qxa8 14. Bxf6
gxf6 15. Nbd2 { Leaves Black with a broken kingside. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "24. Alternative: Anderssen Variation - 5.d3, 5...Bc5 "]
[Black "6...d6 7.O-O O-O 8.h3 b5 9.Bc2 Bb6 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5
{ Another of the supposed downsides of the 5.d3 move order, but quite different from 5...b5 6.Bb3 Bc5. By not committing to ...b5 Black does not give us a target for attack, but on the other hand, we are now in time to play c3 and then retreat our bishop to c2 in one go. In fact, the position is very likely to become an Anti-Berlin. It is not exactly the same version as the ones I am offering as ...a6 Ba4 is included, but it still means that if Black plays it, they are less likely to be into the details. After all, if you are a Berlin player, you would normally play 3...Nf6... }
6. c3 { Not giving Black a second chance to force our bishop to b3. } 6... d6
7. O-O O-O 8. h3
{ Now we have reached a position much more frequently seen after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.c3  O-O  6.O-O  d6  7.h3  a6  8.Ba4  . In the Berlin, I advocated the move orderwith 7.Re1 instead of 7.h3, but as explained there it was due to Black playing a quick ...Ne7 intending c6 and d5. With a6 already on the board such a plan is less strong, as Black won't get a tempo on our bishop.   On the other hand, in our Berlin repertoire after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Re1  a6  I advocate  8.Bxc6  , which is no longer possible here. Those two things combined explain why I am here giving 8.h3 rather than 8.Re1. Yes, all these move orders are a bit tricky to keep track of, I know, but I also promise you it will increase your understanding of the positions and of chess in general! }
8... b5 9. Bc2 Bb6
{ This is Fressinet's second recommendation in his Chess24 Repertoire on the Berlin. Black is trying to save on the move ...h6. }
10. a4 { The typical response. } 10... Bd7
{ The most challenging move. Black is not committing the pawn to b4. } 11. Bg5
{ Setting up a positional threat. } 11... Rb8 12. d4
{ A good moment to expand in the centre. We are toying with the idea of d5, after which ...Ne7 would allow us to take on f6. }
12... h6 { Almost universally a good reaction to Bg5. } 13. Bh4 exd4
{ would also stop our d5-idea, but it is always risky to give up the centre. }
14. cxd4 g5 15. axb5 axb5 16. Qd2
{ A typical idea, sacrificing the h4-bishop for a very strong attack. Again, the reason all these lines are so scary for Black is because so many of the pieces are stuck over on the queenside. }
16... gxh4 { The only critical move. We were threatening to take on g5. } 17.
Qxh6 Nh7
{ Absolutely the only way to defend. Black needs to push the f-pawn in order to get more pieces into the defense. }
18. e5 { Threatening mate in one! } 18... f5 19. exf6 Rf7
{ Again the only move that isn't an immediate mate. I have not been able to find a clear win here, but the position is unbelievably scary for Black and I wouldn't expect anyone to be able to defend in a practical game here. I'll give a few illustrative lines of how the game might develop: }
20. Nc3 { Adding more fuel to the fire! } 20... Qxf6 21. Bxh7+
{ is a useful tactic } *

