[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. d3 Bc5
{ Another of the supposed downsides of the 5.d3 move order, but quite different from 5...b5 6.Bb3 Bc5. By not committing to ...b5 Black does not give us a target for attack, but on the other hand, we are now in time to play c3 and then retreat our bishop to c2 in one go. In fact, the position is very likely to become an Anti-Berlin. It is not exactly the same version as the ones I am offering as ...a6 Ba4 is included, but it still means that if Black plays it, they are less likely to be into the details. After all, if you are a Berlin player, you would normally play 3...Nf6... }
6. c3 { Not giving Black a second chance to force our bishop to b3. } 6... d6
7. O-O O-O 8. h3
{ Now we have reached a position much more frequently seen after @@StartFEN@@r1bqkbnr/pppp1ppp/2n5/1B2p3/4P3/5N2/PPPP1PPP/RNBQK2R b KQkq - 3 3@@EndFEN@@  3...Nf6  4.d3  Bc5  5.c3  O-O  6.O-O  d6  7.h3  a6  8.Ba4  . In the Berlin, I advocated the move orderwith 7.Re1 instead of 7.h3, but as explained there it was due to Black playing a quick ...Ne7 intending c6 and d5. With a6 already on the board such a plan is less strong, as Black won't get a tempo on our bishop.   On the other hand, in our Berlin repertoire after @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Re1  a6  I advocate  8.Bxc6  , which is no longer possible here. Those two things combined explain why I am here giving 8.h3 rather than 8.Re1. Yes, all these move orders are a bit tricky to keep track of, I know, but I also promise you it will increase your understanding of the positions and of chess in general! }
8... Ba7
{ The main move, and what has been the most popular in practical play. Black plays as in the Italian, and preemptively withdraws the bishop. }
9. Re1
{ Our idea is fairly simple here - we intend to play Nbd2-f1-g3 and push d4, after which the central space will give us a slight advantage. }
9... Nh5
{ A rare but very interesting move. Black intends ...Qf6 and to plant the knight on f4. }
10. d4 Qf6 11. Nbd2
{ 11.Na3  is a safer way of playing. The point is  11...Nf4  12.Bxc6!  bxc6  13.Nc4  , and due to the pressure on the e5-pawn Black has to retreat with  13...Ng6  , which relieves a lot of the pressure. Still, if possible, we would of course like to keep our precious light-squared bishop! }
11... exd4
{ Gives up the centre too early, which is very dangerous in combination with moves like ...Nh5.   11...Nf4  12.Nf1  is a worse version for Black, as we keep the option of trading on  c6  whenever we want. }
12. Bxc6 dxc3 13. e5 dxe5 14. Ne4 Qxc6 15. Nxe5 cxb2 16. Bxb2
{ gives Black two extra pawns, but our initiative is super strong! } 16... Qh6
17. Ba3 { would for instance already pick up an exchange, as } 17... Re8 18.
Bc1 { surprisingly wins immediately! The point is that after } 18... Qe6 19.
Qxh5 Qxe5 20. Nf6+
{ wins, as the e8-rook is hanging. Cunning, and not easy, but very logical as Black lacks developing the c8-bishop! }
*

