[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. Anti-Berlin 4.d3 4th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4...Bd6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bd6
{ Another weird-looking move. Black anticipates our capture on c6, after which the bishop would be decently placed on d6. If we don't take, the idea is to play ...O-O, ...Re8, and ...Bf8, after which the d5-break can come in one move. }
5. O-O O-O 6. Re1 Re8 7. Bg5
{ This would be very similar to thesubsequent line, but including ...a6 Ba4 is always in Black's favour. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "25. Anti-Berlin 4.d3 4th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "4...Bd6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bd6
{ Another weird-looking move. Black anticipates our capture on c6, after which the bishop would be decently placed on d6. If we don't take, the idea is to play ...O-O, ...Re8, and ...Bf8, after which the d5-break can come in one move. }
5. O-O a6 { Useful to flick in, now that we don't want to take on c6. } 6. Ba4
O-O 7. c3
{ 7.Re1  intending d4 without c3 is also interesting, but 7.c3 goes well with the rest of our repertoire. Now the position is very likely to transpose to the Anti-Berlinwith 6...Re8. }
7... h6 { this is a bit too slow. } 8. Nbd2 b5 9. Bc2 Bc5
{ does not, in fact, stop d4.   9...Be7  10.d4  would give us a fantastic version of the 6.d3 d6 Ruy Lopez, as Black has nothing to show for the tempo loss Bd6-e7. }
10. d4 exd4 11. e5 { followed by Ne4, with an overwhelming advantage. } *

