9... h6 10. Bh4 g5 { The most critical response. } 11. Bg3 Bg4
{ A normal move. The bishop is trying to cover the weaknesses on the kingside, at the same time creating an unpleasant pin on our f3-knight. }
12. Nbd2 Bb6 { Again important prophylaxis from Black. } 13. Nc4 Re8
{ Aimed at our d4, as the e4-pawn comes under pressure. } 14. d4
{ The most direct way. Slower moves are also possible and lead to an interesting strategic battle. }
14... exd4 15. Nxb6 { To be able to recapture with the queen on d4. } 15...
cxb6 16. Qxd4 c5 17. Qd3 d5 18. e5 Ne4 19. Rad1
{ Activates the rook and puts some pressure on the centre. One thing to note is that after }
19... Qd7
{ It does not really lead anywhere to take on d5, so we should rather play something like h3 intending h4. }
20. h3 Bf5 21. Qe3 { With some play against Black's king. } *

