{ Black's most popular move. The move d6 indicates that Black is ready to just develop their pieces and start to play chess. Now there are a lot of possible moves for both sides, but even so, the position is one more about understanding than about specifics. In order to really fight for an edge, though, we should pay attention to some move orders here. }
7. Re1
{ Highly controversial, and pretty rare. The move Re1 in this structure is of course a very logical and normal one, but here specifically it is a little bit rare. In my opinion, it is one of the most ambitious, though. We are protecting e4, making it possible to push d4, but for the time being not committing to h3 or Nbd2, which are the two other natural moves.  After  7.h3  I don't particularly like facing the continuation  7...Ne7!  intending to push c6 and d5. After  8.d4  Bb6  the game usually continues  9.Bd3  d5  10.Nxe5  Nxe4  , and this position is a bit too dry to my taste. }
7... Ne7
{ A very logical move, played in the same style as against 7.h3. Black intends to play c6 and d5 as quickly as possible, and the knight will find an excellent square on g6. }
8. d4 Bb6 9. a4
{ An interesting way of making use of the tempo gained by omitting h3. } 9...
c6 { The most logical move, as c6 is anyway part of Black's plan. } 10. Bf1
{ In these positions it's always a tough choice where to place the bishop. On d3 it overprotects e4 and is generally a bit more active, but also more vulnerable. It runs into d5 exd5 e4 tactics, and sometimes a knight coming to f4. Here I don't think Black is able to push ...d5 in a good way anyway, so I prefer the bishop on f1. }
10... exd4
{ This is very interesting, and a typical way for Black to play in these positions. The point is that after ...d5 Black will get a very good knight on e4. Still, it's always a strategic risk to give up the centre like this, and I like our chances. }
11. cxd4 Bg4 { Creating some unpleasant pins. } 12. Ra3
{ A key resource. The rook will be needed to recapture on f3 without losing the d4-pawn. }
12... d5 { Looks tempting to get the knight to e4. } 13. e5 Ne4 14. Nbd2
{ Intending to trade the knight. } 14... f5 15. exf6 Nxf6 16. h3 Bh5 17. a5
{ Our typical tactical trick, gaining a nice initiative. } 17... Bc7 18. a6 b6
19. g4 Bg6 20. Bg2
{ This is just great for us. Next, we play Ne5 followed by f4, with complete dominance of the centre. }
*

