[White "30. Anti-Berlin 6...d6 7.Re1 7th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "7...h6 #2"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Re1 h6
{ A slow-looking move, but not without ideas. Black is worried about  7...a6  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.Bg5  so plays ...h6 first, with the idea of ...a6 on the next move. }
8. h3
{ Now that Black has wasted a move on ... h6, the lines with ...Ne7 and a quick ...d5-push aren't really possible anymore. Therefore we can allow ourselves the luxury of including h3 before pushing in the centre. }
8... a6 9. Ba4
{ 9.Bxc6  is possible, and it could be argued that we have an improved version of similar positions, but simply retreating the bishop goes well with the rest of our repertoire. }
9... b5 10. Bc2
{ As usual, we are retreating all the way to c2 once given the chance. Now we will play similarly to our 6.d3 b5 lines, with a4 putting pressure on Black's queenside. }
10... Bb6 11. a4
{ Is similar to what we have seen many times before in other chapters. For instance }
11... Rb8 12. Na3 b4 13. Nc4
{ We will see a similar position in the mainline, in which Black did not waste a tempo on ... Bb6. }
