[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30. Anti-Berlin 6...d6 7.Re1 7th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "7...h6 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Re1 h6
{ A slow-looking move, but not without ideas. Black is worried about  7...a6  8.Bxc6  bxc6  9.Bg5  so plays ...h6 first, with the idea of ...a6 on the next move. }
8. h3
{ Now that Black has wasted a move on ... h6, the lines with ...Ne7 and a quick ...d5-push aren't really possible anymore. Therefore we can allow ourselves the luxury of including h3 before pushing in the centre. }
8... a6 9. Ba4
{ 9.Bxc6  is possible, and it could be argued that we have an improved version of similar positions, but simply retreating the bishop goes well with the rest of our repertoire. }
9... b5 10. Bc2
{ As usual, we are retreating all the way to c2 once given the chance. Now we will play similarly to our 6.d3 b5 lines, with a4 putting pressure on Black's queenside. }
10... Re8 { The most flexible move. } 11. a4 Rb8 12. Nbd2
{ Before Black has played ...Bb6 it wouldn't make much sense to play Na3, as the b5-pawn is defended. }
12... b4
{ A smart move order by Black. By waiting for Nbd2 they avoided our d4-push. }
13. a5
{ These kind of positions are more often reached in 6. d3 b5 7.Bb3 d6 8.c3 O-O 9.a4 b4. Black's bishop is a bit more active on c5 than e7, but we can still play in a similar fashion. Next up is Nc4 and Bd2, perhaps followed by Ba4 at some point. Another idea that could come into play at some point is Nh4 followed by Qf3 and Nf5. For instance }
13... Bd7 14. Nc4 Ba7 { Prophylactic against d4. } 15. Bd2
{ Just developing.  15.Be3  is also natural but trades off a few too many pieces. }
15... bxc3 16. bxc3 Ne7 { Would be a typical move, but it does allow } 17. d4
{ With both d4 and e4 solidly protected we are enjoying a nice spatial edge. }
*

