[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30. Anti-Berlin 6...d6 7.Re1 7th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "7...Ng4 #5"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Re1 Ng4
{ Always a critical response in such positions when playing Re1 before h3. Black attacks f2, but more importantly opens up for the f-pawn. }
8. Re2 f5
{ The logical follow-up to the previous move. Now the play gets quite sharp. }
9. exf5 Bxf5
{ is of course the most natural move, but makes it easier for us to push in the centre. }
10. d4 Bb6 11. Bg5 Qe8 12. h3 Qg6
{ A cunning try. Black is setting up a pin on the g-file @@StartBracket@@!@@EndBracket@@. }
13. hxg4
{ 13.Nbd2  h6!  now works for Black, as  14.hxg4  Bxg4  15.Be3  is met by  15...Bxf3  , and our g-pawn is pinned. }
13... Bxg4 14. Qd3
{ This is the downside of having the queen on g6 - we can step out of the pin by tempo, as a queen trade would be winning for us. }
14... Bf5 { The only move to keep the pressure going. } 15. Qc4+ Kh8
{ We can't hold onto the extra piece, but can give it back in return for a positional edge. }
16. Nbd2
{ Black was actually threatening Bxb1 - something that is very easy to miss! }
16... e4 17. Bxc6 bxc6 18. Qxc6 exf3 19. Nxf3
{ We have an extra pawn, but even that we are willing to give back in order to reach stability. }
19... Bg4 20. Bf4
{ A smart move. The bishop will be an excellent defender on g3. } 20... Qf7
{ Winning back the pawn. } 21. Bg3
{ An excellent square for the bishop, covering our weakest pawn on f2. } 21...
Bxf3 22. gxf3 Qxf3 23. Re4
{ This is a long line, but it is due to this last move that I really wanted to add it. Black has been attacking us for the last 10-15 moves, and finally we get a chance to trade queens. But we don't! The reason is that once we have reached stability on the kingside we are simply having the more active position. The b6-bishop is still out of the game, we have control over the only open file and can switch to creating threats on the kingside. Furthermore, the queen on c6 is excellently placed on a light square. }
*

