1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Re1 Ng4
{ Always a critical response in such positions when playing Re1 before h3. Black attacks f2, but more importantly opens up for the f-pawn. }
8. Re2 f5
{ The logical follow-up to the previous move. Now the play gets quite sharp. }
9. exf5 Bxf5
