1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Re1 Ng4
{ Always a critical response in such positions when playing Re1 before h3. Black attacks f2, but more importantly opens up for the f-pawn. }
8. Re2 f5
{ The logical follow-up to the previous move. Now the play gets quite sharp. }
9. exf5 Bxf5
{ is of course the most natural move, but makes it easier for us to push in the centre. }
10. d4 Bb6 11. Bg5 Qc8 { A strange square, but the idea is to avoid the pins. }
12. Nbd2
{ A natural developing move, but it does give up control of the d4-pawn. }
12... h6 { The best move, forcing our bishop away. } 13. Bh4 exd4 14. cxd4
{ Sacrificing a pawn.  14.Bxc6  as in the previous line is also possible, but then Black has got in the useful h6-move for free. }
