[Black "7...Bb6 8.a4 a5 #6"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Re1 Bb6
{ This is one of the best moves for Black. Voluntarily retreating the bishop looks odd, but we have frequently seen the d4-push being very strong due to attacking the c5-bishop. }
8. a4
{ A very direct reaction to 7...Bb6, actually threatening to trap the bishop!  Normally,  8.Nbd2  is a good reaction against ...Bb6, but here it runs into  8...Ng4!  and Black has an improved version of the 7...Ng4 lines, as there we didn't want to commit our knight to d2 so early. The alternative move @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/1bnp1n2/1B2p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h3  stopping any Ng4, gives Black time for  8...Ne7  and after  9.d4  d5!  we are back to the position we are trying to avoid by playing 7.Re1 instead of 7.h3. }
8... a5
{ This is interesting, but as so often the inclusion of a4 a5 favours us. I have said it before, but the two main reasons are: the bishop is more vulnerable on b6 after a Nbd2-c4 and our rook can enter the game via a3. }
9. h3 Ne7 { Black plays as if a4 a5 isn't included. } 10. d4 d5 11. exd5
{ Normally not the way we want to capture, but here it makes a lot of sense. }
11... exd4 12. Bg5 { Forcing Black to choose with what to recapture on d5. }
12... Nfxd5
{ Generally the most solid move, as the pin against the e7-knight is easier to handle. }
13. cxd4
{ 13.Bc4!?  sacrificing a pawn for the initiative is also a tempting alternative. }
13... h6 14. Bh4 c6 { The most solid move. Black reinforces the d5-point. } 15.
Bc4 Qd6 16. Bxe7
{ Giving up the bishop in order to assert dominance on the light squares.  16.Bg3  keeping all pieces on the board is a decent alternative. }
16... Nxe7 17. Nbd2 Bf5
{ The most solid move. Black is ready to give up the bishop pair to ease the pressure. }
18. Qb3 Nd5 19. Ne4 Bxe4 20. Rxe4
{ We have a slight initiative. The opposite coloured bishops favour us, as the d4-pawn securely blocks the dark-squared one, whereas our bishop can attack both d5 and f7. Additionally, we control the only open file. Black is of course solid, but it does look like a pleasant little something for us. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "30. Anti-Berlin 6...d6 7.Re1 7th Move Alternatives"]
[Black "7...Bb6 8.a4 a6 #1"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Re1 Bb6
{ This is one of the best moves for Black. Voluntarily retreating the bishop looks odd, but we have frequently seen the d4-push being very strong due to attacking the c5-bishop. }
8. a4
{ A very direct reaction to 7...Bb6, actually threatening to trap the bishop!  Normally,  8.Nbd2  is a good reaction against ...Bb6, but here it runs into  8...Ng4!  and Black has an improved version of the 7...Ng4 lines, as there we didn't want to commit our knight to d2 so early. The alternative move @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/1bnp1n2/1B2p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQR1K1 w - - 2 8@@EndFEN@@  8.h3  stopping any Ng4, gives Black time for  8...Ne7  and after  9.d4  d5!  we are back to the position we are trying to avoid by playing 7.Re1 instead of 7.h3. }
8... a6 9. Bxc6
{ Now we take, but having included a4 and a6 makes it possible for us to play against the b6-bishop. }
9... bxc6 10. a5
{ Our idea is that Black's bishop is out of play on a7. For the time being it sounds strange as the diagonal a7-g1 looks useful, but the thing is that in order to prevent us from going d4 long term Black will have to ...c5 at some point. And once c5 is played, the bishop is really struggling on a7. }
10... Ba7 11. h3
{ Just calmly completing development, preventing any Ng4 followed by f5 ideas. }
11... Re8 12. Nbd2 Rb8
{ 12...h6  13.Nf1  Rb8  14.Ng3  transposes to the same line. } 13. Nf1 h6 14.
Ng3 { Now we are ready for d4 next. } 14... c5 15. Be3
{ Excellent timing! By use of tactics we can develop in the most harmonious way. }
15... Rxb2 16. Qc1 { A surprising double attack! } 16... Rb7 17. Bxh6 gxh6 18.
Qxh6 { gives us a winning attack! } *

