9... bxc6 10. a5
{ Our idea is that Black's bishop is out of play on a7. For the time being it sounds strange as the diagonal a7-g1 looks useful, but the thing is that in order to prevent us from going d4 long term Black will have to ...c5 at some point. And once c5 is played, the bishop is really struggling on a7. }
10... Ba7 11. h3
{ Just calmly completing development, preventing any Ng4 followed by f5 ideas. }
11... Re8 12. Nbd2 Rb8
{ 12...h6  13.Nf1  Rb8  14.Ng3  transposes to the same line. } 13. Nf1 c5 14.
Ng3 Be6 { Black is not worried about the pin and develops naturally. } 15. Bg5
h6 { The only move. } 16. Bh4 Kh7 17. Nh5 Rg8
{ The only move, as Black needs to be ready on the g-file as soon as we take on f6. The position is now quite sharp and we have many interesting moves. Generally speaking we are trying to make something happen on the kingside while the bishop is stuck on a7. }
18. Bxf6 { 18.Nxf6+  is also tempting. } 18... gxf6 19. Kh2
{ Preventing Bxh3 and preparing Nh4. As Black, I would be really worried. }
19... Rxb2
{ wins a pawn but is too greedy, as the b-pawn doesn't really matter. } 20. Re2
{ We have excellent compensation. One of our knights will land on f5, where it can never be kicked away. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Magnus Carlsen  vs. Aryan Tari, Altibox Norway Chess, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. d3 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. a4
{ As discussed in thetheory section, I prefer to start with  8.c3  . However, in this game, the kind of position will be similar. }
8... Bd7 9. c3 Na5 10. Ba2 { 10.Bc2  is what I propose in the course. } 10...
c5
{ As discussed in the theory section, I believe  10...bxa4  to be fine for Black and the reason for playing 8.c3 first.  11.Nbd2  c5  12.Bb1  12...O-O  13.Bc2  Bb5!  is a very good move for Black, forcing c4 before White can capture on a4. }
11. Bg5
{ Now we are back on track to ideas very familiar from the theory section. }
11... O-O 12. Nbd2 { 12.Na3  is another interesting route for the knight. }
12... Rb8 13. axb5 { Logical after Black's rook left the a-file. } 13... axb5
14. Re1
{ In the theory section we have similar positions but with Black's light-squared bishop on b7 rather than d7. From d7 the bishop is a bit more flexible in that it can go to both e6 or c6, but overall the position is very similar to those we have seen already. }
14... b4
{ This is a slight concession. Tari's idea is to trade the b-pawns, thereby simplifying the position further. But in doing so he both wastes time and gives up the c4-square.   14...h6  15.Bxf6  Bxf6  16.Nf1  would lead to very typical play. }
15. Nc4
{ The simplest solution.   15.Bxf6!?  Was another interesting option. Playing Bxf6 before ...h6 is normally a bit strange, but here it means White can play Bd5 next move.  15...Bxf6  16.Bd5  followed by doubling on the a-file does look very pleasant for White. Compared to the game continuation Black still has some issues with the vulnerable knight on a5 here. }
15... Nxc4 16. Bxc4 bxc3 17. bxc3
{ The position has stabilized further, but White certainly keeps a nagging edge. It is very instructive to see how Carlsen goes on to win from here. }
17... Qc7 18. Qc2
{ Just improving slowly, bringing the e1-rook over to the queenside. } 18...
Bb5
{ Tari continues in the spirit of 14...b4, trading another piece. Here this is an even bigger concession than on move 14 though, as the light-squared bishop is the last defender of the d5-square! }
19. Bxb5 Rxb5 20. Bxf6
{ After the trade of bishops Carlsen makes sure to end up with a good knight vs bad bishop. }
20... Bxf6 21. Nd2 Qc6
{ 21...h5!  was an interesting way of trying to create at least some sort of counterplay on the kingside. The h-pawn is not much, but it does create just a little bit of tension around White's king, making it riskier to bring everything over to the queenside. }
22. Qa4 Rfb8 23. Nc4 Be7 24. g3
{ The most logical way. Carlsen wants to put his king on a light square, and later on the h-pawn can advance.   24.Na3  R5b6  25.Qxc6  Rxc6  26.Nc4  was also very tempting. Without the queen on the board, White can bring the king into the game, perhaps one day even entering via c4. }
24... Qc8 25. Qd1
{ An excellent move! The queen reroutes to the kingside, from where it can both attack the f7-pawn but also support the advance of the kingside pawns. }
25... g6 26. Kg2 Bf8 27. Qf3 Rb3 28. Rec1
{ At first glance this might look passive, but it's a temporary issue. Eventually White will get the knight to d5, after which the c1-rook can get active. }
28... Qe6 29. Ra7 R8b7 30. Rxb7 Rxb7 31. Ra1 { The rook is free again. } 31...
h5
{ 31...Rb3  Was the best chance, trying to get some sort of counterplay.  32.Ne3  Rxc3  33.Nd5  is a very interesting pawn sacrifice, giving White a huge initiative after  33...Rb3  34.Ra8  but at least Black has a pawn for the suffering...  32.Rc1  is also a possible way to play for White. }
32. Ra8 Kg7 33. Ne3
{ Rerouting the knight to the even juicier d5-square. Now Black is doomed to eternal passivity and although it isn't so easy to break down the defense, in a practical game White's advantage is decisive. }
33... Rc7 34. Nd5 Rc8 35. Ra7
{ Of course White should keep all attacking pieces on the board. } 35... Rb8
{ How should White increase the pressure? } 36. h3
{ Very nice. The idea is to play g4-g5 after which Qf6+ will be a winning threat. Black is too passive to put up meaningful resistance. }
36... Rd8 37. g4 hxg4 38. hxg4 Rd7 39. Ra8
{ 39.Rxd7  Qxd7  40.Qf6+  Kg8  41.Qxg6+!  was another nice way to finish the game off, but by this point it doesn't really matter. }
39... f6 40. g5 { The final touch. } 40... f5
{ 40...fxg5  41.Qxf8+  Kh7  42.Qh8 } 41. Qh3
{ Finally, with the help of the g5-pawn, White enters. } 41... Rf7 42. Re8
{ A nice way to finish off the game. } 42... Qxe8 43. Qh6+ Kg8 44. Qxg6+ Kh8
45. Nf6
{ Now Black has nothing better than ...Rxf6, but that doesn't merely give up the rook for the knight is loses the queen on e8, so Tari resigned. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Maxime Vachier Lagrave vs. Andreas Heimann, Bundesliga, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Nxe4 6. d4 b5 7. Bb3 d5 8. dxe5
Be6 9. c3 Bc5 10. Nbd2 O-O 11. Bc2 Nxf2 12. Rxf2 f6 13. Nf1 Bxf2+ 14. Kxf2 fxe5
15. Kg1 Qd6 16. Ng5
{ 16.Be3  is the move I recommend in thetheory section. Before initiating concrete action White should take the time to develop all pieces. }
16... Bf5 17. Bb3
{ Quite risky. White keeps the bishop pair, but neglects development. } 17...
Ne7 18. Ng3 c6
{ Too slow! Black does not realize that time is of vital importance. ...c6 is not aggressive enough, and lets White consolidate.   18...Kh8!  was the best move, stepping out of the b3-g8 pin.  19.Nxf5   19.Qe2  h6  would basically just be a clear tempo up for Black compared to the game.  19...Nxf5  20.Qxd5?  does not work for White, as  20...Qb6+  21.Kh1  Ng3+!  leads to mate in 4! }
19. Qe2 { 19.Be3  was simpler and good. } 19... Kh8 20. Bd2 h6 21. Re1
{ Typical MVL trickery. } 21... e4
{ Stopping the natural Nf3-retreat.   21...hxg5  22.Qxe5  Qxe5  23.Rxe5  Wins the piece back for White, with some edge. }
22. Qh5 Bg6 23. Qh3 Nf5
{ Black is playing active, strong chess and his position is very decent here, but I still like the game as it goes to show how quickly things can go from counterplay to very bad for Black. }
24. Nxf5 Bxf5 25. Qh4 Qe7
{ Probably just missing White's next move.   25...a5!?  Something like this does not allow White's knight to retreat to f3.  26.Nh3  a4  27.Bd1  Bxh3!  28.Qxh3  b4  gives plenty of counterplay with Black. In fact, White has to be very careful here. }
26. Nf3
{ Moving the knight from a vulnerable to a very active position. Suddenly the downsides in Black's position is really felt. The pawn chain, although well defended, is also stuck on the same colour as the f5-bishop which means that White is getting a very nice blockade on the dark squares. }
26... Qxh4 { 26...Qe8  27.Nd4  would be even worse } 27. Nxh4 Bh7 28. g3
{ Making sure that the knight can reroute to g2-e3. } 28... g5
{ 28...b4!  was probably the last chance, trying to get some counterplay.  29.cxb4?!   29.Ng2  keeps control, but Black is at least asking questions.  29...d4  would make Black's pawns mobile. }
29. Ng2 Kg7 30. Be3 { Cementing the control over the dark squares. } 30... Bf5
31. Bc5 Rf7 32. Bd1 { Activating the bishop } 32... Kg6 33. h4
{ The pawn is more active on h5, restricting Black's king and fixing h6 as a weakness. }
33... Bh3 34. h5+ Kh7 35. Ne3 Bd7 36. Ng4 { Black can hardly move at all }
36... Re8 37. Rf1
{ Perhaps slightly surprising, but MVL judges the arising ending to just be won, which seems correct. }
37... Rxf1+ 38. Kxf1 Bxg4 39. Bxg4
{ Here Heimann simply resigned, which is another fact I quite like about the game. It goes to show just how hopeless Black's position can become once the initiative disappears and the pawns get blocked.   39...Rd8  40.Be6  Kg7  41.Bd4+  Kf8  42.Bb6!  Rb8  43.Bc5+  Ke8  44.Ke2  is one illustrative line of how the game could have continued - Black can't move a thing and White wins easily by entering with the king. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black " Niclas Huschenbeth vs. Rene Stern, German Championship, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Be7 6. Re1 b5 7. Bb3 d6 8. c3
O-O 9. h3 Na5 10. Bc2 c5 11. d4 Qc7 12. d5 Bd7 13. b3
{ In the theory section we reach this position a tempo down, but in such a closed position the tempo isn't of critical value and White should still be enjoying a nice edge. }
13... Ne8 14. Nbd2 { 14.Be3  Would be more in the spirit of our setup. } 14...
g6 15. Nf1 { A natural maneuver, bringing everything over to the kingside. }
15... Ng7 16. Bh6 Nb7 17. c4
{ Logical as soon as the knight leaves a5.   17.a4!?  would also be logical, but when trying to open the queenside it makes sense to have the bishop on e3 and the knight still on d2. }
17... b4
{ Black closes the queenside down. In some sense a solid decision, but also giving White completely free hands on the kingside. This game goes to show that completely passive defense from Black rarely works in this type of position. }
18. g4
{ A natural way of starting the kingside play. With so many pieces on that part of the board there is no risk whatsoever of a counterattack. }
18... f6 19. Ng3 Nd8
{ The typical maneuver, getting an additional defender to f7. } 20. Be3 Nf7 21.
Kh2 Kh8 22. Rg1 Rg8 23. Ne1
{ Rerouting the knight to g2 from where it supports the f4-break. } 23... a5
24. a4 Raf8 25. Ng2 Qc8 26. Qd3 { White brings the last piece into the game. }
26... Rd8
{ This goes to show how passive Black's position is - Stern can merely wait while Huschenbeth prepares the f4-advance in the best fashion. }
27. Raf1 Bf8 28. Bc1 Ne8 29. f4 { Finally! } 29... exf4
{ The first trade of the game occurs on move 29 - not a very rare occurrence in these positions. Black gets the e5-square, but White is gaining even more space. }
30. Nxf4 Ne5 31. Qe2 Bg7 32. Nf5
{ A cool way of breaking through!   32.Nd3  Trading off the e5-knight followed by advancing the kingside pawns was a calmer but also promising alternative. }
32... Bf8
{ 32...gxf5  33.gxf5  opens up the g-file, for which Black isn't yet ready.  33...Bf8  34.Rxg8+  Kxg8  35.Rg1+  Bg7  36.Qg2  followed by Ne6 or Nh5 leads to a crushing attack. }
33. Ne3
{ 33.g5!  was the most convincing way of breaking gthrough  33...gxf5  34.exf5  fxg5  35.Ng6+!  hxg6  36.fxg6  leaves White to pieces down, but with a mating attack! }
33... Nc7 34. h4 Bg7 35. Bb2
{ Huschenbeth's idea is to push g5 at some point, but with such dominance, there is no rush whatsoever! Still, being a bit uncertain of what to do he does not manage to find the right idea immediately. }
35... Rdf8 36. Bd1
{ 36.Kh1  Qe8  37.Qh2  followed by g5 next looks like one excellent way of doing it. }
36... Qe8 37. Rg3 Qe7 38. Kg2 Ne8 39. Bc2 Bh6 40. Rh3 Rg7
{ 40...Bxf4  41.Rxf4  h5!  would have given Black good chances due to the unfortunate position of the h3-rook. }
41. Bd1 Kg8 42. Kg1 Rgf7 43. Rg3 Nc7 44. Bc2 Bc8 45. Qg2 Kh8 46. Rf2 Bd7 47.
Qh2 Kg8 48. Kf1
{ Starting on a good maneuver - the king goes to the queenside to hide before White opens up the kingside. }
48... Bc8 49. Ke2 Bd7 50. Kd1 Ne8 51. Kc1 Bc8 52. Kb1 Bd7 53. Ka2 Bc8 54. Rg1
Bd7 55. Qg3 Kh8
{ The king is as safe as the king can be on a2, so Huschenbeth decides it's time for the break. }
56. g5 Bg7 57. Rh1 Kg8 58. Qh2 { 58.Nf5  was absolutely crushing } 58... fxg5
59. hxg5 Bh8 60. Qh4 h5 61. Nf5
{ Finally it comes, and after ...h5 it's even stronger than before. } 61...
gxf5 62. Qxh5 Rh7 63. Ng6 { A beautiful way of clinching the game. } 63... Nxg6
64. Qxg6+ Rg7 65. exf5
{ Here Stern had enough.   65...Rxg6  66.Rxh8+  Kf7  67.fxg6 } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Jonas Buhl Bjerre vs. Bjorn Moller Ochsner, Danish Championship, 2020"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 d6 5. c3 Bd7 6. d4 g6 7. O-O Bg7 8. h3 Nf6
9. Re1 O-O 10. Bc2 Nh5 11. a4
{ As mentioned in the theory section this is an excellent move, both taking space and preparing Na3-c4. }
11... Qc8
{ Hinting at some Bxh3 sacrifices, but they rarely work so it's a bit of wasted move. }
12. Na3 Kh8 13. Nc4
{ The knight is excellently placed here, putting pressure on the e5-pawn. }
13... b5
{ Natural to remove the knight, but every pawn move on the side where one is weaker is always a risky business. Here Black makes it much easier for White to open up the queenside. }
14. Ne3 exd4
{ Trying to get at least a square on b4 for the knight, but the whole setup with Qc8, Nh5 and Nb4 does not make a harmonic impression. }
15. cxd4 Nb4 16. axb5
{ 16.Bb1  bxa4  is Ochsner's point, although even this would give White excellent compensation. }
16... Bxb5 17. Ra3
{ Another advantage of the move a4 - the rook can enter the game via a3!   17.Bb1  was also very tempting. }
17... Nxc2 18. Qxc2
{ White has given up the bishop pair, but due to the very badly placed Black pieces the position is very, very good for White. }
18... Qb7 19. Rc3 Rac8 20. Bd2
{ 20.Ng4  immediately, intending Bh6 was more convincing. } 20... Nf6 21. Ng4
{ 21.d5  was another good and more positional way. } 21... Nxg4 22. hxg4 c5 23.
dxc5 dxc5
{ 23...Bxc3  24.Bxc3+  Kg8  25.cxd6  is just winning for White - the dark squares are too weak. }
24. e5 Bd7 25. Rc4 Be6 26. Rf4 Rfd8 27. Bc3
{ This setup is very solid. The c3-bishop protects both b2 and e5, and can never be touched. Next White can reroute the knight towards e4 while Black can't really do anything. }
27... h6 28. Nd2 g5
{ Creates some weaknesses, but the knight can't be allowed to e4. } 29. Rf5
{ 29.Rfe4  intending Nc4-e3-f5 also makes sense. } 29... Qd7
{ 29...Bxf5  30.gxf5  gives White a winning initiative. } 30. Re3 Re8 31. Rh3
Bxf5
{ Finally Black crumbles under the pressure.   31...Kg8  would still give reasonable counter-chances. }
32. gxf5 Qd5 33. e6
{ Opening up everything around Black's king. The game is decided. } 33... f6
34. Bxf6 { A 'small combination' winning another two pawns. } 34... Bxf6 35.
Rxh6+ Kg8 { 35...Kg7  36.Rg6+  does not help. } 36. Rxf6 Rf8 37. Rg6+ Kh8 38.
Qc3+
{ 38...Qd4  is forced to avoid immediate mate, but after  39.Qh3+  Qh4  40.Rh6+  the queen is lost and mate will not be far off anyway. }
*

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black " Emil Sutovsky vs. Alexander Onischuk, 2010"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 a6 4. Ba4 Nf6 5. O-O Bc5 6. c3 O-O 7. d4 Ba7 8. Bg5
{ 8.Re1  d6  9.h3  is my recommendation in the theory section, but as we play Bg5 in many of these positions later anyway it makes sense to have a look at a game where White plays it immediately. }
8... h6 9. Bh4 exd4 { 9...g5  10.Nxg5  hxg5  11.Bxg5  gives a huge attack. }
10. cxd4 d6 11. Bxc6 bxc6 12. Nbd2 g5
{ Too risky, as White can now sacrifice.   12...Re8  Has subsequently taken over completely and does lead to very complicated positions. }
13. Nxg5 hxg5 14. Bxg5
{ The main reason this sacrifice is so dangerous is that the a7-bishop is so far from the kingside. This means that White does have quite a bit of time, bringing additional attackers into the game. }
14... Re8
{ 14...Bxd4  was later tried by Bartel. It is a better try, but still very scary.  15.Nf3  Bxb2  16.Rb1  Qd7  17.Rxb2  Nxe4  18.Bh6  White went on to win in Sutovsky-Bartel, 2015. }
15. Qa4 { Not so much attacking c6, but preparing Rae1 and e5. } 15... Rb8 16.
Rae1
{ 16.e5  dxe5  17.Ne4  Nxe4  18.Bxd8  Rxd8  gives Black 3 pieces for the queen. The weak king still gives White an edge, but it's more double-edged than what Sutovsky does in the game. }
16... Re6
{ 16...c5  was the last try. It looks like a blunder as  17.Bxf6  wins a piece due to e8 hanging, but in fact after  17...Bd7!  18.Bxd8  Bxa4  19.Bxc7  Rxb2  Black is only one pawn down in the ending, with some drawing chances. }
17. e5 { The breakthrough. Now the attack is unstoppable! } 17... dxe5 18. dxe5
Rxb2 19. Bxf6 Qd4 20. Qa3
{ White is a pawn up and has a winning attack. The game has been a disaster for Black. }
20... Rxf6 21. exf6 Rxd2 22. Re8+ Kh7 23. Rh8+
{ A nice way of finishing Black off.   23.Rxc8??  Qxf2+!  would be a chock!  24.Rxf2  Rd1 }
23... Kg6 { 23...Kxh8  24.Qf8+  Kh7  25.Qg7 } 24. Qg3+ Kxf6 25. Rxc8
{ Now that f2 is defended it's safe to take. } 25... Rd3 26. Qg8 *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Nikola Djukic vs. Dragisa Blagojevic, 2019"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 g6 4. c3 a6 5. Ba4 Bg7 6. d4 b5 7. Bc2 exd4 8. cxd4
d6 9. h3
{ 9.d5  immediately forcing Black to choose direction for the knight is my recommendation in the theory section. }
9... Nge7
{ 9...Nf6  is a more active square and has been more popular in practice. } 10.
Nc3 O-O 11. O-O Bb7 12. Be3
{ The start of an interesting idea.  12.Re1  would be the normal way of playing. }
12... Na5
{ Very often Black's counterplay is connected to this move, as it both prepares ...Nc4 but more importantly the ...c5-push. }
13. Qc1
{ This is Djukic's idea. Trading the dark-squared bishops makes a lot of sense as Black's king will be quite weak. }
13... Qd7
{ Too slow.   13...f5  something like this, although looking dangerous, must probably be tried as Black desperately needs counterplay. }
14. Bh6 b4 15. Bxg7 Kxg7
{ By simple means White has obtained a serious positional advantage. } 16. Ba4
{ A smart intermediate move.   16.Ne2  would also be better for White } 16...
Qd8 17. d5 { A cute little tactic. } 17... c6 { 17...bxc3  18.Qxc3+ } 18. dxc6
Naxc6 19. Ne2
{ This is a structure often achieved in this line. The d6-pawn is somewhat weak, but that is normally compensated for by the strong g7-bishop. Here, apart from not having the strong bishop, Black also suffers from a weak king, making White's strategic edge considerable. }
19... Qa5 20. Bxc6 { Trading pieces to achieve stability. } 20... Nxc6 21. Ng3
Ne5 22. Nd4 Qd8 23. Rd1 Kh8 24. Qh6 Rg8 25. Qd2
{ 25.Rac1  was also natural and good. } 25... a5
{ 25...Qb6  would not have lost anything immediately, but the position after  26.Qf4  does not exactly inspire confidence for Black }
26. Nb5 { The d6-pawn can't be defended. Black is collapsing. } 26... Qb6 27.
Nxd6 Rgd8 28. Qf4 Rxd6 29. Qxe5+ Rf6 30. Rd2
{ White has an extra pawn and has kept all other strategic advantages. } 30...
Kg8 31. Rad1 Re6 32. Qg5 Rae8 33. Rd8 f6 34. Rxe8+ Rxe8 35. Qf4 Rf8 36. Rd6 Qc7
37. Qd2 Rf7 38. h4
{ A classy way of finishing the game. With the pawn coming to h5 Black can't defend. }
38... Qe7 39. Rd8+ Kg7 40. h5
{ Threatening h5 mate, while ...g5 loses the queen. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Wang Hao vs. Erwin L'Ami, Isle of Man Open, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d5 7. exd5 Qxd5 8.
Bc4 Qd8 9. Nbd2 h6
{ As explained in the theory section, not the most accurate move, as it isn't yet clear if ...h6 is needed. }
10. b4 Bd6 11. Re1 Re8 12. Bb2
{ 12.h3  and  12.a4  are reasonable alternatives. } 12... Bf5 13. Ne4
{ A typical decision that makes extra sense after ...Bf5 as the bishop will have to move again after the trade. }
13... Nxe4 14. dxe4 Be6 15. Nd2
{ A typical idea. As we have a space advantage on the queenside it is there we are trying to play. For that, the knight will be more useful than if it stays on the kingside. }
15... Bf8 16. Qe2 Qd7 17. Bxe6
{ Trading the bishops in order to free up the c4-square for the knight. } 17...
Qxe6 18. Nc4
{ It might not look like a lot and the engine indeed gives equality, but in pratical play these positions are fairly unpleasant for Black to play. White's bishop and knight are a bit better than Black's counterparts, and the extra space on the queenside is an asset. }
18... Rad8 19. Ne3 Rd7 20. Qc4
{ 20.Red1  fighting for the d-file was also possible, although it risks trading off too many rooks. }
20... Qxc4
{ 20...Qg6!?  Perhaps keeping the queens like this makes sense for Black, as White can't activate the king in the same way as in the game. }
21. Nxc4 f6 22. Red1 Red8 23. Rxd7 Rxd7 24. Kf1
{ The king is well placed on e2. After that, the bishop should reroute to e3 followed by pushing the queenside pawns. }
24... Kf7 25. Ke2 Ke6 26. a4 { Grabbing more space. } 26... Nd8
{ Finally rerouting the knight, but it does look a bit too passive. However, it's very hard for Black to suggest anything active to do here. }
27. Bc1 { The bishop is much more active on e3 than b2. } 27... Nf7 28. Be3 b6
29. a5 Nd6
{ It's natural to trade the last set of knights, but it does allow White's rook to enter. Perhaps just waiting would have been better. }
30. axb6 axb6
{ 30...cxb6!?  would not allow the rook to enter  31.Nxd6  Bxd6  32.Ra4  intending to push c4-c5 some day keeps a slight initiative. }
31. Nxd6 Bxd6 32. Ra8
{ The rook still can't threaten anything special, but it's clear that it gets more unpleasant bit by bit. }
32... Be7 33. Rc8 Bd8 34. g4 { Fixing Black's pawns on dark squares. } 34...
Rd6 35. Ra8 { 35.c4  would already have been strong } 35... Kd7 36. c4
{ Further increasing the pressure. By pushing c5 Wang Hao makes sure that the king can enter the queenside. }
36... Re6 37. Kd3 Re8 38. Ra7 { preempting ...Be7, keeping the rooks. } 38...
Ke6 39. c5 bxc5 40. bxc5 { 40.b5!?  also very tempting. } 40... Rh8 41. Ra8 Kd7
42. Kc4 c6 { Desperation, but the pressure was already very serious. } 43. Ra7+
Bc7 44. Bd2 { The key point. } 44... Kc8
{ 44...Rc8  45.Ba5  Kd8  46.Bb6!  is the problem. Black can't ever take on b6, so White can simply invade with Kb4-a5-a6 next. }
45. Ba5 { Now it's just over. } 45... Bb8 { 45...Bxa5  46.Ra8+ } 46. Rxg7 h5
47. h3 hxg4 48. hxg4 Rh2 49. Rf7 Rxf2 50. g5
{ And there is no stopping the g-pawn. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Vladimir Susedenko vs. Volodymyr Galytskyi, 2016"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. Re1 a6 8. Bxc6
bxc6 9. Bg5 h6 10. Bh4 Rb8
{ In the theory section I focused on  10...g5  and  10...Bb6  , but including ...Rb8 and b3 is very similar and leads to the same kind of play. }
11. b3 g5
{ It is very hard for Black to get by without this move in the long run. } 12.
Bg3 Bg4 13. Nbd2
{ We have discussed this structure a fair bit. White is intending to push d4, whereas Black is hoping that the bishop pair will play a key role. It seems to me that White's position is considerably easier to play, as I always prefer a safe king! }
13... Re8 14. Qc2 { A good move, stepping out of the pin and preparing d4. }
14... Nh5 15. d4 Bb6 16. Qd3
{ Keeping the tension.   16.dxe5  was another option  16...Nxg3  17.hxg3  dxe5  18.Nc4  Qf6  leads to a more stable pawn structure which generally favours the knights. Still, Black is quite active and the position wouldn't be so clear. }
16... Nxg3
{ Generally releasing the tension like this is a concession for Black, and this position is no exception.   16...Qf6  Also keeping the tension was an interesting alternative.  17.Rad1  Probably this makes the most sense, with a complicated strategic battle.   17.dxe5  dxe5  18.Qxa6  Bxf3!  gives some play for the pawn }
17. hxg3 a5 18. Nc4
{ Now White is pleasantly better. Not having traded on e5 means that the queen is very safe on d3. }
18... Qf6 19. Rad1 Be6 20. Qe2 { 20.Re2  is another small improving move }
20... g4
{ Black acts, but it is very risky to give the knight a stable square on h4. }
21. Nh4 h5 22. Qd3
{ Back again! But with ...g4 Nh4 included, White's strategic advantage has increased and Black finds it very difficult to break free. }
22... a4 23. Nxb6 { Not necessary, but an interesting change of structure. }
23... Rxb6 24. d5 cxd5 25. exd5 Bd7 26. b4
{ In different circumstances this would perhaps not be so bad for Black, but having pushed ...g4 really hurts here. White's knight is very strong on h4 and both pushing c4-c5 @@StartBracket@@after protecting the b4-pawn@@EndBracket@@ or even f3 and getting a kingside attack is promising for White. }
26... c6 { Attempting to break free, but does not really help. } 27. Qe3 Rb7
28. Rd2 { Calm and collected. } 28... Rc8
{ 28...cxd5  29.Rxd5  Bc6  30.Ra5!  is very good for White as well - the rook is really active on the 5th rank! }
29. dxc6 Bxc6 30. a3 { Protecting b4, so that c4 can come next. } 30... Rbc7
31. Qb6 { 31.c4  would also be strategically winning for White. } 31... Rb7 32.
Qa6 Rbc7 33. c4
{ Black has no counterplay whatsoever and both d6 and a4 are very weak. Strategically White is just winning. }
33... Bb7 34. Qb6 Rd7 35. c5 Rc6 36. Qa7 Qe6 37. Qxa4 dxc5 38. Rxd7 Qxd7 39.
Rxe5 Rd6 40. b5
{ One final thing to note here is just how safe the White king is on h2, due to the knight on h4. This means that the likelihood of a counterattack ever succeeding is very low. }
40... Rd5 41. Qf4 Rxe5 42. Qxe5 Qd5 43. Qxd5 Bxd5 44. Nf5 Kf8 45. b6
{ White's passed pawns are unstoppable. } *

[Event "?"]
[Site "?"]
[Date "????.??.??"]
[Round "?"]
[White "Model Games"]
[Black "Laurent Fressinet vs. Vladimir Kramnik, 43rd Olympiad, 2018"]
[Result "*"]

1. e4 e5 2. Nf3 Nc6 3. Bb5 Nf6 4. d3 Bc5 5. c3 O-O 6. O-O d6 7. h3 Ne7
{ As explained in thetheory section, this move is the main reason why I prefer to start with @@StartFEN@@r1bq1rk1/ppp2ppp/2np1n2/1Bb1p3/4P3/2PP1N2/PP3PPP/RNBQ1RK1 w - - 0 7@@EndFEN@@  7.Re1  instead. Still, the position arising in the game is very similar to what we might get, and the fight is very instructive. }
8. d4 Bb6 9. Re1 Ng6
{ 9...d5  is the reason why I don't like this so much for White.  10.Nxe5  Nxe4  tends to get a bit too dry for my taste. }
10. Nbd2 exd4
{ A typical reaction, that we have also seen in the theory section. Black gives up the centre but gets very active pieces. }
11. cxd4 d5 12. e5 Nh5 13. a4
{ An idea we are very familiar with from the theory section. The pawn can often continue to a5, and the idea of activating the rook via a3 is very useful. }
13... c6 14. Bf1 f6
{ 14...a5  looks like a natural way of stopping a5, but White has a very interesting idea:  15.b4!  axb4  16.Nb3  The point is that Black will struggle to defend the b4-pawn after Bd2 next. Once White wins the pawn back, then the dark squares on the queenside will be firmly in White's hands. Additionally, the bishop would kick blacks rook out of f8, which makes the ...f6-counterplay much less strong. }
15. b4 { Continuing with the plan. } 15... fxe5 16. a5 Bc7 17. dxe5
{ Slightly unusual, but the idea is to put the d2-knight on d4.   17.Nxe5  is another very natural way of recapturing that looks very comfortable for White after  17...Nhf4  18.Ndf3  Again, Ra3-e3 is an important idea next. }
17... Nhf4 18. Ra3 { 18.Nb3  Immediately also looks very harmonious } 18... Bf5
19. Bb2
{ Perhaps a tad unnecessary. The bishop is also well placed on c1, pressuring the f4-knight.   19.Nb3  intending Nd4 gives White a very nice edge. }
19... Qd7 20. Rae3 Rae8 21. Kh2
{ Overprotecting h3, but also wasting a move and stepping into the c7-bishop's diagonal.   Most probably Fressinet was worried about  21.Nb3!  Bxh3  , but it turns out that  22.e6!  is super strong. The point is  22...Bxe6  23.Nc5  23...Qf7  24.Qd4!!  and it turns out that Black is simply overloaded and can't keep both e6 and g7 protected -  24...Bc8?!  25.Rxe8  Rxe8  26.Rxe8+  Qxe8  27.Qxg7  .   21.Nb3  b6  22.Nbd4  is a much better version of the game for White. }
21... Kh8 22. Nb3 b6
{ White is perhaps still very slightly for choice, but the inclusion of the not very useful Kh2 for the very useful Kh8 is certainly in Black's favour. }
23. Qd2 Ne6 24. axb6 axb6 25. Rc1 Rd8
{ 25...Be4  26.Rxe4  would be unfortunate for Black! } 26. Nbd4
{ Initiating forcing play, but it turns out that Black is fine in the end. }
26... Nxd4 27. Qxd4 Be4 28. Rxe4
{ Basically forced, as Black otherwise would take over the initiative. } 28...
dxe4 29. Qxe4
{ For the exchange White has a pawn and is likely to win the one on c6 as well, but Black's pieces are very active and liquidating towards something drawish is the most likely scenario. }
29... c5
{ 29...Qf5  30.Qxf5  Rxf5  31.Rxc6  Bxe5+  is also drawish  32.Nxe5  Nxe5  33.Bxe5  Rxe5  34.Rxb6=  . }
30. bxc5 bxc5 31. Rxc5 Bb6 32. Rc6
{ Probably missing Black's next move.   32.Rc2  Rf4!  33.Qe2  does give White some small chances, but with Black being so active it's hard to believe White is seriously pushing for the win. }
32... Qb7
{ Very smart, pinning the rook.   32...Bxf2  33.Rxg6!  was White's idea.  33...hxg6  34.e6  looks very scary for Black, although the computer still manages to hold on with Black. }
33. Rc4 Qxe4 34. Rxe4 Bxf2
{ Black is now material up, but the very limited material left on the board makes the position an easy draw. }
35. Ba3 Rf5 36. Bd6 h5 37. Bd3 h4 38. Rg4 Bg3+ 39. Kg1 Nxe5 40. Bxe5 Rxd3 41.
Bxg3 hxg3 42. Rxg3 Kg8 43. Kh2 *

